<seg id="b.ACT.2.30" type="verse">Ande þerfore whanne he was a prophete, ande wiste wele þat God þurghe trewe oþe hade sworne vnto hym, þat of þo frute þat oute of hym schulde kome, schulde sitte vpon his sege;
<seg id="b.ACT.23.10" type="verse">Ande whanne grete discencyone was amonges hem, þo tribune dredde hym þat Poule schulde be alle todriuen amonge hem; ande he bade knyghtes to goo ande take hym fro myddes of hem, ande forto lede hym into þo castels .
<seg id="b.ACT.23.11" type="verse">Ande in þo nyghte efter Criste stode bi hym, ande saide, Be stedfaste, for as þow haueste wytnessed of me in Ierusalem, so bihoues þe to wytnes at Rome.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.12" type="verse">Ande whanne daye was comen, summe of þo Iewes gadured hem togider, ande made a vowe amonge hem, sayande, þat þei schulde noþer ete nor drinke vnto þei hade slayne Poule.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.13" type="verse">Ande þei wore mo þanne fourety men þat made þis coniuracyone ande þis oþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.14" type="verse">Þise men ȝode to þo princes of prestes ande þo eldars, ande sayde, We han made a vowe, þat we schal nouþer ete nor drinke to we haue slayne Poule.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.15" type="verse">Þerfore make ȝhe knowne vnto þo tribune wiþ þo cownsel, þat he bringe hym forþe vnto vs as we schulde knowe more certaynly of hym: ande we, or he come to vs, ben redy forto slee hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.16" type="verse">Þis harde a childe þat was Poule sister sone; he come into þo castels ande tolde Poule of þis.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.17" type="verse">Ande Poule called vnto hym one of þe centuryons, ande saide, Lede þis childe to þo tribune, for he haues sumwhat to telle vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.18" type="verse">Ande he toke hym, ande ledde hym to þo tribune, ande saide, Poule þat es bownden preyde me to bringe þis childe vnto þe, for he haues to speke wiþ þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.19" type="verse">Ande þo tribune toke þo hande of þo childe, ande wente wiþ hym biside, ande saide vnto hym, What haues þow to telle vnto me?
<seg id="b.ACT.23.1" type="verse">Ande Poule, lokande vnto þo cownseile, saide, Ȝhe men, breþer, I in alle gode conscience hafe lifed bifore God vnto þis daye.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.31" type="verse">seande ande for-spekande of þo resurreccione of Criste, for noþer was he forlefte in helle, ne neþer his flesche sawe corrupcione (þat es, was neuer filed).
<seg id="b.ACT.23.20" type="verse">Ande he saide, Þo Iewes han accorded to preye þe, þat þow bringe forþe tomorne Poule into þo conseyl, as if þei wolde wyte more wyterly of hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.21" type="verse">Bot trowe hem noghte: for moo þanne fourty men lyne in wayte for hym, þo whiche han made a vowe, nouþer to ete nor drinke to þei haue slayne hym: ande now ben þei redy, ande abiden þi biheste ande þi wille.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.22" type="verse">Ande þo tribune lete þis childe go, ande bade hym þat he schulde telle vnto none þat he hade made þis knowne vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.23" type="verse">Ande he called two centurions, ande saide to hem, Makes redy two hundreth knyghtes forto go vnto Cesarye, ande seuenty horse-men, ande spere-men two hundreth, fro
<seg id="b.ACT.23.24" type="verse">þo þridde houre of þo nyghte; ande make redy ȝour bestes, þat ȝhe may sette Poule on one ande lede saufe vnto Felix
<seg id="b.ACT.23.25" type="verse">þo mayer , ande wrote a letter in þis maner of wordes:
<seg id="b.ACT.23.26" type="verse">Claudius Lysias to gode Felix gretes wele (or, ȝernes hele).
<seg id="b.ACT.23.27" type="verse">Þis man þat was taken of þe Iewes , ande in poynte to be slayne of hem, I , in þo mene tyme comande, toke hym fro þer hende , for I knewe þat he was a Romayn.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.28" type="verse">Ande for I wolde knowe þo cause þat þei keste agayne hym, I ledde hym into þer counseyle.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.29" type="verse">And I fonde þat he was accused of þo questions of þer lawe: bot I fonde hym no þinge worþi þo deþe nor þat bere cryme vnto þo Iewes.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.2" type="verse">Ande Ananye, þo prince of prestes, bad to þoo þat stode nere hym forto smyte hise mowþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.32" type="verse">Hym þis same Iesu God raysed agayn, werof ande of whom we alle ben witnes.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.30" type="verse">Ande whanne hit was tolde me of þo waytynges þat þei ordeyned agayne hym, I sende hym vnto þe, ande biddande vnto þe accusars þat þei telle þer pleynte bifore þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.31" type="verse">Ande þo knyghtes, as hit was boden to hem, þei toke Poule, ande ledde hym into Antipatridem.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.32" type="verse">Ande þo toþer day þei lefte þer þer horses forto go wiþ hym, ande þei ȝode vnto þo castels.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.33" type="verse">Ande whanne þei wore comen vnto Cesarie, ande hade gifen þe letter vnto þo mayre , þei sette bifore hym Poule.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.34" type="verse">Ande whanne he hade redde þo letter, ande asched of what contre
<seg id="b.ACT.23.35" type="verse">he was; ande whanne he knewe þat he was of Cylyce, he saide, I schal here þe whan þine accusars comen. Ande he bade kepe hym in þo mote-halle of Herowde (þo place þere Heroude demed).
<seg id="b.ACT.2.33" type="verse">Ande þerfore forsoþe highe liftud vppe þo righte honde of God ande þurghe þo bihetynge of þo Holygoste taken of þo Fadire, he has ȝotted downe þis, þat ȝhe see ande here.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.3" type="verse">Þanne sayde Poule vnto hym, Þow wall whited , Godde schal strike þe. Ande þou syttande demes me efter þo lawe, ande agaynes þe lawe þow biddes þat I be smyten.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.4" type="verse">Ande þoo þat stoden by saiden vnto Poule, Waries þow þo souereyne preste ?
<seg id="b.ACT.2.34" type="verse">Soþely Dauid steghe noghte vppe into heuen: for hymseluen soþely sais, Oure Lorde saide vnto my Lorde, Syt
<seg id="b.ACT.23.5" type="verse">Ande Poule saide, I wiste noghte, breþer, þat he was prince of prestes. For hit es writen, Þow schalte noghte warye þo prince of þi flokke .
<seg id="b.ACT.2.35" type="verse">þow vpon my righte honde, þe while þat I putte þine enmyse schamel of þi fete (þat es, til þat I putte hem vnder
<seg id="b.ACT.23.6" type="verse">Ande whanne Poule knewe þat one partye of þoo þat wore gadired þer was of þo Pharisens, ande an-oþer of þo Saducens, he cried in þo cownseyle, Ȝhe men, breþer , I am a Pharisene, þo sone of a Pharisene, of þo hope ande of þo resurrecyone I am demed.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.36" type="verse">þi fete) Ande þerfore certaynly wite alle þo folkke of Israel, þat God has maked hym Lorde ande Criste, þis iche same Iesu þat ȝhe crucified.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.7" type="verse">Ande whanne he hade saide þise, onone was made a discencyone þo Pharisens ande þo Saducens, ande so þo multitude was diuersed ande twynned.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.37" type="verse">Ande whanne þei herde þis, in hertte þei wore prikked, ande þanne þei saide vnto Peter ande to þo toþer apostuls, Leue men ande breþer, what schal we do?
<seg id="b.ACT.2.38" type="verse">Soþely Peter saide vnto hem, Dos penaunce, ande iche of ȝowe be baptised in þo name of oure Lorde Iesu Criste in forgifnes of ȝoure synnes; ande ȝhe schal take þo gifte of þo Holygoste.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.8" type="verse">Þo Saducens saide, þat þere schulde no resurreccyone be, ande þat þer was nouþer awngel nor spiritte: ande þo Pharisens saide þo reuerce þat boþe þise was.
<seg id="b.ACT.23.9" type="verse">Ande grete criynge was made: ande sum of þo Pharises faughte, sayande, We fynde none yuel in þis man: what þofe a spirytte hafe spoken vnto hym, or an awngel?
<seg id="b.ACT.2.39" type="verse">Vnto ȝow es hette a bihetynge, ande alsso vnto ȝowre childer, ande to alle þat fer be, ande vnto alle þat God oure Lorde haues called .
<seg id="b.ACT.2.3" type="verse">Ande diuerse langages appered vnto hem, as it wore fire; ande sat abouen icheone of hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.40" type="verse">Wiþ many alsso oþer wordes he has wytnessed , ande he amonested hem, ande saide, Bes ȝhe saued fro þis schrewde kynreden.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.10" type="verse">Ande þo mayre made token to Poule to speke, and Poule ansuered, Of many ȝhere I þat haue knowne þe iuge vnto þis flokke , schal make satisfaccyon for
<seg id="b.ACT.24.11" type="verse">me bifore þe: þow may wele knowe þat no moo days ben vnto me bot twelfe siþen I come fro Ierusalem.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.12" type="verse">Ande in þo temple þei han noghte fownden any disputande wiþ me or elles makande any concourse of company, nouþer in þo temple, nor in þo synagoge, nor in þo cyte.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.13" type="verse">Nor þei may proue þinges þat þei accusen me of vnto þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.14" type="verse">, þat efter þo secte þat þei callen heresie, I haue so serued to God my fadire þat I trowe vnto alle þat ben
<seg id="b.ACT.24.15" type="verse">wryten in þo lawe ande þo prophecye: hafande my hope in God, in þo whiche alsso hemseluen abiden þo resurreccione þat es forto come boþe of þo gode ande þo yuel.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.16" type="verse">In þis alsso I studye forto haue conscience to God euermore, ande to men alsso wiþouten offendikel.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.17" type="verse">Ande efter many ȝhere I come vnto my nacyon forto do almes, ande forto do myne
<seg id="b.ACT.24.18" type="verse">offeringes ande myne auowes: in þo whiche þei fonde me purified in þo temple, noghte wiþ grete companye, nor wiþ noyce. Ande þei toke me, cryande ande sayande, Vndo oure enmye.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.19" type="verse">And summe Iewes of Asye, whom hit bihoued
<seg id="b.ACT.24.1" type="verse">Ande efter fiue dais come þo prince of prestes Anany with summe of þo elders, and wiþ one Tertullo, an orator (þat es, a motar or aduoket); þise wente vnto þe maire agaynes Poule.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.41" type="verse">Ande þoo þat receyued þer sermone wore baptised: ande þat day weren wonnen vnto God ande turned abowte þreo þowsande.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.20" type="verse">oghte agaynes me, or elles say þise hemseluen, if þei hafe fownden any wikkednes in me, siþen I stonde here in þo
<seg id="b.ACT.24.21" type="verse">conseyle, bot onely of þis one voyce, þat I cried stondande amonges hem and sayande, I am demed of ȝowe of þo resurreccione of deade .
<seg id="b.ACT.24.22" type="verse">&amp; Felix differde hem þat accuseden hym, for he knwe how hit was, ande he saide to hem, Whanne þo tribune Lysias komes, I schal here ȝowe.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.23" type="verse">Ande he bade vnto a centuryone forto kepe Poule, ande þat he schulde haue reste; ande þat none of hem schulde be lette forto mynister vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.24" type="verse">Ande efter summe dais Felix come wiþ Drusille, hise wife, þo whiche was a Iewes, ande called Poule, ande harde of hym þo faiþe in oure Lorde Iesu Criste.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.25" type="verse">Ande whanne he disputed of rightwisenes, ande chastite, ande þo dome þat was forto come, Felix was ferde, ande ansuered, Go nowe at þis tyme, for in a couenabul tyme I schal calle þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.26" type="verse">Ande Felix supposed that Poule schulde gife hym summe moneye: and þerfore often tyme he called hym, and speke with hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.27" type="verse">Ande efter þat Felix hade fynisched hise two ȝhere in hise office, he hade a successoure whos name was called Festus. Ande for Felix wolde haue þanke of þo Iewes, he lefte Poule bownden in bondes.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.2" type="verse">Ande whanne Poule was sommunde, Tertullus biganne to accuse Poule, ande saide vnto þe mayre , Siþen we ben in meke pece bi þe, ande many þinges
<seg id="b.ACT.2.42" type="verse">Ande þei wore þanne lastande in þo apostuls techinge, ande in komunynge of brekinge of brede, ande in preyers.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.3" type="verse">ben correctud by þi prouidence, euermore , gode Felix, we han receyued þise wiþ alle dedis of þankes.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.43" type="verse">Dredfulle was forsoþe iche sowle: ande many merueyles ande wondurs wore bi þo apostuls in Ierusalem wroghte; ande grete drede was amonges hem alle.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.44" type="verse">Alle alsso þat trowed weren togader, ande alle
<seg id="b.ACT.24.4" type="verse">Ande þat I no lenger tarye þe , I prey þe, here þis for þi godenes.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.5" type="verse">We haue fownden þis wikked man, ande styrande sedicione vnto alle þo Iewes in alle þo worlde, ande autor of þo sedicione of
<seg id="b.ACT.2.45" type="verse">þer þinges woren in komun amonges hem; þei solden þer londes, þer catelle ande þer godus , ande departed hit amonges hem alle, vnto euerichone efter he hade nede.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.46" type="verse">Ande iche day þei contynued lastande in þo temple togader, ande abowte howses (þat es, vnto þo puple þat þer kome of diuerse places) þei brake þe brede (þat es, Goddes worde) , þei token
<seg id="b.ACT.24.6" type="verse">þo secte of Nazarens: ande oure temple has he ben aboute forto file. Ande whanne we haden taken hym, we wolde haue iuged hym efter oure lawe.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.7" type="verse">Ande þo tribune Lysias kome, and toke oute of our hende with grete
<seg id="b.ACT.2.47" type="verse">mete wiþ ioye ande sympulnes of hertte, þankande God, ande hafande grace vnto alle folke. Ande oure Lorde saued iche day in hymseluen] .
<seg id="b.ACT.24.8" type="verse">strenkthe, ande bade hise accusars come vnto þe, of whom þow may knowe, demande of alle þise, of þo whiche we accusen hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.24.9" type="verse">Ande þo Iewes saiden alsso þat þus hit was.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.4" type="verse">Ande alle were fulfilled of þo Holigoste, ande þei biganne to speke in diuerse langages, righte as þo Holigoste gafe to hem to speke.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.10" type="verse">Ande Poule saide, I stonde atte þo demynge-place of þo Cesare, where hit behoues me forto be demed. I haue noghte noyed vnto þo Iewes, as þow wele knowes.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.11" type="verse">Ande if I haue noyed or done any þinge worþi þo deþe, I recuse noghte to dye. Bot if I haue done no þinge þat þei accuse me of, none may gife me vnto hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.12" type="verse">Vnto þo Cesar I appele. Þanne Festus spake wiþ hise cownseyle, and ansuered, Þow haues appeled vnto þo Cesar, ande to þo Cesar schalte þow go.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.13" type="verse">Ande whanne summe days wore passed, þo kenge Agrippa ande men of Baronye come vnto Cesarie to Festus, forto hayls hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.14" type="verse">And whanne þei hade ben þore many dayes, Festus tolde vnto þo kenge of Poule, &amp; sayde, þer was a man lefte
<seg id="b.ACT.25.15" type="verse">bownden of Felix: for whom, whanne I was at Ierusalem, þo princes of prestes ande þo elders come vnto me, aschande dampnacione agaynes hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.16" type="verse">To whom I ansuered, þat hit es noghte custome vnto þo Romayns to dampne any man, to he þat es accused haue presente hise accusars, and alsso þat he haue place forto defende hym, forto ansuere vnto þo crymes þat ben putte vpon hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.17" type="verse">Ande whanne þei come hider wiþouten any taryynge, I sate on þo toþer day forto deme, and I bade hym forto be broghte forþe .
<seg id="b.ACT.25.18" type="verse">Of whom, whanne hise accusars stode bifore me, I fonde no cause of þo whiche I supposed ille .
<seg id="b.ACT.25.19" type="verse">Bot summe questions of his supersticione þei hade agayne hym, and specially of one Iesu, þat
<seg id="b.ACT.25.1" type="verse">Ande whanne Festus þanne come into þo contre, efter þo þridde daye he wente vnto Ierusalem fro Cesarye.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.20" type="verse">Ande for I was in doute of þis question, I asched if he wolde go vnto Ierusalem and be iuged þore of þise .
<seg id="b.ACT.25.21" type="verse">Ande Poule appeled, &amp; forto kepe hit vnto þo knowynge of þo Auguste, I bade kepe hym to I sende hym vnto þo Cesar.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.22" type="verse">Ande Agrippa saide to Festus, I wolde alsso here þat man. 7Ande Festus ansuered7 , Tomorne þow schalte here hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.23" type="verse">Ande vpon þo toþer daye, whanne Agrippa ande þo men of Beronye wore comen with grete ȝerneynge , ande wore enterd þo audytorye, wiþ þo tribunes ande þo principal men of þo cyte, at þo bidynge of Festus Poule was broghte forþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.24" type="verse">Ande Festus saide, Kenge Agrippa, ande ȝhe alle þat ben here wiþ vs, ȝhe sene þis man, of whom alle þo multitude of þo Iewes speke vnto me at Ierusalem, aschande &amp; criande þat he schulde no lenger life.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.25" type="verse">Ande I fonde no þinge þat he wore worþi þe deþe fore. Ande for he haues appeled, I haue demed to sende hym vnto Auguste.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.26" type="verse">Bot in certayne what I may write to my lorde haue I noghte. Ande for þis cause I haue broghte hym forthe vnto ȝowe, and specially vnto þo kenge Agrippa, þat I may asche hym bifore ȝowe, ande þat I may knowe what I schal write.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.27" type="verse">For wiþouten resone me þenke to sende hym bownden, ande noghte forto telle þo cause.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.2" type="verse">Ande þo princes of prestes come vnto hym, and þo firste &amp; þo moste worþi of þo Iewes, agayne Poule. Ande þei preyde
<seg id="b.ACT.25.3" type="verse">hym, aschande grace agayn hym, þat he schulde bidde hym be broghte into Ierusalem, settande waytynges forto slee hym in þo waye.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.4" type="verse">Ande Festus ansuered, þat Poule schulde be kepped in Cesarye, ande þat hymseluen schulde hastily go þider.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.5" type="verse">Ande þerfore, he saide, þoo þat ben myghty in ȝowe , kome þei alsso. Ande if þer be any cryme in þo man, accuse þei hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.6" type="verse">And he dwelled amonge hem days no mo bot eghte or tenne. Ande he wente into Cesarye,
<seg id="b.ACT.25.7" type="verse">Ande whanne he was broghte forþe, Iewes þat komen fro Ierusalem stoden aboute hym, castande agayne hym many grete causes, þo whiche þei myghte noghte
<seg id="b.ACT.25.8" type="verse">proue; for Poule made his skille agayne, sayande, þat nouper I haue synned agayn þo lawe of þo Iewes, nor agayne þo temple, nor agayne þo Cesar.
<seg id="b.ACT.25.9" type="verse">Ande Festus, in wille forto gife grace vnto þo Iewes , ande forto haue þanke of hem, ansuered vnto Poule and saide, Wilte þou go vnto Ierusalem, ande þer be iuged of þise bifore me?
<seg id="b.ACT.2.5" type="verse">Ande þer wore þat tyme soþely in Ierusalem dwellande Iwes , religiowse men of alle nacyon þat vndur heuen was.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.10" type="verse">Ande I sparde in prisone many halowes; and þis I did in Ierusalem, for suche power I toke of þo princes ; ande whanne þei wore slayne, I bare þo sentence.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.11" type="verse">Ande punyschande hem customabuly by alle þo synagoges, I garte hem forto blaspheme. Ande ȝitte I was more wode agaynes hem, ande pursewed hem to oute nacyons.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.12" type="verse">In þo whiche, when I wente vnto Damaske wiþ þo power &amp; letters of princes of
<seg id="b.ACT.26.13" type="verse">prestes, in þo myddes of þo daye, in þo waye I sawe, kenge Agrippa, fro heuen, passande þo schynynge of þo sunne, a lyghte þat vmschone me and hem þat wore wiþ me.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.14" type="verse">Ande whanne we alle felle vnto þo erthe, I harde a voice spekande to me in þe tunge of Hebrewe, Saule, Saule, whi pursewes þow me? Hit es harde to þe to kes agayne þo brodde .
<seg id="b.ACT.26.15" type="verse">Ande I saide, Who erte þow, Lorde? Ande he saide, I am Iesu whom þow pursewes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.16" type="verse">Bot rise vppe, he saide, ande stonde vpon þi fete: for for þis cause I appered vnto þe, forto make þe a mynister ande wytnes of þinges þat þow haues sene, and of þo in whom I schal appere to þ ;
<seg id="b.ACT.26.17" type="verse">delyuerande þe fro pupuls ande nacyons, to whom nowe
<seg id="b.ACT.26.18" type="verse">I sende þe, forto opun þo eyghne of þo blynde, þat þei turne fro þo derkenes vnto þo lighte, fro þe pouer of þo fende to God, ande þat þei take remyssion of synnes, ande lote amonge
<seg id="b.ACT.26.19" type="verse">Wherfore, kenge Agrippa,
<seg id="b.ACT.26.1" type="verse">Ande þo kenge Agrippa saide vnto Poule, Hit es sufferde þat þow speke for þiseluen. Þanne Poule spredde
<seg id="b.ACT.26.20" type="verse">I was noghte vntrowthfulle to þo heuenly visione: bot to hem þat wore at Damaske firste, ande siþen to þem þat wore at Ierusalem, I schewed hit, ande bi alle þo contre boþe to þo Iewrye ande to þo nacions, þat þei schulde do penawnce, ande þat þei schulde be turned vnto God, doynge þo worþi frutes of penawnce.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.21" type="verse">For þis cause þo Iewes, whan I was in þo temple, wolde haue slayne me, ande toke me.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.22" type="verse">Ande ȝitte vnto þis daye I stande, hulpun wiþ þo grace of God, witnessande boþe to þo lesse ande to þo more, no þinge sayande
<seg id="b.ACT.26.23" type="verse">more þanne Moyses ande þo prophetes saide forto kome; þat Criste was pssibul , &amp; þat he was firste of þo resurreccione of þo deed, forto schewe lyghte vnto þo puple ande to þo naciones.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.24" type="verse">Ande whanne he spake þus ande schewed resone and skille for hym, Festus saide wiþ a grete voyce, Poule, þow fonnes ; myche letturere turnes þe vnto foly .
<seg id="b.ACT.26.25" type="verse">Ande Poule saide, Gode Festus, I fonne noghte, bot I speke wordes of soburnes and soþefastenes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.26" type="verse">For þo kenge knowes of þise, to whom I speke stabuly; I suppose þat none of þise es vnknowne to hym; for none of þise was done in hiddels (or, in hernes).
<seg id="b.ACT.26.27" type="verse">Ande þo kenge Agrippa trowes vnto þo prophetes; I wote þat þow trowes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.28" type="verse">Ande þo kenge Agrippa saide vnto Poule, In lytel þou makes a skille þat I am Cristen.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.29" type="verse">Ande Poule saide, I ȝerne bifore God in lytel ande in myche, noghte onely þe, bot alsso alle þat heren me todaye, forto be made suche as I am, outetaken þise bondes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.2" type="verse">hise hende obrode , and gafe his skille, ande saide, Of alle þo þinges þat I am accused of þo Iewes, kenge Agrippa, I suppose me blessed ande clene bifore þe, siþen I schal defende me today.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.30" type="verse">Ande þo kenge, ande þo mayre, ande þo men of Beronye,
<seg id="b.ACT.26.31" type="verse">and þoo þat sate wiþ hem, rose vp; and wente biside ande speke togider &amp; saide, No þinge haues þis man done þat es worþi þo deþe or bondes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.32" type="verse">Ande Agrippa saide vnto Festus, Þis man myghte haue ben laten go, if he hade noghte appeled vnto þe Cesar .
<seg id="b.ACT.26.3" type="verse">Ande specyally siþen þow knowes alle þo customes þat ben amonge þo Iewes, ande alsso þo questions þat ben amonge hem: wherfore I preye þe þat
<seg id="b.ACT.26.4" type="verse">Ande alsso forsoþe my lyfe fro my ȝowþe, ande fro þo bigynnynge in my nacyone, in Ierusalem,
<seg id="b.ACT.26.5" type="verse">alle þo Iewes knowe; knowande me fro þo bigynnynge, if þei wolde bere wytnes, þat efter þo certayne secte of oure relygione I haue lifed a Pharisene.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.6" type="verse">Ande nowe in þo hope of biheste þat was made vnto oure fadires of oure Lorde God, I
<seg id="b.ACT.26.7" type="verse">stonde subjecte to þo dome; in þo whiche oure twelue tribes, nyghte ande daye seruande, hopen to come. Of þo whiche hope, kenge Agrippa, I am accused of þo Iewes.
<seg id="b.ACT.26.8" type="verse">Bot whatte es demed incredibil anentes ȝowe, if God raise þo deed?
<seg id="b.ACT.26.9" type="verse">Ande I alsso supposed, þat me awghte to do many contraryouse þinges agayne þo name of Iesu of Nazarene.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.6" type="verse">Ande whanne þis voice was made ande þis sowne , þer kome togider grete multitude, ande was confused in mynde: ande þei merueyld gretly, for icheone harde hem spekande in hise langage.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.10" type="verse">fasted, Poule comforþed hem, sayande , Men, I see þat wiþ iniurye ande myche harme noghte onely of þo charge þat es of þo schippe ande of þo schippe, , bigynnes oure schiprode to be.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.11" type="verse">Þo centurio trowed vnto þo guuernere of þo schippe ande to þo schipman more þanne to Poule saynges .
<seg id="b.ACT.27.12" type="verse">Ande for þei haden noghte habul hauenynge forto wynter inne, þei toke þer cownsel to go fro þeþen , if þei myghte on any wise come vnto Phenyce, forto wynter at þo hauen of Crete, þo whiche was berande towarde Affriche, ande Chore.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.13" type="verse">Bot whan þo souþe wynde blewe, whanne þei supposed to holde þer purpose, ande hade gone
<seg id="b.ACT.27.14" type="verse">fro Assere ande hade passed Crete, noghte myche efter come
<seg id="b.ACT.27.15" type="verse">Ande whanne þo schippe was vppe-taken, ande myghte noghte enforce agayne þo wynde, we gafe þo schippe to þo wynde, ande þo wynde bere vs.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.16" type="verse">Ande so we come vnto an ile þat es named Cawda .
<seg id="b.ACT.27.17" type="verse">Ande vneþe myghte we gete þo kokbote: and whanne þis was hade away, þei vsed helpinge, byndande þo schippe; dredande þat ne þei schulde falle into sande place: ande so þei wore borne, while þe vessel was keste downe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.18" type="verse">we wore schaken wiþ a grete tempeste; ande þo toþer þei keste oute of þo schippe þinges þat wore þerinne.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.19" type="verse">Ande vpon þo þridde day þei keste oute þe armorye of þo schippe
<seg id="b.ACT.27.1" type="verse">Ande whanne hit was demed þat he schulde schippe into Ytalye, ande be taken vnto þo centurion of þo companye
<seg id="b.ACT.27.20" type="verse">wiþ þer hende, for noþer sonne nor mone nor sternes appered bi many dais. Ande grete tempeste was, ande þan was alle hope of oure hele away.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.21" type="verse">Ande whanne we longe hade fastud, Poule stode ymyddes and saide, It behoued , ȝhe men, forto here me (or, forto haue harde me), noghte to haue passed fro Crete, ande forto haue wonnen þis losse .
<seg id="b.ACT.27.22" type="verse">Bote ȝitte bes of gode herte: for losse schal þer none be of none of ȝoure lifes, bot only of þo schippe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.23" type="verse">For þis nyghte stode bi me þo awngel of God, whos I am, ande vnto whom
<seg id="b.ACT.27.24" type="verse">I serue, ande saide, Poule, drede þe noghte, forto vnto þo cesar þe bihoues to come. Ande lo, God haues giuen vnto þe alle þat ben in þo schippe wiþ þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.25" type="verse">Ande þerfore, men, bes of gode herte: for I trowe vnto my God, þat so schal it be as hit was saide vnto me.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.26" type="verse">Ande into an ile schal we come.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.27" type="verse">Bot efter þo fourtene nyghte was comen, and we wore schippande in A-drye, aboute þo mydde-nyghte þo schipmen supposed þat þei see a contre.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.28" type="verse">Ande þei put þer plumbe into þe see to knowe þo depnes of water; ande þei fonde twenty paces. Ande whanne þei wore a lytel þen, þei fonde XV pases.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.29" type="verse">Ande for þei dredde þat þei schulde falle into scharpe places, þei sende foure ankers oute of þo schippe,
<seg id="b.ACT.27.2" type="verse">of Auguste whos name was Iulye, we wente into a schippe of Hardumetyne . Ande whanne we biganne to sayle, we bere vppe aboute þo places of Asye; ande with vs dwelled Aristarcus Mecedonye of Thessalonye.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.30" type="verse">Ande whan þo schipmen wolden hafe fledde oute of þo schippe , ande hade put oute þo
<seg id="b.ACT.27.31" type="verse">bote of þe schippe into þe see as forto keste þer ankers, Poule saide 4vnto þo centurion ande to þe knyghtes4 , Bot if ȝhe be stille in þo schippe, ȝhe may noghte be saued .
<seg id="b.ACT.27.32" type="verse">Thanne þo knyghtus kutteden away þo cordes of þo boot, ande suffured hit to falle away.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.33" type="verse">Ande whanne lyghte biganne forto come, Poule preyde hem alle þat þei schulde ete sumwhat, ande saide, Þis es þo fourtende daye þat ȝhe hauen ben fastande, ande no mete haue ȝhe eten (or, taken).
<seg id="b.ACT.27.34" type="verse">Wherfore I pray ȝowe to take summe meate for ȝoure hele: for a heer of none of ȝoure hedes schal perische.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.35" type="verse">Ande whanne he hade saide þis, he toke brede ande þanked God in alle þer sighte. Ande
<seg id="b.ACT.27.36" type="verse">whanne he hade broken þo brede ande biganne forto ete, þei wore made þo more herty ande toke mete alsso.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.37" type="verse">Þo men þat wore in þe schippe wore two hundrethe seuenty ande sexe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.38" type="verse">Ande whanne þei haden eten þer fille, þei allegid þo schippe, ande keste þo whete into þo see.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.39" type="verse">Ande whanne day was comen, þei knew þo londe . Bot an arme þei bihelde, in þo whiche þei see as hit wore a banke. Ande þider þei þoghte, if þei myghte, to keste þo schippe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.3" type="verse">Ande þo nexte day we come unto Sidon: and Iulye treed Poule manly, and lete hym go to hise frendes, and forto do hise owne cure.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.40" type="verse">Ande whanne þei hade drawen vppe þo ankurs, þei putte hem vnto þe see, slakande þo iunctures fro þo gubernacle , &amp; raised a lytel sayle. Ande bi þo blaste of þo wynde þei wente vnto þo banke.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.41" type="verse">Ande whanne we wore fallen into a place þer two sees mette, þei enpeched þo schippe; ande þo forþer partye of þo schippe stode stille. Bot þo schippe lowsed for strenkthe of þo see.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.42" type="verse">Ande þo knyghtes gafe counseile, þat þoo þat wore vndure kepinge in þo schippe schulde be slayne, and þat þei schulde noghte skape awaye.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.43" type="verse">Ande þo centurion, for he wolde þat Poule wore saued, forbedde so to do. Ande he bade þat þoo þat couþe swymme schulde firste go vnto þo see, ande so skape ande come vnto þo londe.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.44" type="verse">Ande oþer toke bordes, and summe toke oþer þinges þat wore of þo schippe. Ande so bifelle, þat þei alle skaped vnto þo londe saufe , &amp; none perisched.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.4" type="verse">Ande whanne we wente fro þeþen , we vndursayled Ciper, for þo wyndes wore contrariouse.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.5" type="verse">Ande we, saylande þo see of Cylyce and Pamphile, in twelue days we come vnto Listram of Lycie.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.6" type="verse">Ande þore þo centurion fonde a schippe of Alysawnder, schippande into Ytalye; &amp; he putte vs in hit.
<seg id="b.ACT.27.7" type="verse">Ande whanne we hade sailed slouly many dais, ande vneþes wore comen agayne Gwyde, for lettynge of þo wynde, we
<seg id="b.ACT.27.8" type="verse">sayled vnto Crete biside Salomon; ande vneþe saylande biside into a place þat es called Gode Porte (or, hauen), to þo whiche es nere þo cyte of Thessal .
<seg id="b.ACT.27.9" type="verse">Ande whanne longe tyme ande myche þan was passed, ande was no forþer siker schippynge ande saylynge, for þat þei haden longe
<seg id="b.ACT.2.7" type="verse">Alle soþely þei were amerueylde , ande gretely wondurden , ande saiden, Lo, ne ben noghte alle þise men of Galilee þat speken vpon þis wise?
<seg id="b.ACT.28.10" type="verse">Ande men of þat ile worschipped vs with myche worschippe, ande gafe vs þat vs nedid vnto oure efteschippinge.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.11" type="verse">Ande efter three monythes we schipped in a schippe of Alysawnder, þo whiche hade wynterde in þat ile, ande hade fairnes of castels .
<seg id="b.ACT.28.12" type="verse">Ande whanne we wore comen to Syracuse, þere we dwelled three dais.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.13" type="verse">Ande fro þeþen we passed abowte, ande come vnto Regyum: ande efter þo mydday whanne þo souþe blewe, þo secunde day we
<seg id="b.ACT.28.14" type="verse">come to Puteolos: where we fonde breþer, ande þei preyd vs forto dwelle wiþ hem seuen dais: ande so come we vnto Rome.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.15" type="verse">Ande whanne þo breþer þere harde of oure comynge, þei come agayne vs vnto þo merket of Appii, þo senator; ande whanne Poule se hem, he þanked God, ande toke gode traiste.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.16" type="verse">Ande whanne we wore comen vnto Rome, Poule was suffurd to dwelle wiþouten þo castels bi hymseluen wiþ one knyghte to kepe hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.17" type="verse">Ande efter þo thridde daye he called togider þo firste of þo Iewes: ande whanne þei wore comen togider, he saide vnto hem, Ȝhe men , breþer, I haue done no þinge agayne þo pupil of þo Iewes, or agayn eldar doynge. Ande fro Ierusalem I am bitaken bownden into þo
<seg id="b.ACT.28.18" type="verse">hende of þo Romaynes; &amp; whanne þei hade aschinge of me, þei wolde haue laten me go, for þei fonde no cause of deþe in me.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.19" type="verse">Ande for þo Iewes agayn-saide þat I schulde noghte be delyuerde, þerfore was I garte forto appele vnto þo Cesar; noghte forto accuse my nacione.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.1" type="verse">Ande whanne we were skaped, þanne knewe we þat þo londe þat we were onne was called þo ile of Mutilene.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.20" type="verse">Ande for þis cause I praide forto see ȝowe, ande forto speke wiþ ȝowe: forwhi for þo hope of Israel I am vmgyuen (or, bounden) with þis cheyne.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.21" type="verse">Ande þei saide vnto hym, We toke neuer lettures fro þo Iewry of þe, nor none comande to vs haues tolde vs any dede or ille of þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.22" type="verse">Bot we prey þe , þat we may here of þe , what þow can ande felys. For of þo secte es knowne þat in iche place hit es withstande.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.23" type="verse">Ande whanne he hade sette hem a daye, many come vnto hise hostage þer he dwelled; vnto whom he expowned, witnessande þo kengdome of God, ande makande skilles to hem of Iesu, of þo lawe of Moisy, ande of þo prophetes, fro þo morne vnto þo euen .
<seg id="b.ACT.28.24" type="verse">Ande summe trowed vnto þoo þat he saide, ande summe trowed noghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.25" type="verse">Ande whanne þei wore not assentande togider, þei lerned of Poule o worde þat wele þo Holigoste speke by
<seg id="b.ACT.28.26" type="verse">Isaye þo prophete vnto oure fadirs, sayande, Go to þis puple,
<seg id="b.ACT.28.27" type="verse">schal noghte biholde: for þo herte of þis puple es hardende , ande wiþ eres heuely þei han harde. Ande þer eyne þai han lokked togider; þat in aunter þei se noghte wiþ eyne, ande here with eres, ande vndurstonde with herte, forto turne hem, þat I hele hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.28" type="verse">Ande þerfore be hit knowne vnto ȝowe, þat þis helfulle þinges es sende vnto naciones: ande þei schal here hit.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.2" type="verse">Ande þo barbarise schewed myche manhede vnto vs, for þei kindeld a fire, ande refresched vs, for þe rayne ande þo colde þat was þanne.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.30" type="verse">Ande Poule dwelled alle þat two ȝhere in þat place þat he hired, ande receyued alle þat come to hym, þo Iewes,
<seg id="b.ACT.28.31" type="verse">ande þo naciones þat wore called gentiles, prechande þo kengdame of God, ande techande þinges þat ben of oure Lorde Iesu Criste wiþ fulle traiste wiþouten lettynge .
<seg id="b.ACT.28.3" type="verse">Ande whanne Poule hade gider stikkes, ande hade layde hem vpon þo fire, a nedder come from þo hete, and smote into his honde.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.4" type="verse">&amp; whanne þo barbarise se þo beste hongande in hise honde, þei saide togider, Forsothe he þis es a mansleare, for þofe he skaped fro þo see, he es noghte suffurde no lenger to lyfe.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.5" type="verse">Ande Poule smote þo beste into þe fire, ande hade none harme.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.6" type="verse">Ande þei supposed þat he schulde bolne , ande sodenly falle downe ande dighe. Ande whanne þei longe hade abiden, and seghe þat he hade none harme, þei turned ande saide þat he was God.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.7" type="verse">Ande in þo places wore þe maners of þo prince of þat ile, whos name was Publyus; þo whiche receyued vs, ande benyngly refresched vs three dais.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.8" type="verse">Ande þo fader of þis prince laye in þo fiuoures ande in þo yuel þat es called dissintery: vnto whom Poule enterde. Ande whanne he hade layde vpon hym his hondes, he helud hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.28.9" type="verse">Ande whanne þis was done, alle þat wore in þo ile ande wore seke come vnto hym, ande wore helud.
<seg id="b.ACT.2.8" type="verse">Ande how es hit þat iche of vs has harde hise langage, in whiche þat we wore borne inne?
<seg id="b.ACT.2.9" type="verse">Of Parthi, Medy ande Elamyte, ande of hem þat dwellen in Mesapotonye,
<seg id="b.ACT.3.11" type="verse">Ande soþely whanne þei Peter ande Iohn, alle þo puple kome rennande vnto hem to Salomons porte , wondurande vpon hem ande biholdande .
<seg id="b.ACT.3.12" type="verse">Ande Peter whanne he sawe þat, he saide vnto þo folke, Men of Israel, whi wonduren ȝhe here-oponne , ande whi biholde ȝhe vs so, as we þurghe oure vertewe or oure power hafe made hym þis to go?
<seg id="b.ACT.3.13" type="verse">Abrahams God ande Isaaks God ande Iacobs God ande ȝoure faders God haues glorified hise sone Iesu; þo whiche forsoþe ȝhe bitraide ande denied bifore þo face of Pilate, demande hym vnto þo deþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.14" type="verse">Ȝhe, forsoþe , þo holy ande þo rightwise man ȝhe denied, ande asched to be gifen vnto ȝowe a man þat
<seg id="b.ACT.3.15" type="verse">was a mansleare; soþefastely þo maker of life ȝhe slowe, þat God raysed fro deþe vnto life, whos wytnes we ben.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.16" type="verse">Ande in þo faiþe of hise name hym þis þat ȝhe see ande knowe, he haues confermed ande helud: þo name of hym, ande þo faiþe þat es bi hym gafe þis man fully his hele bifore alle ȝoure sighte.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.17" type="verse">Ande nowe, breþer, I wote þat þurghe vnknowynge ȝhe hit did, ande so did ȝoure princes.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.18" type="verse">Þo þinges soþely þat God spake bifore þurghe þo mowþe of alle þo prophetes, þat his Criste schulde suffure, þus he fulfilled hit.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.19" type="verse">Dos penawnce þerfore, ande bes turned, þat ȝowre
<seg id="b.ACT.3.1" type="verse">Peter soþely ande saynte John ȝoden into þo temple atte þo houre of none-preyer.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.20" type="verse">synnes be done away, whanne þo tymes schul kome of refreschinge fro þo siȝte of God, ande whanne he schal sende
<seg id="b.ACT.3.21" type="verse">hym þat es preched vnto ȝowe, Iesu Criste: þo whiche schal dwelle in heuen vnto þo tyme of restorynge of alle þat God has spoken þurghe þo mowþe of his sayntes fro þo bigynnynge of þo worlde ande þurghe hise prophetes.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.22" type="verse">Moyses soþely saide, God oure Lorde schal raise vnto vs a prophete of oure breþere; ȝhe schal here hym as meseluen (þat es, as ȝhe done me) anentes alle þinges þat he schal speke vnto ȝowe.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.23" type="verse">Ande soþely hit schal be, þat iche sowle þat heres noghte þo prophete, schal be þutte oute of þo puple &amp; oute of hise termes.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.24" type="verse">Ande alle þo prophetes fro Samuel ande so forþermore, þat spaken, schewed þise dais.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.25" type="verse">Ande ȝhe soþely ben prophetes sones ande of þo testamente þat God disposed ande ordeynde to oure faders, sayande vnto Abraham, In þi sede schal be blessed alle þo meyne of erþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.26" type="verse">To ȝow firste God raysed his sone, sende hym blessande ȝowe, þat icheone schulde turne hym from þo way of his wikkednes.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.2" type="verse">Ande a man þat was crokud fro
<seg id="b.ACT.3.3" type="verse">He þis whan he sawe Peter ande Ioon begynne to enter into þo temple, he preide hem of þer almes.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.4" type="verse">Ande Peter wiþ Ioon bihelde vnto hym, ande saide, Loke vpon vs.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.5" type="verse">Ande he bihelde vpon hem, and trowed sumwhate to haue of hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.6" type="verse">And þanne Peter soþely saide, Golde ande syluer haue I none (þat es to say, noþer) ; bot soþely þat þat I haue I gife vnto þe. In þo name of Iesu Criste
<seg id="b.ACT.3.7" type="verse">of Nazareth, rise ande go; ande toke hise righte honde, ande lifte hym vppe: &amp; alssone wore hise lymes made hole ande sadde.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.8" type="verse">Ande he stode vppe ande ȝode his way, worschipande ande þankande God.
<seg id="b.ACT.3.9" type="verse">: soþely men hym knewe, þat hit was he þat satte at þo temple-dore forto asche mennes almes: ande of hym þei wore merueyled ande gretely awonderde how hit so bifelle vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.10" type="verse">seke man, in þo whiche he þis es made saufe, knowne þinge be hit vnto ȝowe , ande to alle þo folke of Israel: for in þo name of Iesu Criste of Nazareth, þe whiche ȝhe crucified, whom God raysed agayn fro deþe, in þat he þis stondes bifore ȝow hole.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.11" type="verse">He þis Ihesus es þo stone þat of ȝowe was reproued in howsinge, þat es nowe made þo heued kornerstone. Ande þer es no hele in any oþer.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.12" type="verse">Nor soþely oþer name vnder heuen es none gifen vnto men, in whiche we maye ande bihoues be saued.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.13" type="verse">Ande whanne þe men sawe ande bihelde þo stedfastnes offe Peter ande Iohn, ande was founden þat þei wore men unletterde ande ideotes, þei were amerueyled, ande knew þem, þat þei hade ben wiþ Iesu.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.14" type="verse">Ande þei sawe þo man stondande wiþ hem þat was heled ; ande no þinge þei myghte agaynsaye.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.15" type="verse">Ande þei komanded hem forto go oute of þo kownseyl, ande þei kownseilde togider, ande saide, What schal we do vnto þise men?
<seg id="b.ACT.4.16" type="verse">For als mykel soþely as a knowne token ande merueyl es done þurghe hem, knowne vnto alle þo folkke þat dwellen in Ierusalem, ande we maye noghte denye hit.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.17" type="verse">Bot þat hit be no more 15pupplisched ne15 spoken amonge þo folkke, þrete we hem, þat þei in þat name speke nomore vnto any man.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.18" type="verse">Ande þei called hem 15unto hem15 , ande komawnded hem þat þei schulde nomore so speke, teche on no wise in Ihesu name.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.19" type="verse">Peter soþely ande Iohn ansuered and saide vnto hem, If hit is riȝtewise in þo sighte of God soner to
<seg id="b.ACT.4.1" type="verse">As þei stoden ande spaken vnto þe puple, þer kome fallande vnto hem prestes ande maisters of þo temple ande
<seg id="b.ACT.4.20" type="verse">here ȝowe þan God, telle vs; þat we hafe harde ande sene, we may noghte bot we hit speke.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.21" type="verse">Ande þei lefte hem wiþ many þretynges, dredande þo puple. No rightwise cause myghte þei finde hem forto punische, for alle spake hit ande made hit clere ande knowne, þat þinge þat bi hem was done, of þat þinge þat bifelle.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.22" type="verse">Þat man was of elde fourety ȝhere ande twoo more, whanne þis token ande þis hele was.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.23" type="verse">Ande whanne þei wore laten oute of þo kownseile to wende forþe þer way, þei komen vnto þer breþer þat wore conuerted, ande broghte hem worde, what kynnes þinges þo princes of prestes ande þo olde men hade vnto hem saide .
<seg id="b.ACT.4.24" type="verse">Whanne þei hit harde, þei lifte vppe þer voyce togider alle to God , ande saide, Lorde, þow þat madeste heuen ande erþe, þe see
<seg id="b.ACT.4.25" type="verse">ande alle þat in hem are : þat þurghe þo Holigoste, bi þo mowþe of oure fadire Dauid, þi childe , þow saideste, Whi grucched þo folke, ande þo puple þoghte vayn þinges?
<seg id="b.ACT.4.26" type="verse">Kenges of erþe stoden togider, ande princes komen alle in
<seg id="b.ACT.4.27" type="verse">one agayns oure Lorde ande agayns hise Criste: þei komen togider soþely in þis cyte agaynes þi holy childe Iesu, þat þow ennoyntedeste, Herowde ande Pounce Pilate wiþ meny
<seg id="b.ACT.4.28" type="verse">ande folke of Israel , to do þat þi honde ande þi cownseile discryued (20þat es, ordeynde) to be done20 .
<seg id="b.ACT.4.29" type="verse">Ande nowe, Lorde, biholde vnto þer þretynges, ande grawnte þi seruantes wiþ
<seg id="b.ACT.4.2" type="verse">Saduceys (þat wore relygyouse men) , maden grete sorowe þat þei tawghten þo puple ande schewed in Iesu þo
<seg id="b.ACT.4.30" type="verse">alle faiþefulnes to speke þi worde, in þat þow putte forþe þi honde; hele , merueiles ande wondures to be done for þo holy name of þi sone Iesu.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.31" type="verse">Ande whanne þei hade
<seg id="b.ACT.4.32" type="verse">O hertte ande o soule (5þat es, o wille) hade alle þat puple þat troweden togider5 . Ne none of hem þat any þinge hade saide hit was his, bot wore in comun vnto hem alle.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.33" type="verse">Ande wiþ grete vertewe þo apostul bare witnes of þo vprisinge of oure Lorde Iesu Criste: ande grete grace was in hem alle.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.34" type="verse">Ne was þer none nedy amonges hem: als many possessioners as þer wore of houses or of feldes solden hem, ande broghte þo price of hem þat þei
<seg id="b.ACT.4.35" type="verse">solde, ande putte hit bifore þo fete of þo apostuls: , Barsabas —þat
<seg id="b.ACT.4.37" type="verse">bitokens, sone of comforþe—he hade a felde, ande solde hit, ande broghte þo price, ande laide bifore þo apostuls fete .
<seg id="b.ACT.4.3" type="verse">risinge of deþe; ande layden hondes vpon hem, ande putte
<seg id="b.ACT.4.4" type="verse">hem in holde vnto þo toþer daye: þanne soþely hit was
<seg id="b.ACT.4.5" type="verse">Þo toþer day hit felle þat þer schulde be gadired togider þer
<seg id="b.ACT.4.6" type="verse">princes, þo olde men, ande þo wise of Ierusalem, ande Annas þo prince of prestes, ande Cayphas, ande Iohn, ande Alysawndure, ande als many as wore of þe prestes kinreden.
<seg id="b.ACT.4.7" type="verse">Ande put hem ymyddes hem alle, ande asched hem, In whatte vertewe &amp; in whos name did ȝhe þise þinges?
<seg id="b.ACT.4.8" type="verse">Thanne Peter, fulfilled of þo Holygoste, saide vnto hem, Princes of puple ande olde men, heres ande vndurstondes .
<seg id="b.ACT.4.9" type="verse">If we to daye ben demed in þo gode dede of þis
<seg id="b.ACT.5.10" type="verse">Ande alsfaste sche felle downe atte hise fete ande dyed: þo ȝonge men enterd inne ande fonde hire dead, ande toke hire vppe, ande biried hire biside hire husbande.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.11" type="verse">Ande þanne þer was grete drede in alle holy chirche, ande in alle þat hit harde.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.12" type="verse">Bi þo hondes soþely of þo apostuls were done many tokens ande merueyls in þo folke; ande þei wore alle togider in Salomons porte.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.13" type="verse">Soþely of alle þo toþer none durste ioyn hem vnto hem, bot myche þo puple hem praysed.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.14" type="verse">Þo multitude of hem þat preyde wexe euer more ande more, boþe of
<seg id="b.ACT.5.15" type="verse">men ande wymmen; so þat þei hade oute þo seke into þe feldes ande laide hem in þer couches ande in þer beddes in þo felde, þat whanne Peter kome, at þo leste his schadowe myghte ouer-schine iche of hem, ande so be deliuerde of þer sekenes.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.16" type="verse">Soþely þo multitude of neghburs of þo cite runnen togider in Ierusalem, berande þe seke, ande hem þat wore traueiled wiþ vnclene spirittes, þo whiche alle wore helud.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.17" type="verse">Thanne soþely þo prince of prestes rose vppe, ande alle þat wiþ hem wore, þo whiche es heresie of Saduceys (þat wore
<seg id="b.ACT.5.18" type="verse">religiowse) , ande wore fulfilled of enuy ande trecchery, ande layde hondes vpon þo apostuls, ande putte hem into a komun holde þat opunly was knowne.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.19" type="verse">Ande soþely onne þo nyghte one of Goddes awngels opunde þo ȝhates of þo
<seg id="b.ACT.5.1" type="verse">Soþely a man þat hatte Ananyas, ande hise wife Saphira,
<seg id="b.ACT.5.20" type="verse">prisone, ande ledde hem oute, ande saide, Gos, ande stondes in þo temple, ande spekes vnto þo puple alle þo wordes of þis life.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.21" type="verse">Ande whanne þei hade herde þis, þei enterde in þo mornynge into þo temple, ande tawghte . Whanne þo prince of prestes harde þis, ande þoo þat wore wiþ hym, þei called togider a konseile, ande alle þo eldeste men of þo sons of Israel, ande sende vnto þo prisone to bringe þo apostuls to hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.22" type="verse">Ande whanne þo mynistres soþely kome ande opunde þo prisone, þei fonde hem noghte. Bot turned agayne ande
<seg id="b.ACT.5.23" type="verse">tolde þo prince how þat hit was, ande saide, Forsoþe þo prisone we fonde faste sparred as hit was lefte, ande þo kepars stondinge at þo ȝhates: þei opunde þo prisone, ande no man fonde we þerinne.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.24" type="verse">Whanne þo maistres of þo temple ande þo princes of prestes herde þise wordes, þei vmþoghten hem, ande spake togider what was forto do of hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.25" type="verse">Ande þo whiles þer kome one ande broghte worde vnto hem, how þoo men þat þei putte in prisone ben in þo temple, ande 8stonden ande techen8 þo puple.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.26" type="verse">Thanne ȝode þo mayster wiþ his mynistres, ande ladde hem forþe wiþouten strenkþe: þei dredde þo puple, 9in auenture þat9 þei wolde stone hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.27" type="verse">Ande whanne þei hade ledde hem forþe, þei toke hem in a kownseyl. Ande þo prince of prestes
<seg id="b.ACT.5.28" type="verse">asched hem, ande saide, Wiþ comandmente we bid ȝowe, þat ȝhe ne teche noghte in þis name. Ande lo, ȝhe hafe fulfilled Ierusalem wiþ ȝoure techinge, ande ȝhe wil putte vpon vs þo blode of þis man (þat es, þo deþe of Criste).
<seg id="b.ACT.5.29" type="verse">12Peter ande þo apostuls12 ansuerde ande saide, More hit bihoues vs to be buxum vnto God þanne to men .
<seg id="b.ACT.5.2" type="verse">solden a felde , and wiþ þo konseile of hise wife wiþhelde a party of þo price, ande þo remnante broghte ande layde bifore þo apostuls fete.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.30" type="verse">God of ȝoure faders raised Iesu vnto lyfe, whom þat ȝhe slowen, hongande hym vpon a crosse.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.31" type="verse">Hym has God highed, ande made hym a prince ande sauyoure þurghe his righte honde, to gife penaunce vnto hem of Israel, ande forgifnes of þer synnes.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.32" type="verse">Ande we ben witnes of þise wordes; ande þo Holygoste whom God haues gifen vnto alle þat to hym ben buxum.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.33" type="verse">Whanne þat þei harde þis, þei ymagynde ande þoȝte in þer hertes to slee hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.34" type="verse">Ande soþely a Pharisew ros vp in þo kownseile,
<seg id="b.ACT.5.35" type="verse">gange oute a lytel, ande saide þanne vnto hem þat wore gadurd þere, Men of Israel, take hede vnto ȝowreseluen, of þise men whatte ȝhe þinke to do.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.36" type="verse">Bifore þise dais Theodas saide þat he was hymseluen grete; vnto whom assented folke, þo noumbre of men abouten foure hundreþe : þo whiche was slayne; ande alle þat to hym trowed wore disparpulde (þat es, wore spred obrode ande destroide) ande worþed vnto noghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.37" type="verse">After hym was þer an-oþer, Iudas of Galilee, in þo dais of profescion , ande myche puple he efter hym turned: and he perisched ; and als many as vnto hym assented wore sparpulde o-brode.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.38" type="verse">Ande nowe þerfore I say vnto ȝowe, Departes away fro þise men, ande suffers hem: for if þis conseile ande þis dede þat þei do be of man, hit
<seg id="b.ACT.5.39" type="verse">schal be vndone &amp; worþe vnto noghte: ande soþely if hit be of God, ȝhe schul noghte mowe vndo hem, bot suffure hem, in auenture þat ȝhe be not fownden fightande agayn God.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.3" type="verse">Ande Peter saide to hym, Anany, whi tempted Sathanas þi herte, þow forto lyghe vnto þo Holigoste, ande forto defraude of þo price of þo felde?
<seg id="b.ACT.5.40" type="verse">Forsoþe þei assented, ande called þo apostuls vnto hem , ande komawnded hem, þat þei schulde nomore speke in Iesu name, ande lete hem wende þer way.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.41" type="verse">Ande þei forsoþe ȝode ioyande oute of þo sighte of þo cownseile, for þat þei wore made worþi to suffur strife ande schame for þo name of Iesu.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.42" type="verse">Soþely euery day in þo temple &amp; abowte howses þei cessed noghte of techinge ande prechinge of Iesu Criste .
<seg id="b.ACT.5.4" type="verse">Ne was hit dwellande vnto þiseluen, ande þo sale was in þine owne power? Whi puttest þou þis dede in þine hertte? þow ne haues noghte lyed to man bot to God .
<seg id="b.ACT.5.5" type="verse">Soþely whanne Ananyas hade harde þise wordes, he felle downe &amp; dyed: ande grete drede was þer þanne amonge alle þat harde þeroffe.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.6" type="verse">Thanne ȝonge men ros vppe, ande bare hym away ande biried hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.7" type="verse">Efter-worde, as hit were þo space of þre houres, hise wife enterd inne, ande wiste not what was done.
<seg id="b.ACT.5.8" type="verse">Ande soþely Peter ansuered vnto hire, Say me, þow
<seg id="b.ACT.5.9" type="verse">Ande soþely Peter saide vnto hire, Wharto þoghte ȝhe hit acordande to ȝowe forto tempte þo Holygoste of God? Loo þo fete of hem þat biried þine howsebande at þo dore, ande schal bere forþe þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.10" type="verse">Ande þei myghte noghte wiþstonde his wytte ande þo spiritte þat wiþinne hym spake.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.11" type="verse">Thanne sende þei wiþ tresone men þat schulde saye, 17þat þei harde hym saye17 wordes of blaspheme of Moyses &amp; of God.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.12" type="verse">Þei stired ande moued alsso þo puple, &amp; þo olde men, ande þo wise, ande ran togider, ande token
<seg id="b.ACT.6.13" type="verse">hym, ande ledden hym into kownseyl; ande sette agayns hym þo fals witnes, sayande, Þis man cesses noghte to speke
<seg id="b.ACT.6.14" type="verse">wordes agayne holy place ande þo lawe: soþely we harde
<seg id="b.ACT.6.15" type="verse">Ande þei bihelde vpon hym alle þat in þo konseyl satte; þei sawe hise face as hit wore þe face of an awngel amonges hem .
<seg id="b.ACT.6.1" type="verse">Soþely in þo dais gretely wexe þo noumbure of þer disciples, ande was made a murmour ande a grucchinge of þo Grekes agaynes hem of Ebrewe, for þat þer widowes wore
<seg id="b.ACT.6.2" type="verse">Ande þanne called togider twelue þo nowmbur offe þo apostuls ande þo disciples , ande saide þus vnto hem, It es noghte righte þat we schul leue þo worde of God ande serue vnto þo bordes (þat es, atte þo mete).
<seg id="b.ACT.6.3" type="verse">Ande þerfore lokes amonge ȝowe, breþer, seuen gode men offe testymony ande wytnes, þo whiche ben ful of þo Holigoste ande wisdome, whom we schul ordeyne forto do þis bisines ande þis warke.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.4" type="verse">For we wole holde vs in preyer ande in Goddes worde.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.5" type="verse">Ande þis worde was plesinge vnto alle þo multitude , ande gladde were þer-offe. Ande þei ches Steuen, a man fulle of þo Holigoste ande trewe in þo faiþe, ande Philip, ande Prochorum, ande Nichanore, ande Tymothewe , ande Pernyenam , ande
<seg id="b.ACT.6.6" type="verse">Nicholas þat was komen fro Antiochen; þise þei sette bifore þo sighte of þo apostuls, &amp; made þer preyers, ande laide alle 12þer hende vpon hem12 .
<seg id="b.ACT.6.7" type="verse">Ande Goddes worde wexe; ande gretely was þo nowmbur of disciples waxen in Ierusalem. Grete company alsso of prestes bowden vnto þe faiþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.8" type="verse">Steuen, gostely fulle of grace ande strenkþe, did many merueyles ande wondurs amonge þo puple.
<seg id="b.ACT.6.9" type="verse">Summe soþely of þo synagoge risen vppe, þat was of Lybertynes, ande of Sirenences, ande of Alysawndur, ande of hem þat wore of Cilyce ande of Asye, disputande wiþ Steuen.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.10" type="verse">ande solde hym into Egipte: ande God was wiþ hym, ande hym delyuerde of alle hise tribulaciones, ande gafe hym grace ande wisdome in Pharaos sighte, þo kenge of Egipte; ande made hym guuernoure ande prouoste ouer Egipte ande ouer alle hise howse.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.11" type="verse">Bot soþely þer kome þanne a hungur in alle Egipte ande Canaan grete tribulacyone; ande ȝoure fadres fonde no mete.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.12" type="verse">Whanne Iacob harde þat whete was in Egipte, he sende firste oure fadres.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.13" type="verse">Ande þe secunde sonde he was knowen, Ioseph, of hise breþer, ande he schewed his kynreden vnto Pharao.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.14" type="verse">Ande Ioseph sende efter his fader, ande alle hise knowynge.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.15" type="verse">Ande Iacob so kome into
<seg id="b.ACT.7.16" type="verse">Egipte; ande he es deade, ande oure fadres; ande þei ben translated into Sichem, ande putte in þo sepulcur þat Abraham boghte wiþ price of siluer of þo sons of Emor, Sychem sons.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.17" type="verse">Soþely whanne þo tyme of biheste come nerehande , þat God tolde vnto Abraham, þo puple wexe
<seg id="b.ACT.7.18" type="verse">ande multiplied in Egipte, vnto þo tyme þat an-oþer kenge was þerinne , þat knewe noghte Ioseph.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.19" type="verse">He þis ouerȝode oure kynreden, ande tourmented oure fadres, ande ordeynde þat of oure ȝonge childer þat were þanne borne, þo knauechilde schulde not life.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.1" type="verse">Þo prince of þo prestes saide vnto Steuen, Es þis þinge soþe 8þat þise men sayne8 ?
<seg id="b.ACT.7.20" type="verse">Þo same tyme was Moises borne, &amp; plesinge vnto God; þo whiche þree moneþes was norysched
<seg id="b.ACT.7.21" type="verse">in hise owne fader howse: ande soþely he was putte forþe into þo flode, ande Pharaos doghter toke hym vppe, ande norysched hym as hit wore hire sone.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.22" type="verse">Ande Moyses was lerned of alle þo witte of Egipte; ande he was myghty in wordes ande in hise dedes.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.23" type="verse">Whanne hise tyme was fulfilled vnto fourty ȝhere, hit felle in hise hertte þat he wolde visite hise frendes, hise breþer of Israel.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.24" type="verse">Ande whanne þat he sawe one of hise kynne suffer grete wronge, he venged hym, ande wreked hym þat wronge suffurde, ande smote hym offe
<seg id="b.ACT.7.25" type="verse">Egipte: he wende hise breþer schulde haue vndurstonden, þat God þurghe hise hende schulde gife hele vnto hem; ande þei vnderstode hit noghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.26" type="verse">Soþely þo secunde daye he appered vnto hem striuande, ande reconseilde hem into pees, ande sayde, Men, ȝhe ben breþer; wharto noys eyþer of ȝowe oþer?
<seg id="b.ACT.7.27" type="verse">Soþely he þat did þe wronge vnto hise broþer, putte hym agayne, and saide, Who ordeynde þe prince or iustice ouer vs?
<seg id="b.ACT.7.28" type="verse">Þow wilte noghte slee me, as þow ȝisterday dideste þo man of Egipte?
<seg id="b.ACT.7.29" type="verse">Atte þis worde Moises fledde, ande was made a komelynge in þo lande of Madian, where he gate twey sons.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.2" type="verse">Ande he 8ansuered ande8 saide, Ȝhe men, my breþer ande faders, heres ande vndurstondes. God of ioye appered vnto Abraham oure fadire, whanne he was in Mesapotany, bifore þat he schulde dye in Charre, ande
<seg id="b.ACT.7.30" type="verse">Ande whanne fourty ȝhere wore fulfilled , an awngel appered vnto hym in þo deserte of mounte Synaye in flaumbe of fire in þo buske.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.31" type="verse">Moyses, whanne he hit sawe, of þat sighte he was awondurde: ande as he ȝode nerre forto biholde þerto, þo voyce of God spake vnto hym
<seg id="b.ACT.7.32" type="verse">ande saide, I am þo God of þi fadres, God of Abraham, of Isaac ande of Iacob. Moyses þanne trembulde ande durste nomore biholde.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.33" type="verse">God soþely saide vnto hym, Lowse þo schone of þi fete: þo place es holy þat þou stondes ynne.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.34" type="verse">Biholdande I sawe þo affliccione of my folke þat es in Egipte, ande þaire sorowynge I harde, ande I kome downe hem to delyuer: ande kome nowe, ande I schal sende þe into Egipte.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.35" type="verse">Þis Moises whom þei denyed, ande saide, Who ordeynde þe prince ande domes-man ouer vs? hym God sende prince ande byare wiþ þo awngel honde þat in þo buske appered vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.36" type="verse">He þis ledde hem oute, doande merueyles ande wondurs in þo lande of Egipte, ande in þo Rede See, ande in deserte fourty ȝhere.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.37" type="verse">Þis es Moises, þe whiche saide hit vnto þo childer of Israel, A prophete vnto ȝowe God schal raise of ȝoure owne breþeren, ande loke ȝhe here hym reghte as ȝhe do me.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.38" type="verse">He þis hit es þat was in þo chirche in wildernes wiþ þo awngel þat spake vnto hym in þo mownte of Synay, ande with oure fadires: þo whiche toke þo wordes
<seg id="b.ACT.7.39" type="verse">offe life to gife vnto vs: to whom oure faders wolden noghte
<seg id="b.ACT.7.3" type="verse">saide vnto hym, Gange oute of þi londe, ande oute of þi knowynge, ande kome into þat londe þat I schal schewe vnto þe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.40" type="verse">þer hertes vnto Egipte, sayand vnto Aaron, Make vs goddes þat may go bifore vs: he þis Moyses þat ledde vs oute of þo londe of Egipte, we woten noghte what es fallen vnto hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.41" type="verse">Ande in þo dais þei made a kalfe, ande offurde offeringes to þo symulacre (þat es, vnto þo mawmete). Ande þei made ioye in þo warke of þer hende.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.42" type="verse">Soþely God conuerted ande toke hem to serue to þo kengedome of heuen: as hit es writen in þo boke of þo prophetes, Þow , meny of Israel, sacrifice nor offuringes offurde ȝhe none vnto me fourty ȝere in deserte.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.43" type="verse">Ande ȝhe toke þo dwellynge-stede of Meloch ande þo sterne of ȝoure god Rempha, þat wore figures þat ȝhe made forto worschippe. Ande I schal transferre ȝowe into Babilony .
<seg id="b.ACT.7.44" type="verse">Þo tabernacle of testimony was to ȝoure fadire in deserte, God ordeynde, spekande vnto Moises, þat he schulde make hit efter þo schappe of þat þat he sawe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.45" type="verse">Þe whiche þei ledden in, oure faders into þo possession of gentiles, þo whiche God
<seg id="b.ACT.7.46" type="verse">putte away fro þo face of oure faders vnto þo dais of Dauid, þo whiche fonde grace bifore God, ande asched pat he myghte finde a tabernacle vnto God of Iacob.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.47" type="verse">Salomon soþely made
<seg id="b.ACT.7.48" type="verse">hym an howse; bot he þat es alþerhigheste dwelles noghte in þinges þat ben made wiþ hende; as he bi þo
<seg id="b.ACT.7.49" type="verse">prophete sais, Heuen es vnto me a sege, erþe soþely a stool vnto my fete: what howse schul ȝhe make to me? sais oure Lorde, or whiche es þo place þat I schal reste inne? Ne made noghte my hende alle þise þinges?
<seg id="b.ACT.7.4" type="verse">Thanne wente he oute of þo londe of Caldey, ande dwelled in Charram: ande þeþen , efter his fader was deade, he kome into þis londe, 8ande caried hise fader hider8 , where þat ȝhe dwelle nowe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.50" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.ACT.7.51" type="verse">Hardefrownted ande vncircumsised hertes ande eares, euer ȝhe han wiþstonden þo Holygoste: so as ȝoure faders did, so do ȝhe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.52" type="verse">For ȝoure fadirs, ne wore þei noghte pursewars of prophetes? ande þei slowe hem þat schewed bifore of þe komynge of þis rightwise man, of whom ȝe wore traytures ande manslears:
<seg id="b.ACT.7.53" type="verse">ȝe þat token þo lawe þat schulde haue disposed ȝow vnto awngels, ande ȝhe kepped hit noghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.54" type="verse">Ande whanne þei harden þis, þei saiden in þer hertes, ande gnaisted vpon hym wiþ þer teþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.55" type="verse">So whanne Stheuen was ful of þo Holigoste, he bihelde vppe into heuen ande sawe þo ioye of God, ande Iesu stondande atte þo righte side of his fadire, ande saide, Lo, I see heuens opun, ande mannes sone stondande at þo righte side of þe vertewe of God.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.56" type="verse">Þei crieden þanne alle lowde togider , 9ande stopped þer eres, ande þei alle togider
<seg id="b.ACT.7.57" type="verse">did lettynge vnto hym9 ; ande þanne þei cacched hym oute of þo cytee, ande stoned hym: ande þe two falsse wytnes did of hise cloþes biside þe fete of þo ȝonge man þat was called Saule.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.58" type="verse">Ande þi stoned Steuen, þat called ,
<seg id="b.ACT.7.59" type="verse">ande saide, Iesu , receyue my spiritte; ande kneled downe vpon hise knees, ande cried wiþ a lowde voyce, &amp; sais , Lorde, sette noghte þis synne agaynes hem . Ande whanne he hade saide þat, he rested hym in God, ande gafe vnto heuen his goste. Soþely Saule was assentande vnto his deþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.5" type="verse">Ande he gafe hym þerinne none heritage, nor o fote of erthe, ande he bihette forto gife hit vnto hym into hise possessione, ande til hise sede efter hym, whanne þat he hade no sone.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.6" type="verse">Soþely God saide vnto hym, þat hise sede schal hafe a wonynge anoþer londe, ande he schal make hem subgette to hise service, ande yuel he schal lede hem foure hundreþe ȝhere .
<seg id="b.ACT.7.7" type="verse">Ande ; ande efter þat þei schul wende heþen ande serue me in þis place.
<seg id="b.ACT.7.8" type="verse">Ande he gafe vnto hym þo testamente of circumsicyon: ande so he gate Isaac, ande circumsiced hym þo eghtod daye; and Isaac Iacob, ande Iacob þo twelue
<seg id="b.ACT.7.9" type="verse">Ande þo patriarches haden enuye vnto Ioseph,
<seg id="b.ACT.8.10" type="verse">was a god: ande alle hym herkende, fro þo leeste vnto þo meeste , sayande, He þis es þo vertewe of God þat es called Maga .
<seg id="b.ACT.8.11" type="verse">Þei 12gafe tente vnto12 hym, wharfore longe tyme wiþ hise fals craftes he made hem wode.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.12" type="verse">Bot soþely whanne þei schulde haue trowed vnto Philippe, prechinge vnto hem of þo kengdome of heuen in þo name of Iesu , þere wore baptized many men ande wymmen.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.13" type="verse">14Þanne trowed he þat Symon14 ; ande 15whanne he schulde be baptised, he drowe hym vnto Philippe; ande15 whanne he sawe þo vertewes ande þo wondurs þat bi Philippe wore done, þerfore he was amerueylde wondurfully.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.14" type="verse">Whan þo apostuls hade harde þat Samary hade receyued Goddes worde, þei sende vnto hem Peter ande Ioon.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.15" type="verse">Ande whanne þei wore komen, þei preyed for hem þat wore turned, þat þei myghte take þo Holygoste:
<seg id="b.ACT.8.16" type="verse">ȝitte he kome noghte into iche of hem, bot only þei wore baptized in þo name of Iesu, oure Lorde.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.17" type="verse">Þanne putten þei þer hende vpon hem, ande þanne þei token þo Holygoste.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.18" type="verse">Whanne þat Symon hade sene þat þurghe þo puttynge to one of þo apostuls hende þo Holygoste was gifen vnto hem,
<seg id="b.ACT.8.19" type="verse">he profured hem money, ande saide, Haue þis, ande gife me þat power, þat whom I putte vpon my honde, he schal haue þo Holygoste.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.1" type="verse">Soþely þat daye was grete persecucione done in holy chirche þat was atte Ierusalem; ande alle þei wore disparpulde ande wente isonder bi þo kendames of Iurye ande Samary, outtaken þo apostuls þat dwelled stille in Ierusalem.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.20" type="verse">Ande Peter soþely ansuered hym &amp; saide, Þi money ande þi catelle be with þe in dampnacyon, for þow troweste þat þe gifte of God wiþ money myghte be boghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.21" type="verse">Neþer þow haueste parte ne lote in þis worde: for soþely þi hertte es noghte rightwise bifore God.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.22" type="verse">Ande þerfore do penaunce for þi wikkednes, ande preye þanne God, in auenture þat he wole forgife þe þis wikked þoghte of þine hertte.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.23" type="verse">For soþely in galle of bitternes ande in bonde of wikkednes I see þat þow erte.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.24" type="verse">Þanne soþely Symon ansuered &amp; saide, Preye ȝhe vnto God for me, þat none of alle þise falle vpon me whiche þat ȝhe haue sayde.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.25" type="verse">Ande þei soþely witnessed ande spaken Goddes worde, ande ȝede vnto Ierusalem agayne; ande many kengedams of Samarytanes 10tawghten þei ande10 preched.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.26" type="verse">An aungel of God vnto Philippe saide , ande spake, Rise, ande wende to meridiane, vnto þo way þat gos downe fro Ierusalem into Gaȝam , þat es a deserte place.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.27" type="verse">Ande vppe he ros ande ȝede; ande þer he mette wiþ a man of Ethiopes, þat was a myghty man wiþ a qweene of Candacis of Ethiopes, þo whiche was ouer alle hire tresure, ande was a geldynge þat hade hire in kepinge; he
<seg id="b.ACT.8.28" type="verse">kome to worschippe ande forto preye in Ierusalem: ande he was turned agayne, sittande vpon hise charre, redande Ysay þo prophete.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.29" type="verse">Ande þo spiritte sayde vnto Philippe, Kome nerre, ande ioyne þe to þis carte.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.2" type="verse">Men ful dredfulle biried saynte Steuen, ande made grete wepinge ande sorowe ouer hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.30" type="verse">Ande Philippe ranne þerto, ande harde hym redande Isaye þo prophete, ande he saide, Trowes þow, þat þow vndurstondes noghte þat þow redes?
<seg id="b.ACT.8.31" type="verse">Ande he saide, How myghte I , bot if any hade tawghte hit me? Ande he preyde Philippe, þat he wolde kome vppe ande sytte wiþ hym.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.32" type="verse">Þo place þat he redde of was þis in þat prophecye, As a schepe vnto þo slawghter was he ledde, ande as a lombe bifore þo clippar wiþouten voice, so he opunde not hise mowþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.33" type="verse">In meknes he bare his dome awaye ande his rightwise vengeance: hise generacyone who schal hit telle? For his life es taken awaye oute of erþe.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.34" type="verse">Þo geldynge 4ansuered agayne ande sayde vnto Philyppe4 , I preye þe, of what prophete sais he þis? of hym-seluen, or of an -oþer?
<seg id="b.ACT.8.35" type="verse">Þanne soþely Philyppe tawghte hym, ande declared, bigynnande atte þat place þat he redde of þo prophecye, ande tolde hym of Iesus.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.36" type="verse">Ande þo whileste þei kome by þo waye, þei kome vnto a water; ande 9þanne saide þo geldynge, Lo, here es water9 , ande who schal lette me here to be baptised?
<seg id="b.ACT.8.37" type="verse">Ande Philippe saide vnto hym, If þow trowe wiþ alle þine hertte, hit es leffulle vnto þe. Ande he ansuered ande saide, I trowe þat Iesu Criste es Goddes son.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.38" type="verse">Ande he comawnded þo carte to stonde, &amp; boþe þei ȝode downe into þo water, Philippe ande he , ande þer he baptised hym .
<seg id="b.ACT.8.39" type="verse">Soþely whan þei wore wente vp oute of þo water þo spirytte of God rauysched Philippe away; &amp; after sawe he hym nomore. He ȝode soþely bi þo waye makande ioye.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.3" type="verse">Saule forsoþe wastud holi chirche ande destroyde hit , ande ȝode into howses, ande drowe oute men ande wymmen, ande putte hem into holde .
<seg id="b.ACT.8.40" type="verse">Ande Philippe was fownden soþely in Aȝoto , þat was an-oþer cyte; ande þer he ȝode abowte prechande vnto alle cytes, tille he kome to Cesarye.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.4" type="verse">Ande þei þerfore þat wore spredde obrode ȝode
<seg id="b.ACT.8.5" type="verse">Philippe ȝode into þo cyte of Samarye, ande preched Criste vnto hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.6" type="verse">Þo folke soþely gafe gode hede vnto þo wordes þat Philippe saide, herande hym holly togider ande alle wiþ o wille, ande bihelde vnto þo wonders ande tokens whiche þat he wroghte.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.7" type="verse">Many soþely of hem þat haden in hem yuel spirittes cryed wiþ grete voyce ande ȝode awaye oute of hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.8" type="verse">Many þat haden þo palsy, ande alsso þat woren crokude, woren maked alle hole.
<seg id="b.ACT.8.9" type="verse">Ande þerfore was þer maked grete ioye in þat cite. Symon soþely Magus , þat was bifore in þat cite, made hymseluen grete as a god, ande many folke of Samarye hade he deceyued ande saide hem forsoþe þat he
<seg id="b.ACT.9.10" type="verse">þer was a disciple in Damaske þat hatte Ananyas; ande God sayd to hym in vision, Anany. Ande he saide, Lo , Lorde, I am here.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.11" type="verse">Ande oure Lorde saide unto hym , Rise, ande wende vnto þo way þat es called Rectus, ande seche Saule in Iudas howse, whos name es Tharsen: for lo, þer he preys;
<seg id="b.ACT.9.12" type="verse">ande he sawe þo man þat hatte Anany enterande into þo howse, ande puttande hise hondes vnto hym, þat he myghte receyue his syghte .
<seg id="b.ACT.9.13" type="verse">Ande Ananyas ansuered ande saide, Lorde , I hafe harde of many of þis man, how many
<seg id="b.ACT.9.14" type="verse">harmes he haues done vnto þi sayntes in Ierusalem: ande he haues powere of þo princes of prestes to bynde alle hem 19þat ben þi name oknowe19 .
<seg id="b.ACT.9.15" type="verse">Ande soþely oure Lorde sayde vnto hym, Go forþe, for he es maked vnto me a vessel of choos forto bere my name bifore kenges ande folke, ande bifore þo childer of Israel.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.16" type="verse">Ande soþely I schalle schewe hym how many þinges hym bihoues for my name suffure .
<seg id="b.ACT.9.17" type="verse">Ande Ananyas ȝode, ande enterde into þo howse, ande putte hise hondes vnto hym, &amp; sai , Saule, broþer, oure Lorde Ihesus þat appered to þe in þo waye þat þow kome, sende me vnto þe, þat þou haue þi syghte, ande be fulfilled of þo Holy Goste.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.18" type="verse">Ande alssone þer felle fro his eyghne slyme as hit wore þo skales of a fische; &amp; so he receyued his sighte,
<seg id="b.ACT.9.19" type="verse">ande ros vppe, ande was baptized; ande he was gretelyche comforþed whanne he hade taken mete. Ande þan soþely a fewe days he dwelled at Damaske wiþ þo disciples.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.1" type="verse">Saule alwaye þrette ande wayted Goddes discipuls; he
<seg id="b.ACT.9.20" type="verse">Ande anone Poule ȝode into þo synagoges, ande preched Iesu þat he es verray Goddes sone.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.21" type="verse">Ande alle þei wore ameruelde soþely þat hym harde, ande sayden, Ne was noghte he þis he þat in Ierusalem wiþstode hem þat wore þis name oknowe ? ande þerto he kome hider to lede hem bownden vnto þo princes of 9þo lawe þat ben prynces of9 prestes.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.22" type="verse">Ande Poule myche þo more he encresched, ande confunded þo Iewes þat dwelden atte Damaske, wele affermande þat he was Criste.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.23" type="verse">Ande whanne he hade þer many days fulfilled,
<seg id="b.ACT.9.24" type="verse">þo Iewes token cownseyl hym forto slee: ande soþely þer deceytes wore tolde vnto Poule. Ande þei kepped þo ȝates boþe daye ande nyghte of þo cyte, to wayte hym forto slee;
<seg id="b.ACT.9.25" type="verse">ande þo disciples token hym bi nyghte, ande leten hym downe bi þo walle in a bere-lepe.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.26" type="verse">&amp; soþely whanne he vnto Ierusalem kome, he drowe hym towarde þo discipuls; ande alle þei wore of hym aferde, noghte knowande how he was Goddes discipul.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.27" type="verse">Bot Barnabas soþely toke hym, ande ledde hym 9to þo disciples ande9 to þo apostuls , ande tolde hem alle how in þo waye he hade sene Godde, ande how þat he spake wiþ hym, &amp; how faiþefully he hade done in Damaske in þo name of Iesu.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.28" type="verse">Ande he was wiþ hem wendande in ande oute in Ierusalem, ande trewly doynge in þo name of Iesu.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.29" type="verse">Ande vnto þo gentyles he spake, ande disputed wiþ þo Grekes; &amp; 13þei soghten faste aboute hym forto slee13 .
<seg id="b.ACT.9.2" type="verse">kome vnto þo prince of prestes, ande asched of hym pistels ande comyssions into Damaske vnto þo synagoges, þat whomsoeuer he fonde of þo company of þe apostuls or hemseluen, men or wymmen, to brynge hem bownden vnto Ierusalem.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.30" type="verse">&amp; whanne þo breþer knewne þat, vpon þo nyȝte to Cesarye
<seg id="b.ACT.9.31" type="verse">Þanne holy chirche þurghe alle þo Iurye ande Galyle ande Samarye hade pees, ande was gretely edified, wendande in þo drede of God, ande was fulfilled in komforþe of þo Holygoste.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.32" type="verse">Ande Peter, whanne he hade passed alle þo kontres abowte, ande schulde kome to þo holy folke þat wore dwellynge at
<seg id="b.ACT.9.33" type="verse">Lydde, he fonde þer a man whos name was Eneam, þat fro he was eghte ȝhere olde hade lyne bedreden .
<seg id="b.ACT.9.34" type="verse">Ande Peter saide vnto hym, Enea, oure Lorde Iesu Criste hele þe , rise vppe fro þi bedde.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.35" type="verse">Ande he anone rose vppe. &amp; alle þei hym sawe þat atte Lydde dwelled ande Saron, þat wore conuerted vnto God.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.36" type="verse">In Ioppen forsoþe þer was a discipul, a womman þat hatte Tabita, þat propur name es Dorcas: þo whiche was ful 10of almes ande of gode dedes10 þat sche vnto many dide.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.37" type="verse">Ande on a day hit bifelle, þat sche wexe seke ande died. Whanne þei hire hade waschen, þei layde hire in þer halle.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.38" type="verse">Ande soþely so as þat cyte Lydde was nere þo towne of Ioppen, þo disciples harden telle how Peter was þerynne; þei sende tweyne vnto hym, preynge hym noghte forto dwelle, bot faste to kome vnto hem. Ande saynte Peter ros vppe ande ȝode forþe wiþ hem.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.39" type="verse">Ande whanne saynte Peter was komen, þei ledden hym into þo synacle , ande alle þo wydowes stoden aboute hym ande wepped, ande schewed hym þo cloþes ande þo kotes þat Dorcas hade hem made.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.3" type="verse">Ande as he ȝode þiderworde, hit bifelle þat he kome nere Damaske: ande sodenly þer come a wondurful
<seg id="b.ACT.9.40" type="verse">Ande Peter maked hem alle forto wende forþe, ande he kneled downe ande preyed, ande turned hym vnto þo deade body ande saide, Thabita, surge (þat es, Thabita rise). Ande atte his worde sche opund hire eyne;
<seg id="b.ACT.9.41" type="verse">ande whan sche sawe Peter sche toke hym hire honde, ande he raised hire vppe. Ande þanne he called þo sayntes ande þo wydowes, &amp; schewed hem þat sche was on lyue.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.42" type="verse">Ande
<seg id="b.ACT.9.43" type="verse">anne Peter longe tyme ande manye dais efter dwelled in Ioppen wiþ a man þat hatte Symonde, corueser.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.4" type="verse">lyghte alle aboute hym fro heuen, ande he felle downe vnto þo erþe, ande harde a voyce sayande vnto hym, Saule, Saule, wherto pursewes þow me?
<seg id="b.ACT.9.5" type="verse">Ande he saide, Who erte þow, Lorde? Ande þo voyce saide vnto hym, I am Iesus of Nazareth whom þat þow pursewes: hit es ful harde to þe to kese agayne þo prikke.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.6" type="verse">Ande he qwakande ande dredfulle saide, Lorde, what wilte þow þat I do?
<seg id="b.ACT.9.7" type="verse">Ande oure Lorde saide vnto hym, Rise, ande wende into þo cytee, ande þer hit schal be tolde þe, what þat 4þe bus4 do. Soþely þo men þat wore sende wiþ hym stoden alle mased, a voyce soþely þei harde, bot no man þei sawe.
<seg id="b.ACT.9.8" type="verse">Saule þanne soþely ros vppe fro þe erþe, opunde hise eyne, ande loked aboute , bot no man he sawe. Þei drowe hym forþe bi þo hende,
<seg id="b.ACT.9.9" type="verse">ande ledde hym into Damaske; ande þer he was þree days wiþouten sighte ande noþer ete nor dranke.
<seg id="b.COL.1.10" type="verse">, þat ȝe walkeþ worþilyche, plesynge God by alle þinges, &amp; makynge fruyt in eferich good werk, &amp; waxynge in
<seg id="b.COL.1.11" type="verse">þe knowynge of God in eferich vertu; &amp; y-comforted þoroȝ þe power of his clernesse, in eferich pacyence &amp; longanymyte
<seg id="b.COL.1.12" type="verse">wiþ ioye; þankynge God þe Fader, þat haþ y-mad ous worþi
<seg id="b.COL.1.13" type="verse">in-to þe party of þe sort of goode men in lyȝt; þat haþ delyfered ous from þe power of darknesse, &amp; haþ y-broȝt ous
<seg id="b.COL.1.14" type="verse">in-to þe kyngdom of þe Sone of his lofe; in whom we habbeþ
<seg id="b.COL.1.15" type="verse">forbuggynge, &amp; forȝefenesse of oure synnes: and he is þe ymage of God þat is in-visybel, &amp; he is þe furste bygeten
<seg id="b.COL.1.16" type="verse">For in hym beþ alle þinges y-mad, in hefne &amp; in erþe, boþe þinges þat mowen ben y-seye, &amp; invisybel þinges, wheþer it ben thrones oþer lordschypes oþer pryncypatees oþer myȝtes; alle þinges beþ y-maad in
<seg id="b.COL.1.17" type="verse">hym, &amp; þoroȝ hym; &amp; he is to-foren alle þinges, and alle þinges beþ in hym.
<seg id="b.COL.1.18" type="verse">&amp; he is hed of þe body, of holy churche: &amp; he is þe bygynnynge, &amp; þe furst bygeten chyld of dede men; þat he holde þe furste dygnyte among alle þinges.
<seg id="b.COL.1.19" type="verse">For
<seg id="b.COL.1.20" type="verse">it plesed God þat eferich fulnesse dwelled in hym; &amp; þat alle þinges weren reconcyled by hym to hym-selfen, makynge a pees þoroȝ þe blod of his cros, boþe to þilke þinges þat beþ in erþe, oþer in hefne.
<seg id="b.COL.1.21" type="verse">And ȝe, whan ȝe weren sumtyme y-alyened &amp; y-mynused in wyt in efel werkes, now he haþ
<seg id="b.COL.1.22" type="verse">reconsyled ȝow in þe body of his flesch þoroȝ deþ , to ȝelde ȝow
<seg id="b.COL.1.23" type="verse">holy &amp; wiþ-outen wem &amp; wiþ-outen reprefe to-fore hym: so ȝif þat ȝee dwelleþ stylle, y-founded in þe feiþ, stabel and im-mebel from þe hope of þe euangelye þat ȝe han y-herd, þat haþ ben y-preched in alle þe creatures þat beþ vnder hefne; of whuche euangelye y Poule am y-mad mynystre,
<seg id="b.COL.1.24" type="verse">þat ioye nouþe in my suffrynges for ȝou, &amp; fulfille in my flesch þilke þat wanteþ of þe passyones of Crist
<seg id="b.COL.1.25" type="verse">for his body, þat is holy churche; of whom ich am y-mad mynystre, after þe dispesacyoun of God þat is y-graunted to me in ȝow, þat y fulfille þe word of God
<seg id="b.COL.1.26" type="verse">&amp; þe mysterye þat haþ ben y-hud from worldes &amp; from kynredes.
<seg id="b.COL.1.27" type="verse">Bote now it is y-schewed to goode men, to whom God wolde y-knowe þe richesse of þe blisse of þis sacrement, þat is Crist, in hem þat weren mysbylefed men,
<seg id="b.COL.1.28" type="verse">þat is in ȝow hope of blisse: whom we scheweþ, amendynge eferich man, &amp; techynge in eferich wysdom, þat we ȝelden
<seg id="b.COL.1.29" type="verse">eferich man parfyt in Iesu Crist; in whom y trauayle, fyȝtynge aftur þe worchynge of hym, þat he worcheþ in me in vertu.
<seg id="b.COL.1.9" type="verse">Suster , to þe Colocenses seynt Poule wryteþ &amp; seiþ, From þe day þat we han y-herd of ȝow, we ne cesseþ noȝt for-to preyen &amp; to bysechen God for ȝow, þat ȝe ben fulfylled wiþ þe knowynge of his wil &amp; eferich wysdom &amp; spirytual vnderstondynge,
<seg id="b.COL.2.10" type="verse">hym dwelleþ eferich fulnesse of þe Godhed bodylyche, &amp; ȝe beþ fulfylled in hym, þat is hed of eferich pryncypate &amp;
<seg id="b.COL.2.11" type="verse">potestat: in whom ȝe beþ circumsyded þoroȝ circumsyscyoun, þat ne is noȝt y-maad wiþ honden, in spoylynge of þe body of
<seg id="b.COL.2.12" type="verse">flesch, in þe cyrcumscysyoun of Iesu Crist; ȝe beþ y-buryed to-gedere wiþ hym þoroȝ baptysme, in whom ȝe han a-rysen up from deþ to lyf by þe feiþ of þe worchynge of God, þat a-rered hym up from deþ to lyfe.
<seg id="b.COL.2.13" type="verse">And ȝe, whanne ȝe weren dede in ȝoure synnes, &amp; in þe prepucye of ȝoure flesch, he haþ y-mad ȝou lyfe to-gedere wiþ hym, forȝeuenge ȝou ȝoure
<seg id="b.COL.2.14" type="verse">synnes; &amp; doynge a-wey þe wrytynge of þe decre þat was a-ȝeyn ȝow, &amp; toke it a-wey from ȝow, þat was contrarye to
<seg id="b.COL.2.15" type="verse">ȝow, hongynge hym on þe cros; and spoylynge principatees &amp; potestates, ladde ofer trustylyche, ofercomynge hem openlyche in hym-selfen .
<seg id="b.COL.2.16" type="verse">And þerfore no man deme ȝow in mete , ne in drynke, ne in party of þe feste day, oþer of
<seg id="b.COL.2.17" type="verse">neo-mene , oþer of sabotes: þat beþ a schadewe of þinges þat beþ to comen; bote þe body of Crist.
<seg id="b.COL.2.18" type="verse">No man bygyle ȝow, þat wole walken in þe humelnesse &amp; in þe relygyoun of angeles, þat he ne haþ noȝt y-seyn, þat is veynlyche y-blowe
<seg id="b.COL.2.19" type="verse">þoroȝ þe wyt of his flesch, &amp; ne halt noȝt þe hed, of whom al
<seg id="b.COL.2.1" type="verse">And ich wole þat ȝe wyten what bisynesse ich hafe for ȝow, &amp; for hem þat beþ at Laudycye, &amp; alle þilke þat ne
<seg id="b.COL.2.20" type="verse">And ȝef ȝe beþ dede wiþ Crist from þe elementes of þis worlde, whar-to deme ȝe ȝet as men þat lyfeþ in þe worlde?
<seg id="b.COL.2.21" type="verse">Ne touche ȝe noȝt, ne taste ȝe
<seg id="b.COL.2.22" type="verse">noȝt, ne trete ȝe noȝt alle þilke þinges, þat beþ by þe pure vse
<seg id="b.COL.2.23" type="verse">of hem in-to deþ, aftur mennes hestes &amp; hure techynges; þat haueþ þe resoun of wysdom in supersticyoun &amp; in humelnesse, &amp; noȝt for-to spare þe body, ne in no manere worschupe to hele of þe flesch.
<seg id="b.COL.2.2" type="verse">hafeþ noȝt yseye my vysage in flesch; þat hure hertes ben
<seg id="b.COL.2.3" type="verse">mysterye of God þe Fader of Iesu Crist, in whom beþ alle þe tresoures y-hud of wysdom &amp; of connynge.
<seg id="b.COL.2.4" type="verse">&amp; þis y seye, þat no man bygyle ȝow in hyȝenesse of wordes.
<seg id="b.COL.2.5" type="verse">For þouȝ ich be absent from ȝow in body, ich am present wiþ ȝow in spiryt, ioyynge &amp; seynge ȝoure order, &amp; þe sadnesse of ȝoure feiþ þat is in Crist.
<seg id="b.COL.2.6" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ȝef ȝe han vnderfongen oure Lord Iesu
<seg id="b.COL.2.7" type="verse">Crist, walke ȝe in hym, y-roted &amp; y-buld in hym, &amp; y-confermed in þe feiþ, as ȝe han y-lerned, beynge plentefous in doynge þankynges to God.
<seg id="b.COL.2.8" type="verse">And loke ȝe þat no man bygyle ȝow by prophecye &amp; veyn fallas, aftur mennes tradycyones,
<seg id="b.COL.2.9" type="verse">after þe elementes of þis worlde, &amp; noȝt after Crist: for in
<seg id="b.COL.3.10" type="verse">olde man wiþ his dedes, &amp; cloþeþ ȝow wiþ a newe man, wiþ hym þat is renewed in þe knowynge of God aftur þe ymage
<seg id="b.COL.3.11" type="verse">of hym þat haþ y-schaped hym: wher ne is noȝ male &amp; femal, Iew &amp; Gentyl, circumscysyoun &amp; prepucye, vncouþe man &amp; couþ man, bonde man &amp; fre man: bote alle þynges in alle þynges Crist.
<seg id="b.COL.3.12" type="verse">&amp; þerfore cloþeþ ȝow as holy men &amp; derlynges, þat beþ y-chosen of God, þe inwardnesse of mercy,
<seg id="b.COL.3.13" type="verse">benygnyte, humelnesse, softnesse, pacyence; supportynge eferich man oþer, &amp; forȝefynge eferich man oþer, ȝif eny man haþ eny playnt aȝeyn eny of ȝou; &amp; riȝt as God haþ forȝeuen
<seg id="b.COL.3.14" type="verse">ȝou, so do ȝe: and abofen alle þese þinges haue ȝe charite,
<seg id="b.COL.3.15" type="verse">&amp; þe pees of Crist ioye in ȝoure hertes, in þe whuche pes ȝe beþ y-cleped in on body; &amp; be ȝe kynde.
<seg id="b.COL.3.16" type="verse">Þe word of Crist dwelle in ȝow in eferich wysdom plenteuouslyche, techynge &amp; warnynge ȝow-selfe in psalmes , ympnys &amp; spirytual songes, in grace syngynge in ȝoure hertes to God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.17" type="verse">And alle þinge what-efer ȝe don, in word oþer in dede, alle þinges do ȝe in þe name of oure Lord Iesu Crist, doynge þankynges to God &amp; to þe Fader þorow hym.
<seg id="b.COL.3.18" type="verse">And ȝe wymmen, be ȝe sogetes to ȝoure housbondes, as it byhofeþ in oure Lord.
<seg id="b.COL.3.19" type="verse">And ȝe men, lofe ȝe ȝoure wyfes, &amp; ne be ȝe not bytter to hem.
<seg id="b.COL.3.1" type="verse">And þerfore ȝef ȝe han a-resen up to-gedere wiþ Crist, secheþ þilke þinges þat beþ abofen, þere as Crist is syttynge in þe ryȝt syde of God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.20" type="verse">Chyldren, be ȝe buxom to ȝoure eldren by alle þinges, for þat is plesynge to God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.21" type="verse">And ȝe fadres, ne stere ȝe noȝt ȝoure chyldren to indyngnacyoun, þat þey ne be noȝt y-maad of smal soule.
<seg id="b.COL.3.22" type="verse">And ȝe serfauntes, be ȝe buxom to ȝoure fleschlyche lordes by alle þinges, noȝt serfynge at þe yȝe, as plesynge to men, bote in sympelnesse
<seg id="b.COL.3.23" type="verse">of herte, dredynge oure Lord: &amp; what-efer ȝe doþ, doþ it
<seg id="b.COL.3.24" type="verse">wylfullyche, as to oure Lord God, &amp; noȝt to men; knowynge þat of oure Lord ȝe schulleþ vnderfonge a rewardynge of herytage: serfe ȝe to Crist þat is God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.25" type="verse">For he þat doþ wrong schal receyfen þat he haþ yuel y-don: &amp; þer ne is non vnderfongynge of mennes persones to-fore God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.2" type="verse">And safere ȝe þilke þinges þat beþ a-bofen, &amp; noȝt þilke þinges þat beþ up-on þe erþe.
<seg id="b.COL.3.3" type="verse">For ȝe ben dede, &amp; ȝoure lyf is hud wiþ Crist in God.
<seg id="b.COL.3.4" type="verse">And when þat Crist appereþ, ȝoure lyf, þanne schulle ȝe appere wiþ hym in blysse.
<seg id="b.COL.3.5" type="verse">&amp; þerfore mortifye ȝe ȝoure membres þat beþ up-on þe erþe, as fornycacyoun, vnclannesse, lykynge fleschlyche, efel coueytynge, &amp; coueytyse, þat is seruyse of mawmetes;
<seg id="b.COL.3.6" type="verse">for whuche þinges þat wraþþe of God com in-to þe
<seg id="b.COL.3.7" type="verse">children of mys-trust &amp; of vnbylefe; in þe walkeden sumtyme, whyles þat ȝe lyfeden in hem.
<seg id="b.COL.3.8" type="verse">Bote do ȝe now a-wey from ȝou alle þinges, wraþþe, indygnacyoun, malyce, blasphemye , foule wordes ne passe noȝt forþ out of
<seg id="b.COL.3.9" type="verse">ȝoure mouþ: ne lye ȝe noȝt to-gedere, bote spoyleþ ȝow of þe
<seg id="b.COL.4.1" type="verse">And ȝe lordes, þat is efene &amp; riȝtful doþ to ȝoure serfauntes, knowynge þat ȝe habbeþ also a Lord in hefene.
<seg id="b.COL.4.2" type="verse">And be ȝe in ȝoure
<seg id="b.COL.4.3" type="verse">preyeres, &amp; wake ȝe in doynge þankynges to God, preyenge to-gedere &amp; for ous also, þat God opene to ous þe dore of his speche, to speke þe mysterye of Crist, wherfore ich am
<seg id="b.COL.4.4" type="verse">y-bounde; þat y schewe it openlyche, so as it byhofeþ me for-to speken.
<seg id="b.COL.4.5" type="verse">Walke ȝe in wysdom to þilke þat beþ wiþouten-forþ, forbuggynge þe tyme.
<seg id="b.COL.4.6" type="verse">And ȝoure word in grace be y-safered wiþ salt, þat ȝe knowen how it byhofeþ ȝow to answeren eferich man.
<seg id="b.COL.4.7" type="verse">And þilke þinges þat beþ aboute me, Tyte, my broþer schal make ȝow knowe, þat is a trewe
<seg id="b.COL.4.8" type="verse">serfaunt &amp; serfaunt wiþ me in oure Lord: hym ich haue y-sent to ȝou for þis enchesoun, þat he knowe how it is wiþ ȝou &amp; coumforte ȝoure hertes.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.10" type="verse">&amp; he þat com doun is he þat steyȝ up a-bofen alle hefenes to fulfullen alle þinges.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.11" type="verse">&amp; he ordeynede summe men aposteles; &amp; summe prophetes; &amp; summe euangelistes; &amp; oþer schepherdes &amp;
<seg id="b.EPH.1.12" type="verse">techeres in-to þe ende of þe worldes; &amp; in-to þe werke of
<seg id="b.EPH.1.13" type="verse">mynystrynge in-to þe buyldynge of þe body of Cryst: forto þat we comen alle to-gedere in vnyte of feiþ, &amp; of þe knowynge of Godes Sone, in-to a parfyt man , in-to þe mesure of þe age of þe fulnesse of Crist.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.14" type="verse">Þat we ne ben noȝt nouþe smale children, fletynge abrood, ne ben noȝt y-boren aboute with eferych wynd of techynge, in þe wykkednesse of men, in gyle,
<seg id="b.EPH.1.15" type="verse">to þe deceyt of errour; bote do we trewþe in charite, &amp; waxe
<seg id="b.EPH.1.16" type="verse">we in hym þoroȝ alle þinges, þat is oure hed, Crist; of whom al þe body is y-knyt to-geder by eferich myȝt of mynystrynge, þoroȝ worchynge in mesure of eferich membre, þat makeþ þe waxynge of þe body in þe buyldynge of hym in charyte.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.17" type="verse">And þerfore y sey ȝow, &amp; wytnesse to ȝow in oure Lord, þat ȝe ne walkeþ noȝt nouþe as mysbylefed men, þat walkeþ in
<seg id="b.EPH.1.18" type="verse">vanyte of hure wyt, hauynge a derke vnderstondynge y-mad darke þoroȝ darknesse, &amp; beþ alyened from þe wey of God, þoroȝ þe vnkunnyngenesse þat is in hem, for þe blyndenesse
<seg id="b.EPH.1.19" type="verse">of hure hertes; and þei dispeyrynge han y-taken hem-selfen to vnclannesse, in worchynge of eferyche vnclannesse in-to couetyse.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.1" type="verse">To þe Epheses, suster, he wryteþ, &amp; sayþ, Y þat am y-bounden in oure Lord, pray ȝou þat ȝe walken worþilyche
<seg id="b.EPH.1.20" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.EPH.1.21" type="verse">Bote ȝe ne haueþ not so y-lernyd Crist; &amp; ȝif ȝe han y-herd hym, &amp; beþ y-tauȝt in hym, as trewþe is in Iesu:
<seg id="b.EPH.1.22" type="verse">do ȝe a-wey ȝoure olde conuersacyoun, &amp; þe olde man þat
<seg id="b.EPH.1.23" type="verse">is corrupt þoroȝ þe desyres of errour; &amp; be ȝe renewed in þe
<seg id="b.EPH.1.24" type="verse">spyryt of ȝoure þouȝt, &amp; cloþeþ ȝow wiþ a newe man, þat is y-schape orouȝ God in ryȝtfulnesse &amp; in holynesse of trewþe.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.25" type="verse">Wherfore, do ȝe a-wey lesynge, &amp; speke ȝe trewþe eferych man wiþ his neyȝbore: for we beþ eferychone membres to oþer.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.26" type="verse">Be ȝe wroþ, &amp; ne sunge ȝe noȝt: ne þe
<seg id="b.EPH.1.27" type="verse">sonne go noȝt a-doun vp-on ȝoure wraþþe: ne ȝefe ȝe no stude to þe defel.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.28" type="verse">He þat haþ y-stolen here byfore, ne stele he noȝt nouþe: bote trauayle he more, worchynge wiþ his honden þat þing þat is good, &amp; he haue wher-of to ȝefen to hym þat haþ nede.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.29" type="verse">Ne passe þer non euel word out of ȝoure mouþ, bote ȝif þer is any good word to edefyynge of þe feiþ, þat ȝefe grace to hem þat hereþ.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.2" type="verse">in þe clepynge þat ȝe beþ y-cleped, wiþ al humelnesse &amp; mansuetude, wiþ pacyence, berynge up eferichone oþer in charite;
<seg id="b.EPH.1.30" type="verse">&amp; ne sorowe ȝe noȝt þe holy Spiryt of God, in whom ȝe beþ y-marked in þe day of redempcyoun.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.31" type="verse">Eferych bitternesse, &amp; wraþþe, &amp; indygnacyoun, &amp; cryynge, &amp; blasphemye, be don a-wey from ȝou, &amp;
<seg id="b.EPH.1.32" type="verse">eferyche malice: &amp; be ȝe benygne eferychone to oþer, &amp; mercyful, &amp; forȝefynge eferychone oþer, as God haþ forȝouen ȝou in Crist.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.3" type="verse">&amp; be ȝe bysy to kepe þe vnyte of Spiryt in þe bond of pees.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.4" type="verse">On body, &amp; on spiryt, as ȝe beþ y-cleped in on hope of ȝoure
<seg id="b.EPH.1.5" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.EPH.1.6" type="verse">clepynge; on Lord, on feiþ, on baptysme, on God &amp; Fader of alle þinges, &amp; abofen alle þinges, &amp; by alle þinges, &amp; in ous alle.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.7" type="verse">And to eferich of ȝou is y-graunted grace aftur þe mesure of þe ȝefynge of Crist.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.8" type="verse">Wherfore he seiþ, He þat styeþ up an hyȝ þrowȝ awey wrecchednesse, &amp; ȝef ȝiftes to men.
<seg id="b.EPH.1.9" type="verse">And what is þat, þat he steyȝ up an hyȝ, bote þat he come doun first in-to þe neþer partyes of þe erþe?
<seg id="b.EPH.2.10" type="verse">&amp; prefe
<seg id="b.EPH.2.11" type="verse">ȝe what þing is wel plesynge to God: &amp; ne comune ȝe noȝt to þe vnfruytful werkes of darknesse, bote raþere vndernymeþ
<seg id="b.EPH.2.12" type="verse">hem; for þilke þinges þat beþ y-don of hem in prifete it is foul forto speke.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.13" type="verse">&amp; alle þilke þinges þat beþ vndernomen of lyȝt, beþ openliche y-schewed: &amp; al þynge þat is y-schewed openlyche is lyȝt.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.14" type="verse">&amp; þerfore he sayþ, Aryse up, þat slepest, &amp; rys þou up from deþ, and Crist wole schyne on þe.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.15" type="verse">And þerfore, bryþeren, loke ȝe how wyslyche ȝe walken, noȝt as
<seg id="b.EPH.2.16" type="verse">vnwyse men, bote as wyse men; forbugge ȝe tyme, for þese dayes beþ yuele.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.17" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ne be ȝe noȝt y-maad vn-redy men, bote vnderstondynge whuche be þe wylle of God.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.18" type="verse">And ne be ȝe noȝt y-maad dronken þoroȝ wyn , in whom is
<seg id="b.EPH.2.19" type="verse">leccherye, bote be ȝe fulfylled wiþ þe Holy Gost; spekynge to ȝou-selfen in psalmes &amp; in ympnys &amp; in spyrytual songes,
<seg id="b.EPH.2.1" type="verse">And þerfore be ȝe foloweres of God, as his dereste children;
<seg id="b.EPH.2.20" type="verse">syngynge in ȝoure hertes, &amp; doynge þankynges to oure Lord efer more for alle men in þe name of oure Lord Iesu Cryst
<seg id="b.EPH.2.21" type="verse">to God þe Fader; beynge soget eferych man to oþer in þe drede of Crist.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.22" type="verse">Wymmen also ben sogettes to hure housbondes as to oure Lord.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.23" type="verse">For a man is þe hed of a womman, as Crist is hed of holy churche, &amp; he is þe safeour of þe body of holy chuche.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.24" type="verse">&amp; ryȝt as holy churche is soget to Crist, so ben wymmen sogetes to hire housbondes in alle þinges.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.25" type="verse">And ȝe housbondes, lofe ȝe ȝoure wyfes, as Crist lofed holy
<seg id="b.EPH.2.26" type="verse">churche, &amp; ȝef hym-self for hure; to maken hure holy, makynge hure clene þoroȝ þe waschynge of water in þe word
<seg id="b.EPH.2.27" type="verse">of lyf, þat he maked hure gloryous to hym-selfen, hafynge no wem, ne non ryfelynge, (þat is, no sen) , ne non suche oþer þing: bote þat he be holy &amp; wiþouten wem.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.28" type="verse">&amp; so men schulleþ lofen hure wyfes ryȝt as hure owne bodyes. &amp; who
<seg id="b.EPH.2.29" type="verse">þat lofeþ his wyf lofeþ hym-selfen: for þer ne is no man þat hateþ his owne flesch; bote norscheþ it &amp; kepeþ it, as Crist
<seg id="b.EPH.2.2" type="verse">&amp; walke ȝe in lofe, as Crist haþ y-lofed ous, &amp; ȝef hym-selfen for ous, an offrynge &amp; a sacryfyce to God in a swet smellynge of softnesse.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.30" type="verse">doþ holy churche; for we beþ þe membres of his body, of
<seg id="b.EPH.2.31" type="verse">Wherfore a man schal lefen his fader &amp; his moder, &amp; drawen hym to his wyf; &amp; þei schulleþ ben tweyn in on flesch.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.32" type="verse">Þis sacrament is gret; and y seye in Crist &amp; in holy churche.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.33" type="verse">Þat eferych of ȝou lofe his wyf as hym-selfen, &amp; drede þe wyf hure housbonde.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.3" type="verse">And fornycacyoun, ne non oþer vnclannesse, ne couetyse, ne be noȝt y-nemyd among ȝou, as it bysemeþ noȝt
<seg id="b.EPH.2.4" type="verse">goode men; ne non fylþe, ne folye speche, ne harlotrye, þat ne parteneþ noȝt to þe þing: bote raþere þankynges to God.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.5" type="verse">For þis wyte ȝe wel &amp; vnderstondeþ it, þat eferych lecchour , oþer an vnclene man, oþer a coueytous man, þat is þe seruyce of false goddes, ne haþ non erytage in þe kyngdom of Crist &amp; of God.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.6" type="verse">No man bygyle ȝou wiþ weyn wordes: for herfore þe wraþþe of God com in-to þe children of mystrust.
<seg id="b.EPH.2.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ne be ȝe noȝt y-mad partyneres of hem;
<seg id="b.EPH.2.8" type="verse">for ȝe weren derknesse sumtyme, bote ȝe beþ now lyȝt in
<seg id="b.EPH.2.9" type="verse">For þe fruyt of lyȝt is in eferych goodnesse &amp; ryȝtfulnesse &amp; treuþe.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.10" type="verse">&amp; her-aftur, my breþeren, be ȝe y-comforted in oure Lord &amp; in þe myȝt of his vertu.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.11" type="verse">&amp; casteþ up ȝou þe armer of God, þat ȝe mown stonden aȝeyn þe aspyes of þe defel.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.12" type="verse">For ȝoure wrastlynge ne is noȝt a-ȝeyn flesch &amp; blood, bote aȝeyn princes &amp; potestates, a-ȝeyn þe gouernoures of þe worlde of þis darknesse, a-ȝeyn þe spyrytual armer of wykkednesse in hefnelyche þinges.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.13" type="verse">Wharfore take ȝe þe armer of God, þat ȝe mown aȝeyn-stonde in þe luther day, &amp; þat ȝe mowen stonde parfyt in alle þinges.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.14" type="verse">&amp; þerfore cutteþ up ȝoure lendes , &amp; stonde ȝe in trewþe, &amp; cloþeþ ȝou wiþ an
<seg id="b.EPH.3.15" type="verse">haberioun of riȝtfulnesse, &amp; schoyeþ ȝoure fet in greyþynge
<seg id="b.EPH.3.16" type="verse">of þe euangelye of pees; and in al þinge, take ȝe þe scheld of þe feyþ, in þe whuche ȝe mowen quenchen alle þe fuyry
<seg id="b.EPH.3.17" type="verse">&amp; take ȝe to ȝow þe helm of hele, &amp; þe swerd of þe Spiryt, þat is Goddes
<seg id="b.EPH.3.18" type="verse">word: preynge in eferych tyme in spiryt þoroȝ eferych preyere &amp; bysechynge, &amp; wakynge in spiryt in eferich bysynesse, &amp;
<seg id="b.EPH.3.19" type="verse">preynge for alle goode men, &amp; for me þat þer be y-ȝefe to me speche in openynge of my mouþ wiþ trust, to make ȝou knowe þe mystery of þe euangely.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.1" type="verse">And, ȝe children, be ȝe buxom to ȝoure eldren: for þat is ryȝtful.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.20" type="verse">For whom y vse worschupfulyche my ligacyon (byndynge) in þis chayne, so þat in hym y dare speke, þat y schulde speke.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.21" type="verse">And for þat ȝe schulden y-knowe, how it is wiþ me &amp; what y do, alle þinges Tyte, my derest broþer &amp; a trewe serfaunt in oure Lord, schal
<seg id="b.EPH.3.22" type="verse">make ȝou knowe: whom ich hafe y-send to ȝow for þis enchesoun, þat ȝe knowen how it is wiþ ous to comforte ȝoure hertes.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.23" type="verse">Pees be to oure breþeren, &amp; charite wiþ feiþ of oure God þe Fader &amp; oure Lord Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.24" type="verse">Þe grace of God be wiþ alle hem þat lofeþ oure Lord Iesu Crist incorcyoun . Amen.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.2" type="verse">Worschupe þi fader &amp; þi moder, þat is on of þe
<seg id="b.EPH.3.3" type="verse">furste comaundementes in þe byheste, þat it be weel to þe, &amp; þat þou be longe lyfynge on þe erþe.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.4" type="verse">And, ȝe faderes, ne stere ȝe noȝt ȝoure children to wraþþe: bote norsche ȝe hem in þe techynge of oure Lord, &amp; amende hem of here defautes.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.5" type="verse">Serfauntes , be ȝe boxum to ȝoure fleschlyche lordes, wiþ drede &amp; wiþ quakyng, in sympelnesse of ȝoure herte, ryȝt as
<seg id="b.EPH.3.6" type="verse">to Crist; noȝt serfynge to þe , as for-to plesen men, bote as Cristes serfauntes, doyng þe wylle of God wylfullyche,
<seg id="b.EPH.3.7" type="verse">serfynge wiþ a good will as to oure Lord, &amp; noȝt as to men:
<seg id="b.EPH.3.8" type="verse">knowynge þat what good dede any man do, he schal vnderfongen it of God, wheþer he be a serfaunt oþer a fre man.
<seg id="b.EPH.3.9" type="verse">And, ȝe lordes, do ȝe þe same þinges to hem, forȝefynge hem þretynges: knowynge þat boþe ȝoure Lord &amp; hure Lord is in hefene, &amp; þer ne is non vnderfongynge of mennes persones to-fore God.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.10" type="verse">Bote y truste in ȝow in oure Lord, þat ȝe ne woleþ safere non oþer þing: bote he þat affrayeþ ȝou schal bere his dom, whyche-efer he be.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.11" type="verse">And breþeren, ȝif y preche ȝit circumsisyoun, wharto suffre ych ȝet persecucyoun? þanne is þe sclaundur of þe cros y-voyded awey.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.12" type="verse">&amp; wolde God he were y-kut awey þat affrayeþ ȝou þus.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.13" type="verse">My breþeren, ȝe beþ y-cleped in-to fredom; &amp; ne ȝefe ȝe noȝt ȝoure fredom in-to occasyoun of flesch, bote serfe ȝe to-gedere þoroȝ charite of spiryt.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.14" type="verse">For eferich lawe is fulfulled in on word, Þou schalt lofe þi nexte neyȝeboure as þi-selfe.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.15" type="verse">&amp; ȝef ȝe byteþ &amp; gnaweþ to-gedere, byseþ ȝou lest ȝe ben y-wasted awey eferichone of oþer.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.16" type="verse">&amp; y sey ȝou in Crist, Walke ȝe in Crist, &amp; ȝe ne schuleþ noȝt fulfylle þe desyres of þe flesch.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.17" type="verse">For þe flesch coueyteþ aȝeyn þe Spiryt, &amp; þe Spiryt a-ȝeyn þe flesch; for þese beþ aduersaryes eferychone to oþer; þat ȝe do noȝt al þat ȝe wolleþ.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.18" type="verse">&amp; ȝif ȝe beþ y-lad þoroȝ þe Spiryt, ȝe beþ not vnder lawe.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.19" type="verse">&amp; þe workes of þi flesch beþ opene, þat
<seg id="b.GAL.1.20" type="verse">beþ fornycacyoun, vnclennesse, in-contynence, seruyse of false goddes, wycche-craftes, enemytees, stryfynges, hatynges,
<seg id="b.GAL.1.21" type="verse">wraþþes, chydynges, debates, sectes, enuyes , manslauȝtes, dronkenesse, etynge out of mesure, &amp; oþer þat beþ y-lyche þese, þe whuche y sey ȝow by-fore, as y haue y-seyd ȝow. For þilke þat doþ suche þinges ne schuleþ noȝt hafe þe kyngdom of hefene.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.22" type="verse">Bote þe fruyt of þe Spiryt is charyte, ioye, pees, pacyence, longe abydynge, benyngnyte, goodnesse,
<seg id="b.GAL.1.23" type="verse">mansuetude (þat is, myldene) , feiþ, softnesse, contynence, chastite; aȝeyn suche þer ne is no lawe.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.24" type="verse">&amp; þilke þat beþ of Crist hafeþ y-crucyfyed hure flesch wiþ vyces and wiþ coueytynges.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.25" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.GAL.1.26" type="verse">And ȝif we lyfeþ in Spiryt, walke we in Spiryt. Ne be we noȝt y-mad coueytous of veyn glorye, taryynge eferychone
<seg id="b.GAL.1.2" type="verse">And to Galathes he wryteþ, &amp; seyþ, Lo, y Poule seye to ȝow, þat ȝef ȝe beþ circumcyded, Crist profyteþ ȝow no þing.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.3" type="verse">For y bere wytnesse eftsones to euerich man þat circumcydeþ hym-selfen, þat he is dettour to don al þe lawe.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.4" type="verse">&amp; ȝe beþ y-voyded a-wey from Crist, for ȝe þat beþ y-iustyfyed in þe lawe, ȝe beþ y-fallen a-wey from grace.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.5" type="verse">For ȝe ne abydeþ noȝt þe hope of riȝtfulnesse þoroȝ þe spiryt of bylefe.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.6" type="verse">&amp; in Iesu Crist nouþer cyrcumsysyon is ouȝt worþ, ne þe prepucye nouþer; bote feiþ þat worcheþ by charite.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.7" type="verse">Ȝe ronne wel; who haþ y-lat ȝou nouþe, þat ȝe ne obeyscheþ ȝou noȝt to
<seg id="b.GAL.1.8" type="verse">Ne assente ȝe to no man in þis, for þis persuacyoun (or, euidence) ne is noȝt of hym þat haþ y-cleped ȝow.
<seg id="b.GAL.1.9" type="verse">A lytel sourdouȝ schendeþ al-to-geder a gret pese.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.10" type="verse">And þerfore whyle we haueþ tyme, do we good to alle men, bote most to þilke þat beþ homlyche to þe bylefe.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.11" type="verse">&amp; loke ȝe what manere letteres y wrot to ȝow myn owne hond.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.12" type="verse">Alle þilke þat woleþ plesen in flesch, þei constreyneþ ȝow to ben circumcyded; onlyche for þei ne wolde noȝt suffre þe persecucyoun of Cristis cros.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.13" type="verse">&amp; nouþer þei þat circumcydeþ kepeþ þe lawe; bote þei wolden þat ȝe weren circumcyded, for þei wolden ioyen in ȝoure flesch.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.14" type="verse">Bote God forbede þat y ioye bote in þe cros of oure Lord Iesu Crist , þoroȝ whom þe world is y-crucyfyed to me, &amp; y to þe worlde.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.15" type="verse">For in Iesu Crist nouþer circumsysyoun is ouȝt worþ, ne þe prepucye nouþer, bote a newe creature.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.16" type="verse">&amp; whycheefer þat han y-folewed þis reule, pees &amp; mercy be on hem &amp; up-on þe Israel of God.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.17" type="verse">Aftur þis tyme no man be greuous to me: for y bere þe markes of þe woundes of Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.1" type="verse">And breþeren, ȝef any man be y-ocupyed in any trespas, ȝe þat beþ spirytual, enformeþ such a man in þe spiryt of softnesse; byholdynge þi-selfe lest þat þou be y-temptyd.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.2" type="verse">On of ȝow bere oþeres burþenes, &amp; so ȝe schuleþ fulfullen Cristes lawe.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.3" type="verse">For who þat weneþ þat he be any þing, whan þat he ne is noȝt, he bygyleþ hym-selfe.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.4" type="verse">Bote eueryche man prefe his owne werk, &amp; so he schal ioyen in an-oþer man, &amp; noȝt in hym-selfen. For eferych man schal bere his owne burþene.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.5" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.GAL.2.6" type="verse">And he þat is y-tauȝt, comune he to hym þat techeþ in alle goode þinges.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.7" type="verse">Ne erre ȝe noȝt, for God ne wole noȝt ben y-scorned: for þilke þinges þat a man soweþ , þilke þinges he schal repen.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.8" type="verse">For he þat soweþ in his flesch, of his flesch he schal repe corrupcyoun; bote he þat soweþ in his spiryt, of his spiryt he schal repe an eferlastynge lyf.
<seg id="b.GAL.2.9" type="verse">And ne fayle we noȝt doynge þing þat is good.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.10" type="verse">In þe whuche wylle we beþ y-halewed by þe offrynge of þe body of Iesu Crist ones.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.11" type="verse">And eferich prest mot ben eferich day redy mynystrynge &amp; offrynge fele syþes
<seg id="b.HEB.10.12" type="verse">þe same sacryfyces, þat mowen nefer don awey synnes: bote þes prest , offrynge on sacryfyce for synnes, sytteþ efermore
<seg id="b.HEB.10.13" type="verse">in þe ryȝt syde of God, abydynge her-aftur for-to þat his enemyes ben y-sett þe stool of his fet.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.14" type="verse">For þoroȝ on offrynge he made men holy for efer.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.15" type="verse">For þe Holy Gost
<seg id="b.HEB.10.16" type="verse">wytnesseþ þat whanne he saiþ, Þis schal be þe testement þat ich wole make to hem aftur þilke dayes, seiþ God, ich wole ȝeue my lawes in hure hertes, &amp; ich wole wryte hem in hure
<seg id="b.HEB.10.17" type="verse">þoȝtes; &amp; y nul byþenke no more of hure wyckednesse &amp; hure synnes.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.18" type="verse">&amp; þer as is forȝeuenesse of þese, þer is non offrynge for synne.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.19" type="verse">And þerfore, breþeren, we habbeþ a trust
<seg id="b.HEB.10.1" type="verse">For þe lawe haþ a schadewe of goodis þat beþ to comynge, &amp; noȝt þat ymage of þinges, eferich ȝer offreþ þe selfe sacrifyces wiþ-outen cessynge, &amp; may noȝt maken hem parfyt þat haueþ accesse to hem.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.20" type="verse">in þe entrynge of seyntes in Cristes blod, in þe whuche trust he haþ y-cast to ous a newe weye &amp; a lyfynge þoroȝ þe
<seg id="b.HEB.10.21" type="verse">keferynge, þat is, þoroȝ his flesch; &amp; þoroȝ a gret prest vp-on
<seg id="b.HEB.10.22" type="verse">Godes hous; &amp; come we to hym wiþ a trewe herte in fulnesse of bylefe, &amp; sprenge we oure hertes from an efel conscyence,
<seg id="b.HEB.10.23" type="verse">&amp; wasche we þe body wiþ clene watyr, &amp; holde we þe knowlechynge of oure hope bowynge to no syde; for he is trewe of þat he haþ y-ȝefen ous a byheste.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.24" type="verse">And byholde we togedere
<seg id="b.HEB.10.25" type="verse">in sterynge of charyte &amp; of goode werkes, noȝt lefynge oure quyletes, as it is a custom to summe men, bote
<seg id="b.HEB.10.26" type="verse">For ȝif þat we synneþ wylfullyche after þe vnderfongynge of þe knowleche of trewþe, þer ne is noȝt
<seg id="b.HEB.10.27" type="verse">y-laft a sacrifyce for oure synnes, bote þer is a dredful abydynge of þe dom, &amp; þe sewynge fuyr þat schal consumen þe aduersaryes of Crist.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.28" type="verse">For who þat brekes Moyses lawe, wiþ-outen any mercy, vnder two oþer þre wytnesses, he is
<seg id="b.HEB.10.29" type="verse">y-don to þe deþ; how muche more trewe, ȝef þat he deserfe grettere tormentynges þat defouleþ Godes sone, &amp; defouleþ þe blod of þe testament, in whom he is y-halewed, &amp; doþ wrong to þe Spiryt of grace?
<seg id="b.HEB.10.2" type="verse">For elles me schulde hafe y-cessyd to offren sacrifyces, for as muche as þe doeres þer-of , ones y-mad clene, ne schulden hafe y-had afturward no conscyence of synne.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.30" type="verse">For we wyteþ þat he seyde, To me veniaunce, &amp; ich wole ȝelden aȝeyn . &amp; eftsones, For God schal demen his pepel.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.31" type="verse">And þerfore it is dredful to fallen in-to þe hondes of þe lyfynge God.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.32" type="verse">Bote hafe ȝe muynde of þe raþer dayes, in whom ȝe weren y-lyȝted &amp;
<seg id="b.HEB.10.33" type="verse">susteyned a gret batayle of suffrynges; &amp; in anoþer day ȝe weren y-mad a spectakel to reprefes &amp; trybulacyones; &amp; anoþer day ȝe beþ y-mad felawes of þilke þat han such conuersacyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.34" type="verse">For ȝe haden compassyoun of hem þat weren y-bounden, &amp; vnderfongen þe robbynge of ȝoure goodes wiþ ioye, knowynge þat ȝe haden a beter substaunce dwellynge in hefne.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.35" type="verse">Ne lese ȝe noȝt þanne ȝoure trust þat haþ a gret rewardynge.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.36" type="verse">For pacyence is nedful to ȝow þat ȝe don þe wylle of God, þat ȝe bryngen his byheste.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.37" type="verse">And ȝet a lytel whyle, &amp; wiþynne a lytel whyle he þat is to comynge schal
<seg id="b.HEB.10.38" type="verse">come; &amp; my ryȝtful man lyfeþ of bylefe: &amp; ȝef he wiþ-draweþ his fot he ne schal noȝt plesen his soule.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.39" type="verse">Bote we ne beþ noȝt chyldren of wyþdrawynge in-to perdycioun, bote Goddes chyldren in getynge of þe soule.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.3" type="verse">Bote eferyche ȝer in hem þer is y-mad a muynde of synnes.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.4" type="verse">For it is impossybel for synnes
<seg id="b.HEB.10.5" type="verse">And þerfore whanne he comeþ in-to þe worlde, he saiþ, Þou ne desyredest noȝt sacryfyce &amp; offrynge, bote þou schapedest to
<seg id="b.HEB.10.6" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.HEB.10.7" type="verse">me a body; &amp; holocaustes for synne ne plesede þe noȝt: &amp; þo y sayde, Lo, y come—in þe bygynnynge of þe bok it is y-wryten of me—þat y do þi wille, God.
<seg id="b.HEB.10.8" type="verse">&amp; so suggynge abofe, þat þou ne woldest noȝt sacrifyces &amp; offrynges &amp; holocaustes for synnes, ne þei weren noȝt plesynge to þe þat beþ
<seg id="b.HEB.10.9" type="verse">y-offred aftur þe lawe, þo y sayde, Lo, God, y come þat y do þi wylle. He doþ awey þe raþer, þat he stable þat þat foleweþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.10" type="verse">&amp;, Lord, in þe bygynnynge þou foundedest þe erþe, &amp; hefnes beþ þe werkes of þyn honden:
<seg id="b.HEB.11.10" type="verse">byheste: for he abod a cyte hauynge foundementes, whos werk-men &amp; makere was God.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.11" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Sara þat was bareyne vnderfong vertu in consceyfynge of seed &amp; aȝeyn þe tyme of hure age, for heo bylefed þat he was trewe þat
<seg id="b.HEB.11.12" type="verse">hade by-hoten hure; wherfore of on beþ many y-boren, &amp; aftur þat he was ded, as þe multitude of þe sterres of hefne, &amp; as þe grafel in þe brynke of þe see þat may noȝt ben y-nombred.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.13" type="verse">By feyþ alle þese beþ dede, wiþ-outen vnderfongynge of þe byheste, bote byholdynge a-fer þyne of byhestes, &amp; saluwynge hem, &amp; knowlechynge þat þei beþ pilgrymes &amp; men herborewed on þe erþe.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.14" type="verse">For þei þat seyen þis sygnyfyeþ þat þei secheþ a contray.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.15" type="verse">&amp; ȝef þei haden y-had muynde of þe contray þat þei wenten out of, þei haden tyme to haue y-turned aȝeyn.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.16" type="verse">Bote now desyreþ a beter, þat is, an hefenlyche contrey. And þerfore God ne is noȝt
<seg id="b.HEB.11.17" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Abraham offred Ysaac whan he was y-tempted , &amp; offred his on bygeten sone þat hade
<seg id="b.HEB.11.18" type="verse">vnderfongen þe byheste; for to hym it was y-sayd, In Ysaac
<seg id="b.HEB.11.19" type="verse">þi seed schal ben y-cleped: schewynge þat God is myȝty to areren up men from deþ to lyf. Wherfore he vnderfong hym in a parable.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.1" type="verse">Bote feiþ is þe substaunce of þinges þat beþ to ben y-hoped, &amp; an argument of þinges þat semeþ noȝt.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.11" type="verse">þei schuleþ perysche, bote þou schalt efermore duelle stylle:
<seg id="b.HEB.11.20" type="verse">&amp; þoroȝ feiþ of þinges þat weren to comynge, Ysaac blessed Iacob &amp; Esau.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.21" type="verse">&amp; þoroȝ feiþ Iacob dyynge blessed Iosephes chyldren, &amp; honoured þe hyȝschyp
<seg id="b.HEB.11.22" type="verse">of his ȝerde; &amp; þoroȝ feyþ Ioseph dyynge hade muynde of þe passynge forþ of þe chyldren of Israel, &amp; comaunded of his bones.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.23" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Moyses, whan he was y-bore, was y-hud þre moneþes of his eldren, for þei seyen þat he was a welfaryng chyld, &amp; dradde noȝt þe kynges comaundement.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.24" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Moyses y-mad gret and forsok
<seg id="b.HEB.11.25" type="verse">þat he was Pharaoes douȝter sone; desyryng more to ben y-peyned wiþ Goddes peple, þan for-to haue temporel murþe
<seg id="b.HEB.11.26" type="verse">of synne; trowynge þe obbroyd of Crist grettour rychesse þan þe tresour of Egypcyenes: for he byheld in-to þe remuneracyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.27" type="verse">Þoroȝ feiþ he lefed Egypt, noȝt dredynge þe boldschype of þe kyng; for he abod hym þat was in-vysybel as þouȝ he seye hym.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.28" type="verse">Þoroȝ feyþ he halewed pask, and þe schedynge of blod, lest he touched hem þat wasted þe furste bygeten þinges of Egipcyenes.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.29" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ þei passeden ouer þe Rede See as by druye lond: bote þe Egypcyenes asayeden þat &amp; weren deuoured.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.12" type="verse">&amp; alle þei schuleþ waxen old as cloþinge; &amp; as an helynge þou schalt chaungen hem, &amp; þei schuleþ ben y-chaunged: bote þou art efermore on, &amp; þi ȝeres ne schuleþ noȝt faylen .
<seg id="b.HEB.11.2" type="verse">For in þis olde men han y-had testymonye.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.30" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ men of Ierycho fullen a-doun þoroȝ þe circuyt of sefen dayes.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.31" type="verse">&amp; þoroȝ feiþ Raab þe hore ne perysched noȝt wiþ oþer þat weren vnbylefed, vnderfongynge þe aspyes wiþ pees.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.32" type="verse">&amp; what schal y seye ȝet? for tyme wole fayle me to telle of Gedeon, Barac, Sampson, Iepte,
<seg id="b.HEB.11.33" type="verse">Dauyd, Samuel &amp; þe prophetes: þat by feiþ ofer-comen kyngdomes, &amp; wroȝten ryȝtfulnes, &amp; geten repromyssyones,
<seg id="b.HEB.11.34" type="verse">&amp; stoppeden lyones mouþes, &amp; quencheden þe impetuesnesse of fuyr, &amp; dryfen a-wey þe scharpnesse of swerd, &amp; han
<seg id="b.HEB.11.35" type="verse">&amp; wymmen han vnderfongen hure housbondes arysynge aȝeyn from deþ to lyf: but oþer han y-be wiþholden, noȝt underfongynge redempcyoun; for þei wolden y-fynde a beter resureccion:
<seg id="b.HEB.11.36" type="verse">oþer hafeþ assayed dyspysynges &amp; betynges, &amp; prisones
<seg id="b.HEB.11.37" type="verse">&amp; byndynge: &amp; han y-ben y-stoned &amp; to-hewe &amp; y-temptyd, &amp; han y-dyed þoroȝ sleynge of swerd. And summe han y-gon aboute in rouȝ cloþinge of heres, &amp; in gotes skynnes;
<seg id="b.HEB.11.38" type="verse">nedy &amp; a-nuyed &amp; y-angwysched, to whom þe world ne was noȝt worþi; errynge in wyldernesse &amp; in hulles &amp; in dennes &amp; holes of þe erþe.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.39" type="verse">&amp; alle þese , prefed þoroȝ wytnessynge
<seg id="b.HEB.1.13" type="verse">Bote to whom of þe aungeles haþ he y-sayd her-byfore, Sitte on my ryȝtsyde, for-to þat y putte þin enemyes a stol vnder þi feet?
<seg id="b.HEB.11.3" type="verse">Þoroȝ feiþ we vnderstondeþ þat þe worldes weren y-mad þoroȝ þe word of God, &amp; þat of in-vysybel þinges weren y-mad þinges þat mowen ben y-seye.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.40" type="verse">of feiþ, ne vnderfongen noȝt þe repromyssyoun: for God ordeyned sum þyng beter for us, þat þei ne schulde noȝt ben y-broȝt to ende wiþ-outen ous.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.14" type="verse">Ne beþ noȝt alle þe spirites serfauntes, &amp; y-send for-to seruen for hem þat takeþ þe erytage of hele?
<seg id="b.HEB.11.4" type="verse">Þoroȝ feiþ Abel offred a grettere sacrifyce þan
<seg id="b.HEB.11.5" type="verse">Þoroȝ feiþ Enoch was translated þat he ne seyȝ noȝt deþ; &amp; he ne was noȝt y-founde, for God translated hym: for byforen his translacyoun he hade
<seg id="b.HEB.11.6" type="verse">witnesse þat he plesede God: &amp; wiþ-outen feiþ it is impossybel for-to plese God: for it byhoueþ þilke þat wolleþ come to God bylefen þat he is, &amp; to þilke þat secheþ hym bysylyche he is y-mad a rewarder.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.7" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Noe vnderfong an answere of þinges þat ne were noȝt y-seye byfore, &amp;, dredynge, he ordeyned hym a schyp to þe hele of his houshold; by whom he dampned þe worlde, &amp; was y-mad eyr of þe ryȝtfulnesse þat is þoroȝ feiþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.8" type="verse">And þoroȝ feiþ Abraham, y-cleped, obeysched to gon in-to þe place þat he schulde vnderfongen for erytage; &amp; wente forþ, noȝt knowynge whyder þat he wente.
<seg id="b.HEB.11.9" type="verse">&amp; þoroȝ feiþ he dwelled in þe lond of byheste, as a straunger, wonyng in lytel houses, wiþ Ysaac &amp; wiþ Iacob, þat weren eyres wiþ hym of þe same
<seg id="b.HEB.1.1" type="verse">God haþ y-spoken in many maneres sumtyme in prophetes
<seg id="b.HEB.12.10" type="verse">And þei wiþ-ynne a fewe dayes enformeden ous aftur hure owne wylle; bote þes to þat þing þat is profytabel, in receyfynge his holynesse.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.11" type="verse">Bote eferyche techynge in þis tyme ne semeþ noȝt to ben of ioye, bote of deþ. Bote afterward he schal ȝelde to þilke þat han wel y-lerned þe moste pesful fruyt of ryȝtfulnesse.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.12" type="verse">Wherfore rereþ up ȝoure remysse hondes, &amp; ȝowre knees þat
<seg id="b.HEB.12.13" type="verse">beþ dissolut; &amp; makeþ efene þe goynges to ȝoure fet, þat no man erre haltynge, bote be raþer y-heled.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.14" type="verse">&amp; folewe ȝe pes with alle men, &amp; holynesse wiþouten whom no man schal y-seo God.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.15" type="verse">And loke ȝe, þat no man lakke þe grace of God; ne þat no rote of bytternesse bourgenynge upward latte no
<seg id="b.HEB.12.16" type="verse">man, þoroȝ þe whuche many men ben defouled; ne þat no man be a lechour, &amp; wycked as Esau, þat for mete solde his herytage.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.17" type="verse">For wyte ȝe wel, þat whanne he desyred to hafe an-heryted þe blessynge, he was reprefed, for he ne fonde no place of penaunce, þouȝ þat he souȝte it wiþ teres.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.18" type="verse">For ȝe ne beþ noȝt y-come to þe fuyr, þat me may holden &amp; neyȝlechen
<seg id="b.HEB.12.19" type="verse">þer-to , ne to þe whyrlewynd &amp; to tempest, ne to þe sown of a trumpe, ne to þe voys of wordes, whom þilke þat herde excuseden hem-selfe, for þat þe voys ne schulde noȝt ben
<seg id="b.HEB.12.1" type="verse">And þerfore we þat hafeþ so gret a cloud of wytnesses y-putte to ous, do we a-wey from ous eferich charge &amp; synne þat stondeþ abouten ous, &amp; renne we by pacyence to þe
<seg id="b.HEB.12.20" type="verse">y-mad to hem: for þey ne beren noȝt þat þat was y-seyd, &amp; ȝef a best hade y-touched þe hul, he schulde haue ben
<seg id="b.HEB.12.21" type="verse">y-stoned; &amp; so dredful it was þat was y-seye, for Moyses seyde, Ich am a-gast &amp; quakynge for drede.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.22" type="verse">Bote ȝe beþ y-come to þe hul of Syon, &amp; to þe hefenlyche Ierusalem þat is þe cyte of þe lyfynge God, &amp; to þe cumpany of many
<seg id="b.HEB.12.23" type="verse">þousandes of aungeles, &amp; to þe churche of primytyfes þat beþ y-wryten to-gedere in hefenes, &amp; to þe domesman of alle
<seg id="b.HEB.12.24" type="verse">spyrytes &amp; of ryȝtful men &amp; of parfyt men, &amp; to þe medyatour of a newe testement, Iesus, &amp; to þe schedynge of his blod þat spak betere þan Abel.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.25" type="verse">&amp; loke ȝe þat ȝe ne refuse noȝt hym þat spekeþ. For ȝef þei ne a-scaped noȝt , þat refuseden
<seg id="b.HEB.12.26" type="verse">hefene: whos voyce meued þe erþe sumtyme: bote he byhoteþ now &amp; seiþ, Ȝet ones, &amp; ich wol meue noȝt onlyche þe erþe bote hefene also.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.27" type="verse">What is þat, þat he seiþ Ones? in þat he declareþ þe translacyoun of mebel þinges, as of þinges þat beþ y-don, þat þey þat beþ im-mebel þinges dwellen stylle.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.28" type="verse">&amp; þerfore we þat vnderfongeþ a kyngdom þat is im-mebel hafeþ a grace, þoroȝ whom we schulen
<seg id="b.HEB.12.29" type="verse">seruen oure God wiþ drede &amp; wiþ reuerence: for oure God is fuyr þat consumeþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.2" type="verse">fyȝtynge þat is y-purposed to ous, byholdynge in-to þe auctor &amp; þe bryngere to ende of oure feiþ Iesus, þat whenne ioye was y-purposed to hym he suffred þe cros, dispysynge confusyoun, &amp; he sytteþ on þe ryȝt syde of þe sege of God.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.3" type="verse">&amp; þerfore byþinkeþ ȝow on hym þat suffred synful men aȝeyn-seyenge hym, þat ȝe ne ben noȝt y-wryed , faylynge to ȝoure soules.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.4" type="verse">For ȝet now ȝe ne hafeþ noȝt aȝeynstondynge, fyȝtynge aȝeyn synne, to þe schedynge of ȝoure blod.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.5" type="verse">&amp; hafe ȝe forȝeten þe comfort þat God haþ spoken to ous as to his chyldren, seyenge, My chyld, ne dispyse þou noȝt þe techynge of oure Lord, ne be þou noȝt y-weryed whyles þou art
<seg id="b.HEB.12.6" type="verse">y-prefed of hym; for he chasteþ þilke þat he loueþ, &amp; he scoureþ eferych chyld þat he receyfeþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.12.7" type="verse">Abyde ȝe stylle in techynge, for God ȝefeþ hymself to ȝow as to his chyldren; &amp; what chyld is þere þat þe fader ne chasteþ noȝt?
<seg id="b.HEB.12.8" type="verse">&amp; ȝef ȝe beþ out of techynge, whos partyneres ben ȝe y-mad alle?
<seg id="b.HEB.12.9" type="verse">Furþermore, we haden fadres þat weren techeres of oure flesch, &amp; we worschupeden hem: muche more we schulleþ be buxom to þe Fader of spirytes, &amp; we schulleþ lyfen.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.2" type="verse">to oure fadres, bote al-þer last in þese dayes he haþ y-spoken to ous in his Sone, whom he haþ y-ordeyned to ben eyr
<seg id="b.HEB.13.10" type="verse">We han an auter, of whom no men han power forto eten bote þilke þat serfeþ in þe tabernakel.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.11" type="verse">For of þilke bestes, whos blod is y-boren in-to holy places by þe byschop for synne, hure bodyes beþ y-brent wiþ-outen þe casteles.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.12" type="verse">Wherfore Iesus, for he wolde halewen his pepel þoroȝ his blod, he suffred his passyoun with-outen þe ȝate.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.13" type="verse">&amp; þerfore go we out to hym wiþ-outen þe casteles,
<seg id="b.HEB.13.14" type="verse">For we ne hafeþ noȝt here no cyte þat is dwellynge, bote we secheþ on þat is to comen.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.15" type="verse">For þoroȝ hym we offreþ efermore a sacrifyce of heryynge to God, þat is, þe fruyt of þe lyppys þat knowlecheþ to his name.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.16" type="verse">Bote ne forȝete ȝe noȝt of wel doynge &amp; of comunyon, for in syche sacrifices God is y-worschuped.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.17" type="verse">&amp; be ȝe buxom &amp; sogettes to hem þat beþ abofe ȝow: for þei wakeþ as for-to ȝelden acountes for ȝoure soules; þat þei don it wiþ ioye &amp; noȝt wiþ sorowe : for þat ne is noȝt spedful to ȝow.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.18" type="verse">&amp; preyeþ for ous: for we trusteþ þat we han a good conscyence in all þilke þat han good wylle to don wel.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.19" type="verse">&amp; þe more largelyche y preye ȝow þat ȝe don so, in as myche as y schal þe raþere comen aȝeyn to ȝou.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.1" type="verse">Þe charite of breþerhede dwelle a-mong ȝow.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.20" type="verse">&amp; God of pees, þat broȝte out from deþ oure Lord Iesu Crist, a gret schepherde of alle men
<seg id="b.HEB.13.21" type="verse">in þe blod of on eferlastynge testement, ordeyne ȝow in eferich place þat ȝe don his wylle, &amp; do in ȝow þat be plesynge in hym by Iesu Crist; to whom be ioye &amp; blysse worlde wiþouten ende. Amen.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.2" type="verse">&amp; ne forȝete ȝe noȝt hospytalite: for þer-þoroȝ sum men han y-plesed aungeles in receyuynge hem to herborewe.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.3" type="verse">&amp; hafe ȝe muynde of hem þat beþ y-bounde, as þouȝ ȝe weren y-bounde ȝow-selfen; &amp; of hem þat trafayleþ, as þouȝ ȝe ȝow-selfen weren duellynge in body.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.4" type="verse">And be þer worschupful wedlak in alle þinges, &amp; a bed wiþ-outen wem: for God schal deme boþe lecchours &amp; spousbrekeres.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.5" type="verse">And ben ȝoure maneres wiþ-outen coueytyse , a-payd wiþ present þinges: for God saiþ, Y nul noȝt lefe þe.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.6" type="verse">So þat we mowen seye trustylyche, My lord is myn helpere, &amp; y nul not drede what no man do to me.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.7" type="verse">And hafe ȝe muynde of hem þat beþ y-set to-fore ȝow, þat hafeþ y-spoke to ȝow Goddus word; &amp; byholde ȝe þe yssew of hure conuersacyoun, &amp; folewe ȝe hure feiþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.8" type="verse">Iesu Crist was ȝurstay &amp; to day, and he is efermore.
<seg id="b.HEB.13.9" type="verse">Ne be ȝe noȝt y-lad awey with dyuerse techynges &amp; straunge: for it is best þat þe herte be y-stabled in grace; noȝt in metes, þat ne profyted noȝt to hem þat walkeden in hem.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.3" type="verse">of alle þinges, by whom also he made þe worldes; &amp; he is þe brytnesse of his blisse, &amp; þe fygure of his substaunce, berynge alle þinges þoroȝ þe word of his vertu, &amp; makynge þe purgacyoun of synnes, he syt on þe ryȝt syde of þe mageste an
<seg id="b.HEB.1.4" type="verse">hyȝ in hefne; so muche y-maad betur þan aungeles, in as muche as he haþ an-heryted a different name to-foren hem.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.5" type="verse">For to whuche of þe aungeles haþ God y-sayd in any tyme, Þou art my Sone, to day ich haue bygete þe? &amp; eftsones, Ich wole be to hym a Fader &amp; he schal be my Sone?
<seg id="b.HEB.1.6" type="verse">And eftsones whan he bryngeþ his furst bygeten sone in-to þe worlde he sayþ, &amp; alle his aungeles heryen hym.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.7" type="verse">&amp; to aungeles he seiþ, He makeþ his aungeles spirytes &amp; þi serfauntes lye of þe fuyr.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.8" type="verse">Bote to þe sone he seyþ, Þi throne, God, is from worlde to worlde; &amp; a ȝerde of equyte þe ȝerde of þi kyngdom.
<seg id="b.HEB.1.9" type="verse">Þou hast y-lofed riȝtfulnesse &amp; y-hated wykkednesse; wher-fore þi God haþ a-noynted þe wiþ oyle of gladnesse to-fore þi felawes.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.10" type="verse">For it bysemed hym, þoroȝ whom beþ alle þinges, &amp; for whom beþ alle þinges, þat ladde wiþ hym many chyldren in-to blisse &amp; was auctor of hure hele, to hafe an ende by passyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.11" type="verse">For he þat haleweþ,
<seg id="b.HEB.2.12" type="verse">breþeren, seyenge, Y wol telle þi name to my breþeren, &amp; in þe myddel of þe churche y wole herye þe. &amp; eftsones, Y wole haue turst in hym.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.13" type="verse">&amp; eftsones, Lo y &amp; my chyldren þat God haþ y-ȝefe me.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.14" type="verse">And þerfore for chyldren han y-comuned to his flesch &amp; his blod, he haþ also y-parted wiþ hem; þat þoroȝ deþ he wole distroyen hym þat hade þe
<seg id="b.HEB.2.15" type="verse">empyre of deþ, þat is, þe defel; &amp; wolde delyueren hem þat in drede of deþ by al hure lyf weren soget to þraldom.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.16" type="verse">For nowȝere he toke aungeles, bote he toke þe sed of Abraham.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.17" type="verse">Wherfore he owed by alle þinges to ben y-lekened to breþeren, þat he were y-mad mercyful &amp; a trewe byschop to-fore God, to forȝefen his pepel hure synnes.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.18" type="verse">For in þat he suffred &amp; was y-temptyd, he is myȝty to helpen þilke þat beþ y-tempted.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.1" type="verse">And þerfore it byhoueþ ous more largelyche to kepen þilke þinges þat we han y-hed , lest þat we fleten awey .
<seg id="b.HEB.2.2" type="verse">For ȝif þat word þat was y-maad by aungeles was ferme &amp; stabel, &amp; eferich priuaricacyoun &amp; in-obedyence haþ vnderfongen
<seg id="b.HEB.2.3" type="verse">a ryȝtful rewardynge to mede; how schule we ascape, ȝef we dyspyseþ þus gret an hele? þe whuche hele, whan it hade y-take a bygynnynge to ben y-told by oure Lord, of hem
<seg id="b.HEB.2.4" type="verse">þat herden in ous heo is confermed, God berynge wyttnesse in sygnes &amp; wondres, &amp; dyuerse vertues &amp; delynges of þe Holy Gost, aftur his owene wylle.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.5" type="verse">And God ne made noȝt þe worlde þat is to comen, of whom we spekeþ, of soget to aungeles.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.6" type="verse">Bote on wittnesseþ in a place &amp; sayþ, What is man, þat þou hast mynde of hym? oþer mannes sone, þat þou vysytest hym?
<seg id="b.HEB.2.7" type="verse">Þou hast y-mad hym lytel lasse þan aungeles, &amp; þou hast corowned hym wiþ ioye &amp; wiþ worschupe, &amp; þou hast y-ordeyned hym up-on þe werkes of þin honden: alle þinges þou hast y-mad soget vnder his fet.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.8" type="verse">&amp; in þat it haþ y-mad alle þinges soget to hym, he ne lefed no þing þat ne was soget to hym. Bote ȝet we ne seþ noȝt alle þinges soget to hym.
<seg id="b.HEB.2.9" type="verse">And we seþ hym þat was y-mad luytel lasse þan aungeles, Iesus, for þe suffrenge of deþ y-corowned wiþ ioye &amp; wiþ worschupe, þat þe grace of God schulde for alle men taste þe deþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.10" type="verse">Wherfore ich was wroþ to þis generacyoun, &amp; y seyde, Þese erreþ efermore in hure herte: bote þei knewen noȝt my
<seg id="b.HEB.3.11" type="verse">weyes; &amp; y swor to hem in my wraþþe, þat þei ne schulden noȝt entren in-to my reste.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.12" type="verse">And breþeren, loke ȝe, wheþer
<seg id="b.HEB.3.13" type="verse">ȝou from þe lyfynge God; bote prefeþ ȝou-selfe by eferich day, whyles þat þis day is nempned, wheþer eny of ȝou be yharded
<seg id="b.HEB.3.14" type="verse">þoroȝ þe fallas of synne: for we beþ y-mad partyneres of Crist, ȝef þat we holdeþ þe bygynnynge of his substaunce
<seg id="b.HEB.3.15" type="verse">to þe ende: whyles it is y-sayd, To day ȝef ȝe hereþ his voys, ne harde ȝe noȝt ȝoure hertes, as þei duden in hure tarrynge.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.16" type="verse">For summe tarreden hym, bote noȝt alle þilke þat comen out of Egypt by Moyses.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.17" type="verse">Bote to whom was he wroþ fourty ȝere? bote to þilke þat synneden, whos careynes weren þrowen a-down in desert.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.18" type="verse">And to whom swor he þat þei schulden noȝt entren in-to his reste, bote to þilke þat weren vnbylefynge?
<seg id="b.HEB.3.19" type="verse">&amp; we seþ þat þei ne myȝte not entren in-to his reste for hure vnbylefynge.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.1" type="verse">Wherfore, ȝe holy breþeren þat beþ partyneres of an hefenlyche clepynge, byholde ȝe þe apostul &amp; þe byschop
<seg id="b.HEB.3.2" type="verse">of ȝoure knowlechynge, Iesus, þat is trewe to hym þat made hym, as Moyses was in al his hous.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.3" type="verse">Bote þes is worþi to muche more worschupe þan Moyses, as muche more as he is worþi þat makeþ an hous þan þe hous.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.4" type="verse">For eferich hous is y-buld of sum man; bote he þat made alle þinges he is God.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.5" type="verse">&amp; Moyses was trewe in al his hous as a serfaunt, in witnesse of þilke þinges þat weren to seyen þer-aftur.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.6" type="verse">Bote Crist is as a sone in his hous; whyche hous we beþ, ȝef it so be þat we holden oure trust &amp; þe ioye of oure hope sadlyche to þe ende.
<seg id="b.HEB.3.7" type="verse">Wherfore þe Holy Spiryt saiþ, To day ȝef ȝee
<seg id="b.HEB.3.8" type="verse">hereþ his voyce, ne harde ȝe noȝt ȝoure hertes, after þe day of temptacyoun, þat ȝoure fadrus tempteden me in desert,
<seg id="b.HEB.3.9" type="verse">where þei prefeden me and syen my werkes fourty ȝeres.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.10" type="verse">For he þat entred in-to his reste, he rested from his werkes, as God dude from his werkes.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.11" type="verse">&amp; þerfore hyȝe we to entren in-to þat reste, þat no man falle in-to þat ensampel of
<seg id="b.HEB.4.12" type="verse">For Goddes word is lyfynge, &amp; spedful, &amp; more persynge þan eny two-egged swerd: for he comeþ to þe departynge of þe soule &amp; of þe spiryt, &amp; of þe myndes &amp; of þe maryȝes, &amp; knowere of þoȝtes &amp; of þe willes of þe herte. &amp; þer ne is no creature invysybel in his syȝt.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.13" type="verse">Bote alle þinges beþ naked &amp; opne to his yen to whom oure speche is.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.14" type="verse">And þerfore we þat haueþ a gret byschop þat haþ y-persed hefnes, Iesu Goddes Sone, holde we þe knowlechynge of oure hope.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.15" type="verse">For we ne haueþ no bischop þat ne may haue compassyoun to oure infirmytees, þat haþ ben y-tempted by alle Þinges to oure lyknesse wiþ-outen synne.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.16" type="verse">And þerfore go we wiþ trust to þe throne of his grace, þat we han mercy &amp; y-fynden grace in cofenabel help.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.1" type="verse">And þerfore drede we, leste þe byheste be y-lafte to entren in-to his reste, leste þer be y-founde any of ous fayle þer-hennes .
<seg id="b.HEB.4.2" type="verse">For it is y-told to ous, as it was to hem; bote þe word þat þei herden ne profyted hem noȝt, for it ne was noȝt y-medled wiþ bylefe.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.3" type="verse">For we þat haueþ bylefed schuleþ entren in-to reste , as he sayde, As ich haue y-swore in my wraþþe, þei ne schuleþ noȝt entren in-to my reste. And whanne in þe bygynnynge of þe worlde he hade parformed
<seg id="b.HEB.4.4" type="verse">his werkes, he saiþ in on place of þe sefeþe day in þis wyse,
<seg id="b.HEB.4.5" type="verse">God rested þe sefeþe day from alle his werkes; &amp; in þis place also, Þei ne schuleþ noȝt entren in-to my reste.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.6" type="verse">And for þat summe entreden in-to þat reste, &amp; þilke þat weren byfore to whom it was y-told, ne entrede noȝt in-to þat reste,
<seg id="b.HEB.4.7" type="verse">þerfore he setteþ a certeyn day, To day, in Dauyd seyenge as it is y-sayd abofen, aftur so muche tyme, To day ȝef ȝe hereþ his voys, ne harde ȝe noȝt ȝoure hertes.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.8" type="verse">And ȝef Iesus hade y-ȝefen hem reste, he ne wolde nefer aftur han y-spoken of þis day.
<seg id="b.HEB.4.9" type="verse">And þerfore þer is y-laft a day of reste to Goddes pepel.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.10" type="verse">a cause of an eferlastynge hele; &amp; of God he was y-cleped a byschop aftur þe order of Melchysedech.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.11" type="verse">Of whom þer is to ous a gret speche þat may noȝt ben expouned, for ȝe beþ y-maad ful febel for-to heren.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.12" type="verse">For þouȝ ȝe oweden to ben maystres for tyme, ȝow byhoueþ aȝeynward to ben y-tauȝt whuche beþ þe elementes of þe bygynnynge of Goddes wordes.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.13" type="verse">For eferich man þat is partener of mylk, he is wiþ-outen part of þe word of ryȝtfulnesse; for he is a smal chyld.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.14" type="verse">Bote sad mete is of parfyt men, of hem þat by costom han hure wyttes y-vsed to discrecyoun of good and of yuel.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.1" type="verse">For euerych byschop þat is y-taken up of men, he is y-ordeyned for men in þese þinges þat beþ to God: to offren
<seg id="b.HEB.5.2" type="verse">ȝiftes &amp; sacryfyces for oure synnes; þat may sorowen wiþ hem þat beþ vnkunnynge &amp; erreþ, for he hymselfe is
<seg id="b.HEB.5.3" type="verse">enuyroned aboute wiþ infirmyte; and þerfore he is y-holde to offren for hym-self &amp; his synnes, as for þe pepel &amp; hure synnes.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.4" type="verse">Ne no man takeþ worschype to hymselfen, bote he þat is y-cleped of God, as Aaron.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.5" type="verse">So Cryst ne claryfyed noȝt hym-selfen, þat he were y-maad a byschop, bote he þat spake to hym &amp; sayde, Þou art my sone, to day ich haue bygete þe.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.6" type="verse">As he seiþ in an oþer place, Þou art an euerlastynge prest aftur þe ordre of Melchysedech.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.7" type="verse">&amp; he in þe dayes of his flesch offred preyeres &amp; bysechynges wiþ gret cry &amp; wiþ teres to hym þat myȝte safen hym from deþ, &amp; for his reverence he was y-herd.
<seg id="b.HEB.5.8" type="verse">And ȝet whan he was Goddes sone, he lerned
<seg id="b.HEB.5.9" type="verse">obedyence of þinges þat he suffred; &amp; he þat was y-broȝt to an ende, was y-maad to alle þilke þat boweþ hem to hym
<seg id="b.HEB.6.10" type="verse">þus: for God ne is noȝt vnryȝtful, þat he wole forȝeten ȝoure werk &amp; ȝoure lofe þat ȝe han y-schewed in his name: for ȝe han y-mynystred to goode men &amp; ȝet ȝe doþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.11" type="verse">&amp; we desyre þat eferich of ȝou schewe oftesyþes þe same bysynesse to
<seg id="b.HEB.6.12" type="verse">fulfullynge of ȝoure hope to þe ende: þat ȝe ben noȝt y-mad slowe, bote foleweres of hem þat by feiþ &amp; pacyence schulleþ an-heryten þe byhestes.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.13" type="verse">For God þat made his byheste to Abraham, for he ne hade no grettour to swere by, he swor by
<seg id="b.HEB.6.14" type="verse">hym-selfe &amp; sayde, Ich wole blesse þe, &amp; ich wole multyplye þe.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.15" type="verse">And so wiþ his longe abydynge he get his byheste.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.16" type="verse">For men swereþ by hym þat is grettur þan þei beþ; &amp; þe confirmacyoun of þe ende of eferich ple is an oþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.17" type="verse">In þe whuche þing God, þat wolde schewen to eyres þe immebelnesse of his
<seg id="b.HEB.6.18" type="verse">conseyl, putte by-twene a gret oþ: þat þorow tweyne immebel þinges, in þe whuche it is im-possybel for God to lye, we han þe strengest solas; we þat goþ to-gedere to
<seg id="b.HEB.6.19" type="verse">holde þis forseyd hope, þe whuche we han as a syker &amp; a stabel anker of oure soule, &amp; goynge in-to þe inwardnesse
<seg id="b.HEB.6.1" type="verse">Werfore we woleþ senden in a word of þe bygynnynge of Crist, &amp; passen forþ to a more parfyt; noȝt castynge aȝeyn þe foundement of penawnce from dede werkes, &amp; of feiþ
<seg id="b.HEB.6.20" type="verse">of þe huydynge; wher Iesus, oure byfore-goere, entred in for ous, y-mad an eferlastynge byschop aftur Melchysedekes ordre.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.2" type="verse">to God, &amp; of baptysmes, &amp; of techynge also of puttynge of hondes, &amp; of arysynge aȝeyn of dede men, &amp; of þe eferlastynge dom.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.3" type="verse">&amp; þis we woleþ don, ȝef þat God wole leten us.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.4" type="verse">For it is im-possybele to þilke þat beþ ones y-lyȝted &amp; han y-tasted an hefenlyche ȝefte, &amp; beþ y-made parteneres
<seg id="b.HEB.6.5" type="verse">of þe holy Spiryt, &amp; han y-tasted also þe goode word of God,
<seg id="b.HEB.6.6" type="verse">&amp; þe vertues of þe worlde þat is to comynge, &amp; beþ y-slyde a-ȝeyn, to ben renewed aȝen to penaunce. For þei crucyfyeþ aȝeyn Goddes sone to hem-seluen, &amp; han hym to a spectakel.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.7" type="verse">For þe erþe þat drynkeþ þe reyn þat falleþ ofte syþes up-on hym, &amp; bryngeþ forþ a cofenabel herbe to þilke men þat heo
<seg id="b.HEB.6.8" type="verse">is y-tyled of, vnderfongeþ blessynge of God: bote ȝef heo bryngeþ forþ breres &amp; þornes , heo is nyȝ cursynge; &amp; þe ende þer-of is to ben y-brand.
<seg id="b.HEB.6.9" type="verse">Bote, my lefeste breþeren, we trusteþ of ȝou beter þinges and neer to hele, þouȝ we speken
<seg id="b.HEB.7.10" type="verse">vnderfong ten-þinges, was y-tenþed; for he was ȝet in his fader lendes, whanne þat Melchysedek mette wiþ hym.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.11" type="verse">And þer-fore ȝef þer hade y-ben an ende by þe presthod of Leui—for vnder þat presthod þe pepel vnderfong þe lawe—what had it be nedful þat þer hade rysen up an-oþer prest aftur
<seg id="b.HEB.7.12" type="verse">For ȝef þe presthode be y-translated, it mot nede ben þat þer be y-mad a translacyoun of þe lawe.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.13" type="verse">For in hym of whom þese þinges beþ y-sayd it is of an-oþer kynrede, of þe whuche kynrede þer ne was non ordeyned to þe auter.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.14" type="verse">For it is open y-knowe þat oure Lord was y-boren of þe kynrede of Iuda; in þe whuche kynrede Moyses spak no þing of prestes.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.15" type="verse">And ȝet furþer-more it is openlyche y-knowe þat, ȝef þer is a-rysen up an-oþer prest aftur þe lyknesse of Melchysedech,
<seg id="b.HEB.7.16" type="verse">þat ne is noȝt y-mad after þe lawe of þe fleschlyche comaundement, bote aftur þe vertu of a lyf þat may not ben vndon.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.17" type="verse">For he bereþ wytnesse, Þat þou art an eferlastynge prest aftur þe order of Melchisedech.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.18" type="verse">Þanne is þe raþere comaundement
<seg id="b.HEB.7.19" type="verse">reprefed for his infirmyte &amp; his vnprofytabelnesse: for þe lawe brouȝte no man to perfeccyoun. Bote þer is a bryngynge in of a betur hope, by þe whuche we neyȝlacheþ to God.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.1" type="verse">For þes Melchysedek , kyng of Salem, and a prest of þe heyeste God, þat mette wiþ Abraham whenne he come
<seg id="b.HEB.7.20" type="verse">In as muche as it ne is noȝt wiþ-outen a gret oþ—for
<seg id="b.HEB.7.21" type="verse">þe oþer weren y-mad prestes wiþ-outen a gret swerynge bote þes was wiþ a gret swerynge by hym þat sayde to hym, Oure
<seg id="b.HEB.7.22" type="verse">Lord haþ ysworen &amp; it ne schal noȝt a-þinken hym, Þou art an euerlastynge prest—&amp; in so muche Iesu Crist is y-made a byhoter of a beter testement.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.23" type="verse">And þe oþer weren y-mad many prestes, for as muche as þoroȝ deþ þei weren forboden
<seg id="b.HEB.7.24" type="verse">to dwellen efermore stille: bote þes, in þat he dwelleþ efermore,
<seg id="b.HEB.7.25" type="verse">he haþ an eferlastynge presthode. Wherfore he may efermore safen, neyȝenge by hym-selfen to God, &amp; lyfynge efermore to byseche God for ous.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.26" type="verse">For it by-semed þat oure byschop were holy, innocent, im-pollut, departed from synful
<seg id="b.HEB.7.27" type="verse">men, &amp; y-mad heyȝer þan hefnes; þat haþ no nede eferich day, as oþer prestes, furst to offren for hure owne gyltes sacryfyces &amp; seþþe for þe pepel: for þat he dude ones, offrynge hym-self.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.28" type="verse">And þe lawe ordeyneþ men to ben prestes, þat habbeþ infyrmyte; bote þe word of þe grete swerynge, þat is aftur þe lawe, ordeyneþ þe sone þat is efermore parfyt .
<seg id="b.HEB.7.2" type="verse">aȝeyn from þe sleynge of kynges, &amp; blessed hym, to whom Abraham departed þe tenþinges of al his good; &amp; he was furst y-cleped Kyng of ryȝtfulnesse, &amp; afturward Kyng of
<seg id="b.HEB.7.3" type="verse">Salem, þat is, Kyng of pees; wiþ-outen fadur, wiþ-outen moder, wiþ-outen kynrede, nouþer hade bygynnynge of his dayes ne ende of his lyf, bote y-lykned to Goddes Sone, he duelleþ stille an eferlastynge prest.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.4" type="verse">Bote byholdeþ how gret þes is, to whom Abraham ȝef tenþinges þat was on of þe moste worþy patryarkes.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.5" type="verse">For þilke þat weren of þe children of Leui þat vnderfongen presthod haden a comaundement to take tenþinges of þe pepel, after þe lawe of hure owne breþeren, þouȝ þat þei passeden out of Abrahames lendes.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.6" type="verse">Bote he whos generacyoun ne is noȝt y-nombred a-mong hem tok tenþinges of Abraham, &amp; blessed hym þat hade þe repromyssyones.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.7" type="verse">Bote wiþ-outen any aȝeyn-seyenge þat þing þat is lasse is yblessed of þat þing þat is beter.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.8" type="verse">&amp; here men þat dyeþ takeþ tenþinges; bote þere it is y-wytnessed þat he lyfeþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.7.9" type="verse">And ȝef it mowe be seyd so, by Abraham Leui, þat
<seg id="b.HEB.8.10" type="verse">For þis is þe testement þat ich wole ordeyne to þe hous of Israel aftur þilke dayes, God seiþ, ich wole ȝeue my lawe in hure þouȝt
<seg id="b.HEB.8.11" type="verse">þei schuleþ be my pepel: and eferich man ne schal noȝt seye to his nexte neyȝbore, ne to his broþer, Knowe þou God: for alle þei schulleþ knowe me, from þe leste to þe meste.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.12" type="verse">For ich wole forȝeuen hem hure synnes, &amp; y nul noȝt haue muynde on hem þer-aftur.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.13" type="verse">And in suggynge, A newe, he made þe raþere waxen old. &amp; þat þing þat waxeþ old is nyȝ his dystruccioun.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.1" type="verse">A chapytre on þilke þinges þat beþ y-sayd: we han suche a byschop, þat sitteþ in þe ryȝtsyde of þe sege of þe
<seg id="b.HEB.8.2" type="verse">Gretnesse of God an hyȝ in hefne, mynyster of seyntes &amp; of þe verrey tabernakel, þat God made, &amp; noȝt man.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.3" type="verse">For eferich byschop is ordeyned to offren ȝeftes &amp; sacryfyces: wherfore it is nedful þat he haue sumwhat forto offren.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.4" type="verse">And þerfore ȝef were up-on þe erþe, ne were no prest, when þer weren þilke þat schulden offre ȝeftes aftur þe
<seg id="b.HEB.8.5" type="verse">lawe, þat serfed to þe ensampler &amp; þe schadewe of hefnelyche þinges; as it was y-answerd to Moyses, when he schulde make þe tabernakel, Loke , God sayde, þat þou make alle þinges as it was y-schewed to þe in þe hul.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.6" type="verse">Bote now þer is y-comen a beter serfynge, by as muche as þe medyatour is of a beter testement, þat is y-halewed in beter byhestes.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.7" type="verse">For ȝef þat raþere hade y-ben wiþ-outen blame, þe place of þe secounde ne schulde noȝt haue ben y-soȝt.
<seg id="b.HEB.8.8" type="verse">Bote God, blamynge hem, saiþ, Lo, dayes comeþ, God saiþ, &amp; ich wole bryngen on þe hous of Israel &amp; on þe hous of Iuda a newe
<seg id="b.HEB.8.9" type="verse">testement; noȝt aftur þat testement þat y made to hure fadres in þat day þat y toke hure hond to bryngen hem out of þe lond of Egypt; for þei ne dwelled not stille in myn testement, &amp; y dispysed hem, saiþ God.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.10" type="verse">&amp; drynkes &amp; dyuerse waschynges &amp; riȝtfulnesse of þe flesch, þat weren y-ordeyned in-to þe tyme of correccyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.11" type="verse">Bote Crist þat is a byschop of goodes þat beþ to comynge, a more large &amp; a more parfyt tabernakel, noȝt y-mad wiþ
<seg id="b.HEB.9.12" type="verse">honden, þat is to seyn, noȝt of þis creacyoun, nouþer by gotes blod ne by calfes blod, bote þoroȝ his owne blod he entred in-to holy places þat weren y-founden by an eferlastynge redempcyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.13" type="verse">For ȝef þat gotes blod oþer boles blod, oþer þe aschen of a cow-calf y-spreynd on men, haleweþ
<seg id="b.HEB.9.14" type="verse">hem þat beþ defouled to þe clansynge of hure flesch: how muche more schal Cristes blod, þat by þe Holy Gost offred hym-selfe wiþ-outen wem to God, make clene hure conscyence from dede werkes to serue þe lyuynge God?
<seg id="b.HEB.9.15" type="verse">And þerfore he is a medyatour of a newe testement, þat, þoroȝ þe bysechynge of deþ in forbuggynge of þe preuarycaciones þat
<seg id="b.HEB.9.16" type="verse">For þer as is a testament, it is nedful þat þe deþ go bytwene of hym þat oweþ þe testament.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.17" type="verse">For a testement in dede men is y-confermyd: for it a-vayleþ noȝt whyles he lyueþ þat makeþ þe testement.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.18" type="verse">Wherfore þe furste ne was noȝt y-halewed wiþ-oute blod.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.19" type="verse">For whanne þat eferich comaundement of þe lawe was y-rad of Moyses to al þe pepel, he toke gotes blod &amp; calfes blod, wiþ water &amp; red wolle &amp; ysope, &amp; spreynde þe bok &amp; al þe
<seg id="b.HEB.9.1" type="verse">And þe raþere hade iustifyenges &amp; an holy seculer.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.20" type="verse">pepel, &amp; sayde, Þis is þe blod of þe testement þat God haþ y-send to ȝow.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.21" type="verse">He spreynde also wiþ blod þe tabernakel &amp; alle þe vesseles þat serfeden þer-to.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.22" type="verse">And almost alle þinges beþ y-mad clene wiþ blod aftur þe lawe, &amp; wiþ-outen schedynge of blod þer ne is y-mad no remyssyoun.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.23" type="verse">And þerfore it is nedeful þat þe sampleres of hefenlyche þinges ben y-mad clene þoroȝ þese þinges; bote þilke hefenliche þinges roȝ muche betur þinges þan þese beþ.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.24" type="verse">For Iesu ne entred noȝt in-to holy places y-mad wiþ honden, þat beþ sampleres of verrey places; bote in-to þe self hefne, þat he
<seg id="b.HEB.9.25" type="verse">appere now to þe syȝt of God for ous: and noȝt þat he offre felesyþes hym-selfe, as þe byschop doþ wiþ-ynne holy places,
<seg id="b.HEB.9.26" type="verse">eferich ȝer in an-oþer þinges blod; oþer it hade byhoued hym fele syþes to haue y-suffred from þe bygynnynge of þe worlde. Bote now he apered ones in þe ende of þe worlde to distruccioun of synne by his owne sacrifyce.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.27" type="verse">&amp; riȝt as it was y-ordeyned
<seg id="b.HEB.9.28" type="verse">to men for-to dyen ones &amp; syþþe comen to dom; ryȝt so Crist was y-offred ones to þe clensynge of many mennes synnes, &amp; in þe secounde tyme he schal appere to hem þat abydeþ hym in-to hele.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.2" type="verse">For þe tabernakel was furst y-mad, in whom þer weren
<seg id="b.HEB.9.3" type="verse">Bote aftur þe veyl þer is þe secounde tabernakel
<seg id="b.HEB.9.4" type="verse">, þat is y-sayd holy þinge of holy þinges, þat haþ a censer of gold, &amp; þe arke of þe testement wiþ helynge on eferich syde of gold; in þe arke þer is a pot of gold þat is wiþ manna, &amp; Aarones ȝerde þat broȝte forþ bowes, &amp; þe tables of
<seg id="b.HEB.9.5" type="verse">þe testament; &amp; abouen þese þinges was Cherubyn of blisse ferschadewynge þe propycyatorye; of whuche it ne is noȝt now to speken of sundrylyche.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.6" type="verse">&amp; whenne alle þese þinges weren þus y-ordeyned, in þe furste tabernakel entred in prestes efermore, doynge þe offyces of sacryfyces.
<seg id="b.HEB.9.7" type="verse">Bote in þe secounde tabernakel þe byschop al-one, ones in þe ȝer, schulde entren in, noȝt wiþ-outen blod, þat he schulde offren
<seg id="b.HEB.9.8" type="verse">for his owene vnkunnyngnesse &amp; þe peples also: &amp; þis sygnyfyeþ þe Holy Spiryt, þat ȝet noȝt holy mennes lyfynge ne was noȝt y-schewed, whiles þe raþer tabernakel hade his
<seg id="b.HEB.9.9" type="verse">stondynge; þe whuche parable is of þe tyme þat is nowþe , by whom ȝeftes and sacrifyces beþ y-offred, þat mowe noȝt maken hym þat serfeþ parfyt in his conscyence, in metes
<seg id="b.JAM.1.10" type="verse">And an humel broþer ioye he in hys hyȝenesse, &amp; a ryche man in his lowenesse: For as þe flour of þe gras he schal passe forþ his weye.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.10" type="verse">a riche man soþely make ioye in his mekenesse. For as þe floure of þe heyȝe schal he passe.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.11" type="verse">For þe sunne haþ y-rysen up wiþ hete, &amp; haþ y-druyed ·þe heþ; &amp; his flour is y-fallen a-down, &amp; his fayrnesse is y-perysched: so a ryche man schal welewen in his iourneyes.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.11" type="verse">Soþely þe sunne wiþ his hete dryeþ the heyȝe; s floure fallith, &amp; þe fayrnesse of his semblante peryschiþ: so schal þe riche man in his weyes wexe drye.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.12" type="verse">Blessid is þat man þat suffreþ temptacyon: for whanne he is prouyd, he schal take þe coroune of lyf þat God haþ byhote to hem þat louen him.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.12" type="verse">Þat man is y-blessed þat suffreþ temptacyoun: for whanne he is y-prefed, he schal vnderfonge a coroune of lyf, þat God haþ byhoten to þilke þat loueþ hym.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.13" type="verse">&amp; no man
<seg id="b.JAM.1.13" type="verse">No man whan he is temptud seiþ, I am tempted of God: soþely God is an vntemptar of wickede men, soþely he tempteþ no man.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.14" type="verse">But echone for-soþe is temptyd , of his desyris wiþ-drawen, &amp; oute of himself ledde.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.14" type="verse">man: bote eferiche man is i-tempted þoroȝ sterynge &amp; drawynge of his owne coueytyse.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.15" type="verse">&amp; after whan þat mannes coueytyse haþ y-conseyued, he bryngeþ forþ synne: &amp; whan þe synne is y-don, it bygeteþ deþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.15" type="verse">&amp; so whan wille haþ conseyuyd, it bryngeþ forþ synne: soþely synne whan it is endyd engendereþ deeþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.16" type="verse">&amp; þerfore, my lefe breþeren, ne wele ȝee noȝt erre.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.16" type="verse">&amp; þerfore, my leueste bryþeren, ne erre ȝe noȝt.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.17" type="verse">Alle þe beste þing þat is ȝeue &amp; alle parfite ȝefte it is from a-boue, comynge down from þe Fadir of lyȝte, wiþ whom is no chaungynge, ne no derknesse of synne.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.17" type="verse">Eferich ȝeft þat is best &amp; parfyt is from abouen, comynge adoun from þe Fader of lyȝtes, at whom ne is non chaungynge, ne ouer-schadewynge of rewardynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.18" type="verse">For wylfullyche he haþ bygeten ous þoroȝ þe word of trewþe, þat we ben sum bygynnynge of his creature.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.18" type="verse">Soþely wiþ his good fre wille he gate us þurgh þe word of soþfastnesse, þat we be some bygynnynge of his creature.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.19" type="verse">&amp; wyte ȝe wel, my dereste breþeren, eferich man be swyft
<seg id="b.JAM.1.19" type="verse">Wyte ȝee, my deere loued breþeren, be euery man smert for-to here &amp; late for-to speke &amp; late vn-to yre:
<seg id="b.JAM.1.1" type="verse">Iamys þe seruaunt of God &amp; of oure Lord Iesu Criste, to þe twelue kynredis þat beþ spred a-brode, gretynge wel.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.1" type="verse">James þat is a seruaunt of oure Lord &amp; oure God Iesu Crist, to þe twelue kynredes þat beþ in dyspersyon, hele and gretynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.20" type="verse">forte heren &amp; slow for-to speken &amp; slow to wraþþe: For a mannes wraþþe ne worcheþ noȝt þe ryȝtfulnesse of God.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.20" type="verse">soþely þe wraþþe of man wurcheþ noȝt þe riȝtwisnesse of God.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.21" type="verse">&amp; þerfore caste ȝe awey from ȝow eferych vnclennesse &amp; plente of wyckednesse, &amp; in goodnesse vnderfonge ȝe þe word þat is y-sowe to ȝow, þat may saue ȝoure soules.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.21" type="verse">&amp; þerfore kastynge a-wey alle vnclennesse &amp; abundaunce of malice, myldenesse takeþ to drynke þe word, þat may saue ȝoure soulis.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.22" type="verse">Beþ also doeres of þe word &amp; wyrcheres, but not only þe hereres, disceyuynge ȝoure-selfe.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.22" type="verse">Bote be ȝe doeres of þe word, and noȝt onlyche hereris, bygylynge ȝowselfe.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.23" type="verse">For who-so is herere of Godes worde, &amp; not doere, he may be lykkened to a man þat byldeþ þe semblaunt of his birþe in a myroure:
<seg id="b.JAM.1.23" type="verse">For who þat is an herer of þe word, &amp; noȝt a doere, þerafter he schal be lyckned to a man þat byholdeþ hymselfen
<seg id="b.JAM.1.24" type="verse">he byhelde him soþly, &amp; ȝede a-wey, &amp; a-noon he haþ forȝete what he was.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.24" type="verse">in a myrour: for he haþ byholden hymself, &amp; wente forþ his weye, and anon he haþ forȝeten whyche he was.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.25" type="verse">Bote he þat byholdeþ in þe lawe of parfyt fredom, &amp; duelleþ þerynne, &amp; ne is noȝt y-mad a forȝetful herer, bote a doere of þe werk, he is y-blessyd in his doynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.25" type="verse">For-soþe he þat lokeþ in þe lawe of parfite frenesse, and dwelliþ þer-inne, he is not maked a forȝetful hyrer, but a doere of þe worke: here in his deede he schal be blessid.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.26" type="verse">&amp; who þat troweþ hym-selfe a relygyous man, &amp; refreyneþ noȝt his tunge bote bygyleþ his owne herte, his relygyoun is veyn.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.26" type="verse">Soþely who-so wenyþ him-self þat he be religyous, noȝt wiþ-holdynge his tunge but disseyuynge his herte, veyne is his religyoun.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.27" type="verse">A clene relygyoun &amp; wiþ-outen wem to-fore God &amp; þe Fader þis is, to vysyten faderles chyldren and moderles, &amp; wydewes in hure trybulacyoun, &amp; to kepen hym-self wiþ-outen wem from þis worlde.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.27" type="verse">Clene religioun &amp; vnfiled as to God &amp; þe Fadur is þis, to vysite fadurles children, &amp; wydows in here tribulacyoun, &amp; from al þis worlde to kepe hem clene, vnfouled.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.2" type="verse">Breþeren, trowe ȝe þat it be eferych gladnesse whan ȝe falleþ in-to dyuerse temptacyons,
<seg id="b.JAM.1.2" type="verse">My deere breþeren, wite ȝee &amp; hopeþ alle ioye whanne þat ȝe been in many temptacyonus,
<seg id="b.JAM.1.3" type="verse">knowynge þat þe prefynge of ȝoure feiþ worcheþ pacyence.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.3" type="verse">wite ȝee wel þat prouynge of ȝoure feiþ worcheþ pacyence.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.4" type="verse">And pacyence haþ a parfyt werk, þat ȝe ben parfyt &amp; hol, faylynge in no þing.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.4" type="verse">Pacience soþeliche haþ a parfyte worke, þat ȝee be parfit &amp; hole, faylynge in no þinge.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.5" type="verse">&amp; whuche of ȝow so haþ nede of wysdom, aske of God þat ȝeueþ plentyuously to alle, &amp; withstonde him nouȝte, &amp; it schal be ȝoue to him.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.5" type="verse">And who-efere of ȝou nedeþ wysdom, axe he of God, þat graunteþ eferich man plentyuouslyche and obbraydeþ no man.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.6" type="verse">&amp; axe he in feiþ &amp; trust, doutynge no þing: For he þat douteþ is lyche to þe flod of þe see þat is y-mefed &amp; y-boren aboute of þe wynd.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.6" type="verse">Aske he soþely in feiþ, nouȝte faylynge: for soþely he þat is faylynge (þat is, faylynge in þe feiþ) he is lyke to þe flowynge of þe see þe whuche is meuyd wiþ þe wynde &amp; bore a-boute.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore trowe he noȝt þat is suche a man eny þinge to take of God.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.7" type="verse">And þerfore þilke man ne trowe noȝt þat he schal vnderfonge any þing of God;
<seg id="b.JAM.1.8" type="verse">A man of double wille is vnstable in alle weyes.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.8" type="verse">A man þat is doubel in soule, he is vnstabel in alle his weyes.
<seg id="b.JAM.1.9" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.JAM.1.9" type="verse">Soþely make he ioye þat is a meke broþer in his hye state,
<seg id="b.JAM.2.10" type="verse">&amp; who þat kepeþ al þe lawe, &amp; offendeþ in on þing, he is y-mad gulty of al þe lawe.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.10" type="verse">Who-so-euere soþly keepe al þe lawe, &amp; trespaseþ in o þinge, þat is forbodyn in þe lawe, he is maked gilty of alle.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.11" type="verse">For he þat bad ȝow not synne in leccherye, he bad þat þou schuldest not slee. If þat þou do no leccherye, and sleist any man, þou art þanne trespasere &amp; brekere of þe lawe.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.11" type="verse">For he þat seyde, Þow schal do no leccherye, seyde also, Þow schalt not sleen. &amp; ȝef þow dost no leccherye, bote sleest, þow art y-mad a trespasour of þe lawe.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.12" type="verse">So speke ȝe, &amp; so do ȝe, as þouȝ ȝe bygonne to ben y-demed by þe lawe of fredom.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.12" type="verse">So speke ȝee, &amp; so dowte ȝee, so þat by þe lawe of frenes (þat is, þe lawe of mercy) ȝee schal mowe be demed.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.13" type="verse">For soþly to him þat dooþ no mercy schal be doe wiþ-oute mercy: but soþly mercy ouergoþ dome.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.13" type="verse">For to hym þat doþ no mercy þer is a dom wiþ-outen mercy: for mercy heueþ vp an hyȝ dom.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.14" type="verse">And my breþeren, what prophyteþ it, ȝef a man sayþ þat he haþ feiþ, &amp; ne haþ noȝt werkes ? wheþer his feiþ mowe sauen hym?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.14" type="verse">What schal profyte to man, my lef breþeren, ȝif eny seye þat he haþ feiþ, &amp; he soþely haue nouȝt þe deede? ne may not feiþ saue him?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.15" type="verse">And ȝef a broþer oþer a suster be naked, oþer haue nede to hure
<seg id="b.JAM.2.15" type="verse">Soþly if eny broþer or sister ben naked, &amp; neden eche day sustynaunce,
<seg id="b.JAM.2.16" type="verse">and if eny of ȝow sey to hem, Goþ forþ in pees, &amp; be ȝee hole &amp; ȝee fedde; &amp; ȝee ȝeue hem nouȝt þat nedeful is to here body, what schal it profyte hem?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.16" type="verse">eferyche dayes lyflode, &amp; on of ȝow seye, Be ȝe y-warmed , oþer, Be ȝe fulfillyd; &amp; ne ȝefe hem noȝt þat is nedeful to þe body, what profyteþ it?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.17" type="verse">Ryȝt so feiþ, ȝef he ne haue none werkes, he is deed in hym-selfen.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.17" type="verse">Ryȝt so feiþ, if it haue nouȝt deedis, it is dede in it-self.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.18" type="verse">Bote sum man seyþ , Þow hast feiþ, &amp; ich haue werkes: schewe me þi feiþ wiþouten werkes, &amp; ich wole of my werkes schewe þe my feiþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.18" type="verse">But some seiþ, Þou hast feiþ, &amp; I haue dedis: schewe me þi feiþ wiþ-outen werkes, &amp; I schal schewe þe my feiþ þorow my werkes.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.19" type="verse">Þow
<seg id="b.JAM.2.19" type="verse">Þow trowest þat þer is o God, þou doost weel: &amp; deueles trowe it &amp; quaken.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.1" type="verse">And my dere breþeren, ne haue ȝe noȝt þe feiþ of þe blysse of oure Lord Iesu Crist in vnderfongynge of mennes
<seg id="b.JAM.2.1" type="verse">My breþeren, ne wele ȝe noȝt be oute-takeres of persones (þat is, take mannys persone in more state a-ȝens God for his hye kyn, ne for his riches, ne powere in þis worlde, hauynge feiþ þat God takeþ more hede to hem for here gentil kyn, or here grete richesse, or here muchel myȝt, or here sotil witte þan he doþ to þe pore þat loueþ him as welle)g.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.20" type="verse">byleuest þat þer ne is bote on God, &amp; þow dost wel: &amp; fendes byleueþ &amp; quakeþ for drede. Bote wolt þou y-wyte, þow veyn man, þat feiþ is ded wiþ-outen werkus?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.20" type="verse">Þou veyne man, wilt þou wite, how þat feiþ wiþ-outen werkes is deed?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.21" type="verse">Abraham oure fader ne was noȝt he y-iustyfyed of his werkes, offrynge Ysaac his sone up-on þe auter?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.21" type="verse">Abraham oure fadur ne was he noȝt þorw his werkes maked ryȝtwyse, offerrynge Ysaac his sone on an auter?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.22" type="verse">Lo, hou feiþ was wrouȝt þorow his deedis, &amp; þorow werkes feiþ is endid;
<seg id="b.JAM.2.22" type="verse">Ne seest þou þanne, þat feiþ helped his werkes, &amp; of werkes feiþ was y-broȝt to an
<seg id="b.JAM.2.23" type="verse">&amp; þe scripture is fulfillid þat seiþ, Abraham trowed to God, &amp; it is putt him to riȝtwisnesse; &amp; he is clepid Godis freend.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.23" type="verse">ende; &amp; þe scripture was fulfilled þat seyde, Abraham byleued to his God, &amp; it was y-holde to hym for ryȝtfulnesse; &amp; he was y-cleped Godes frend.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.24" type="verse">Ne seo ȝe not þanne þat a man is y-iustyfyed of his werkes, &amp; noȝt of feiþ alone?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.24" type="verse">Now ȝe se how þat man is maked riȝtwyse þorow his werkes, &amp; nouȝt only þorow feiþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.25" type="verse">Also Raab þe hore ne was noȝt heo y-iustyfyed of hure werkes, vnderfongynge Goddes messyngeres, &amp; letynge hem gon out an oþer weye?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.25" type="verse">On þe same wyse also Raab þe hore ne is sche not maked riȝtwyse þorow here werkes , takynge messageres, &amp; by oþer weye kastynge a-wey wickednesse?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.26" type="verse">&amp; ryȝt as þe body is deed wiþ-outen spiryt, so feiþ is ded with-outen werkes.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.26" type="verse">Soþly riȝt as þe body wiþ-outen þe soule is deed, so is feiþ wiþ-outen good werkes deed.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.2" type="verse">&amp; þerfore if eny man come in-to ȝoure siȝt (that is, in-to ȝoure cumpenye þat beþ Godes religiouse men in what degre so ȝe be) , þe whuche haþ gold rynge on his fynger &amp; schynynge cloþus, &amp; anoþer pore man in symple &amp; feble cloþinge come also to ȝow;
<seg id="b.JAM.2.2" type="verse">For ȝef þer come in-to ȝoure cumpanye a man in fayr cloþynge, hauynge a gold ryng on his hond, &amp; a pore
<seg id="b.JAM.2.3" type="verse">&amp; ȝe take hede to him þat is in schynynge cloþinge, &amp; ȝe sey to him, Sitte þou here wel a-boue; &amp; soþely to þe pore ȝe seye, Þou stonde þere, or sitte vndir þe stole of oure fete;
<seg id="b.JAM.2.3" type="verse">man also in a foul cloþinge; þanne ȝef ȝe byholdeþ in hym þat is wel cloþed , &amp; seye, Sytte þou here wel; &amp; seyn to þe pore man, Stonde þou þere, oþer sytte vnder þe stol of my
<seg id="b.JAM.2.4" type="verse">fet; ne deme ȝe noȝt þanne among ȝow-selfe, &amp; be ȝe noȝt y-mad domes-men of wykkede þoȝtes?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.4" type="verse">in þis ȝoure-self beþ demed, &amp; ȝee beþ maked iustises of ȝoure wickede þouȝtes.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.5" type="verse">Hereþ &amp; take hede, my ful welle loued breþeren; ne haþ not God chosen þe pore in þis worlde to be riche in þe feiþ, &amp; eyres of þe kyngdom, þat God haþ by-hyȝt to alle þat him loueþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.5" type="verse">Y-hereþ, my dereste frendes; ne ches noȝt God pore men in þis worlde, &amp; ryche men in feiþ, &amp; heyres of þe kyngdom, þat God haþ by-hoten to þilke þat loueþ hym?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.6" type="verse">&amp; ȝe haueþ vnworschuped þe pore man. &amp; ne doþ noȝt þese ryche men þoroȝ hure myȝt þruste ȝou adoun? &amp; þei draweþ ȝou to domes.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.6" type="verse">&amp; soþly ȝee vnworschupe þe pore. Ne ouerlye nouȝt þe riche ȝow þorow here power? &amp; þei drawe ȝow to domes.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.7" type="verse">&amp; ne doþ noȝt þei blaspheme þe goode name þat is y-cleped on ȝow?
<seg id="b.JAM.2.7" type="verse">Ne blasfeme þei nouȝt þe goode name þat is ouer ȝow called? (þat is, cristene men of Criste) .
<seg id="b.JAM.2.8" type="verse">And so ȝef ȝe parformeþ þe kynglyche lawe, after scripturis, Þou
<seg id="b.JAM.2.8" type="verse">Nouȝt forþi if þou fulfille þe kynges lawe of heuene aftir holy writte, Þou schalt loue þi neyȝebore ryȝt as þi-self, þan þou doost wel,
<seg id="b.JAM.2.9" type="verse">schalt loue , þann do ȝe wel; &amp; ȝef ȝe vnderfongeþ mennes persones, ȝe doþ synne, &amp; beþ vndernome of þe lawe as trespassoures.
<seg id="b.JAM.2.9" type="verse">soþeli if ȝee any mennys persones accepte, þan ȝee doon gret synne, &amp; ȝee schal be blamyd of God as trespaseres aȝeyn þe lawe.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.10" type="verse">&amp; of þat same mowþe goþ forþe blissynge &amp; cursynge. My breþeren, it is not byhoueful þat þese þinges so be.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.10" type="verse">ymage of God: of þe same mouþ passeþ forþ blessynge &amp;
<seg id="b.JAM.3.11" type="verse">Ne oute of þe hole of a welle ne goþ noȝt forþe bittir watir &amp; swete to-gedur?
<seg id="b.JAM.3.11" type="verse">Wheþer þer sprynge out of hol a welle þat welleþ boþe suete watyr &amp; bytter watyr?
<seg id="b.JAM.3.12" type="verse">&amp; my breþeren, wheþer a fyge-tre mowe brynge forþ grapes, oþer a vyne fyges? so salt water may maken no fresch watyr .
<seg id="b.JAM.3.12" type="verse">My breþeren, þe fyge-tre ne may not brynge forþe grapes, or þe vyne-tre fyges: so no more may salt watur make swete watur.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.13" type="verse">Who is a wys man &amp; a wel y-tauȝt man a-mong ȝow? schewe he of his good conuersacyoun his worchynge in goodnesse of wysdom.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.13" type="verse">Who-so is wyse &amp; wel tauȝt a-monges ȝow, schewe he of his goode lyuynge his werke in myldenesse of wysdome.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.14" type="verse">&amp; ȝef ȝe haueþ bytter hate &amp; stryuynges in ȝoure hertes, ne ioye ȝe noȝt to ben lyerys aȝeyn trewþe.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.14" type="verse">Ȝif þat ȝee haue bittur loue &amp; stryuynges in ȝoure hertis, ne make ȝee no ioye &amp; be lyeres aȝens soþfastnes.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.15" type="verse">For þis wysdom ne comeþ not doun from a-boue, bote it is an erþelyche wysdom, &amp; a bestysch wysdom, &amp; þe defeles wysdom.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.15" type="verse">Soþely þis wysdom is not comynge from a-boue, but erþely, bestlyche, deuellyche.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.16" type="verse">Forsoþe wherso enuye is &amp; strif, þer is vnstabulnes &amp; eche schrewed deede.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.16" type="verse">For þer is hate &amp; stryuynge , þer is vnstabelnesse &amp; eferych schrewyd werk.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.17" type="verse">Bote þe wysdom þat is of a-bouen heo is furst chaste, &amp; seþþe discret, &amp; temperat, pesybel, and bleþelyche wole be conseyled, &amp; assentynge to goode þinges, ful of mercy &amp; of goode fruytys, demynge wiþoute symulacyoun.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.17" type="verse">Soþely þat wytte þat is of a-bouen first forsoþe it is clene, &amp; aftur þat peysyble, mylde to a-moneste, assentynge to þe goode, ful of mercy &amp; of good fruyte, schewynge wiþoute fals colourynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.18" type="verse">&amp; þe fruyt of ryȝtfulnesse is y-sowen in pees to þilke þat doþ pees.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.18" type="verse">Soþely þe fruyte of riȝtwysnes is sowen in pees to hem þat dooþ pees.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.1" type="verse">And my breþeren, ne wylne ȝe noȝt to ben y-mad many maystres, wytynge þat ȝe takeþ þe grettere dom.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.1" type="verse">My deere breþeren, ne wyle ȝe not be maked many maystris, wytynge þat ȝee take þe more dome.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.2" type="verse">For we offendeþ in many þinges euerychone. &amp; who þat offendiþ in non word, he is a parfyt man, &amp; he may wiþ a brydul leden al þe body aboute.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.2" type="verse">We alle forsoþe haue offendid in many þingis. Who-so trespasiþ not in his word, he is here a parfyte man; he may al-so wiþ a brydul lede a- boute al his body.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.3" type="verse">For we putte brydeles in-to horses mouþes to maken hem assente to ous, and we bereþ aboute al hure body.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.3" type="verse">Soþely if we putte brydulis in mowþes of horses to make hem to be at oure wille, we beren a-boute al þe body of hem.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.4" type="verse">&amp; thouȝ it so be þat scheppis be grete &amp; wiþ grete wyndis þei been dreuen, soþly wiþ a lytul stere, wiþ hasty gouernynge of him þat ledeþ it, it is bore a-boute.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.4" type="verse">And grete schyppes þat beþ y-meued wiþ grete wyndes, þei beþ y-turned aboute wiþ a lytul gouernynge, whydur þat he wole þat is gouernour of þe schypp.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.5" type="verse">And so þe tonge is a lytul membre, bote he arereþ up grete þinges.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.5" type="verse">Riȝt so þe tunge soþly a litul membre it is, &amp; gret þinges it makeþ hyȝe. Loo, how litul fyre how grete a wode it brenneþ!
<seg id="b.JAM.3.6" type="verse">And lo, how lytul a fuyr wole brennen up a gret wode! &amp; þe tonge is fuyr &amp; uniuersyte of wikkednesse; &amp; þe tonge is y-set in oure membres, þat defouleþ al þe body; &amp; heo is y-tend of þe fuyr of helle, &amp; tendeþ þe wheol of oure natyuyte.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.6" type="verse">And oure tunge is fyre, is alle manere of wickednes; þe tunge is ordeyned in oure membris, þe whuche defouliþ al þe body; &amp; it brenneþ þe roote of oure birþe in flawme of helle fyre.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.7" type="verse">For eferich kynde of bestes, of bryddes, of eddres,
<seg id="b.JAM.3.7" type="verse">Soþely alle þe kyndes of bestes, &amp; of foulès, &amp; of nedderis, &amp; of alle oþere, beþ maked tame &amp; beþ tamed of mankynde:
<seg id="b.JAM.3.8" type="verse">&amp; of alle oþer, beþ y-temed of mankynde, bote þe tonge no man may temen; for it is a wicked þing, &amp; wiþ-outen reste, &amp; ful of dedlyche venym.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.8" type="verse">soþely tunge no man may make tame, ful of vnpeisyble yuel &amp; deedly venym.
<seg id="b.JAM.3.9" type="verse">In it we blesse oure Fadur God, &amp; in it we mysseye men, þat aftir þe ymage of God beþ maked:
<seg id="b.JAM.3.9" type="verse">In þe tonge we blesseþ God þe Fader; &amp; in hure we curseþ men, þat beþ y-mad after þe
<seg id="b.JAM.4.10" type="verse">&amp; be ȝe y-humeled in þe syȝt of oure Lord, &amp; he wole arere ȝou vp yn tyme of trybulacion .
<seg id="b.JAM.4.10" type="verse">Make ȝow meke in þe syȝt of God, &amp; he wole make ȝow hye ain life wiþ outen ende .
<seg id="b.JAM.4.11" type="verse">And my breþeren, ne bakbyte ȝe noȝt eferychone to oþer: for who þat bakbyteþ his broþer, oþer demeþ his broþer , he bakbyteþ þe lawe, &amp; demeþ þe lawe: &amp; ȝef þou demest þe lawe, þou ne art not a doer of þe lawe, bote a domes-man.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.11" type="verse">Ne bakbyteþ none of ȝow oþer, my dere breþeren; who-so bakbyteþ his broþer, or demeþ his broþer, he bakbyteþ þe lawe, &amp; demeþ þe lawe: soþely if þow deme þe lawe, þow art not a doere of þe lawe, but a domesman.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.12" type="verse">And þer is on þat is makere of þe lawe &amp; domes-man, þat may boþe sauen &amp; distroye: &amp; what art þou þat demest þi nexte neyȝebore?
<seg id="b.JAM.4.12" type="verse">On þer is ȝeuer of þe lawe &amp; a domes-man, þe whuche may boþe saue &amp; lese:
<seg id="b.JAM.4.13" type="verse">And lo, now ȝe seye , We schuleþ gon to day oþer to morewe in-to þat cyte, &amp; þere we woleþ abyden a ȝer, &amp; chaffaren, &amp; wynne muche: &amp; ȝe ne wyteþ noȝt what schal fallen a-morewe.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.13" type="verse">þow soþly, what art þow þat demest þi neiȝebore? Lo, ȝee þat now seye, To day or to morowe schal we goo in-to þat cytee, &amp; soþely a ȝere wele we þer dwelle, &amp; to marchaundise, &amp; þer we wile gete wynnynge:
<seg id="b.JAM.4.14" type="verse">For what is ȝoure lyf? A breþ þat scheweþ hym-seluen a lytel whyles, &amp; soone þer-aftur it is ydon.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.14" type="verse">þat knoweþ not what to morwe schal falle.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.15" type="verse">&amp; þer-fore seye ȝe, Ȝef God wole, &amp;, Ȝef we lyfeþ , we woleþ don þis oþer þat.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.15" type="verse">Soþelyche whuche is oure lyfe? Nouȝt but breþe þat lytul whyle lasteþ &amp; scheweþ, &amp; also sone it is ended. Þerfore ȝe may seye, If God wule, or, If I leue we schal do þis or þat.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.16" type="verse">Bote now ȝe ioyeþ in ȝoure pruydes, &amp; eferich such ioye is wikked.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.16" type="verse">Now ȝee make ioye in ȝoure prides, soþeliche alle suche ioye is wicked.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.17" type="verse">And þerfore who þat can do wel, &amp; doþ noȝt wel, it is synne to hym.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.17" type="verse">Þerfore whoso can do wel &amp; doþ not, it is synne to him.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.1" type="verse">Where-of comeþ bataylis &amp; stryues amonges ȝow? ne comeþ þei
<seg id="b.JAM.4.2" type="verse">Ȝe coueyteþ, &amp; ȝe ne haueþ noȝt: ȝe sleþ , &amp; ȝe hateþ, &amp; ȝe mowe noȝt geten: ȝe stryueþ &amp; ȝe werreþ; ȝe ne haueþ noȝt, for ȝe ne axeþ noȝt.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.2" type="verse">Ȝee desyre &amp; ȝee ne haue it noȝt: ȝe slee, &amp; ȝee haue enuye, &amp; ȝee may not gete it: ȝee streuen &amp; ȝeuen batayle, &amp; ȝee ne haue it nouȝt wherfore þat ȝee aske.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.3" type="verse">Ȝe axeþ, &amp; ȝe ne vnderfongeþ noȝt,. for ȝe axeþ in yuel manere, as ȝe scheweþ openlyche in ȝoure coueytynges.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.3" type="verse">Ȝee asken &amp; ȝee gete it not, for as muchel as ȝee yuel aske, to dwelle stille in ȝoure desyres.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.4" type="verse">Auoutoures, ne wite ȝee not þat loue of þis worlde is enmy to God? whoso-euere þerfore wolde be frend of þis worlde, he is ordeynyd þe enmy of God.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.4" type="verse">Ȝe spousbrekeres, ne knowe ȝe noȝt þat þe frendschype of þis world is enemy to God? &amp; þerfore, who euere þat wol ben frend of þis world, he schal ben y-mad Goddes enemy.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.5" type="verse">Or ellis wene ȝee þat holy write be seyde in-veynelyche? to enuy desyreþ þe sperit þat in ȝow dwelleþ.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.5" type="verse">What wene ȝe? Þat scripture seye in veyn, þat þe spiryt þat is in ȝow coueyteþ to enuye. Bote he ȝeueþ þe more grace.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.6" type="verse">&amp; þerfore he say , God aȝeynstondeþ proude men, &amp; ȝeueþ grace to humel men.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.6" type="verse">Soþely þe more grace he ȝeueþ. Wherfore seiþ holy writte, God wiþstondiþ þe proude, soþely to meke he ȝeueþ grace.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore be ȝe suget to God; &amp; aȝeynstonde ȝe þe deuel, &amp; he schal fleen a-wey from ȝow.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.7" type="verse">Be ȝee þerfore sogettes to God: &amp; soþly wiþstondeþ þe deuel, &amp; he schal flee fro ȝow.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.8" type="verse">Come ȝe nyȝ to God, &amp; he wole neyȝleche to ȝow: ȝe synful men, make ȝe clene ȝoure honden;
<seg id="b.JAM.4.8" type="verse">Neyȝeþ ny to God, &amp; wole come to ȝow. Makeþ clene ȝoure synful hondis, and clenseþ ȝoure hertes þat beþ of double wille.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.9" type="verse">Be ȝe nedy, &amp; makeþ sorowe, &amp; wepeþ, &amp; turneþ ȝoure lauȝtre in-to sorowe, &amp; ȝoure ioye in-to mornynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.4.9" type="verse">Be ȝe sory, &amp; make ȝe waymentacion: &amp; be ȝoure lawȝwynge y-turnyd in-to sorewynge, &amp; ȝoure ioye in-to drerynesse .
<seg id="b.JAM.5.10" type="verse">&amp; briþeren, take ȝe ensampel of an efel yssew, &amp; of longe abydynge, &amp; of pacyence, &amp; of trafayl, of prophetes þat han y-spoken in þe name of oure Lord.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.10" type="verse">Takeþ ensample, my breþeren, of yuel wyndynge, &amp; of þe longenesse, &amp; of traueyle, &amp; þe
<seg id="b.JAM.5.11" type="verse">&amp; þei han y-seyd, þat þei beþ y-blessed þat habeþ y-suffred &amp; abyde. And ȝe habbeþ y-herd þe suffrynge &amp; þe abydynge of Iob, &amp; ȝe han y-seye þe ende of oure Lord: for he is mercyful &amp; doþ mercy .
<seg id="b.JAM.5.11" type="verse">Lo, we blessen hem þat suffrede. Ȝee haue herd þe sufferynge of Iob, &amp; þe ende of oure Lord ȝe seyȝ: for oure Lord is mercyful &amp; forȝeuere.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.12" type="verse">And to-fore alle þinges, my dereste briþeren, ne swere ȝe noȝt by hefne, ne by erþe, ne be non oþer oþ: bote be ȝoure word ȝe, ȝe, &amp; nay, nay; þat ȝe ne falle noȝt vnder dom.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.12" type="verse">Byfore alle þinge, my breþeren, ne wyle ȝe not swere neiþer by heuene, ne be erþe, ne noon oþer manere othe: loke þat ȝoure word be ȝe, ȝe, nay, nay; þat ȝee falle not vndur dome.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.13" type="verse">Ȝef any of ȝow is sory, preye he , &amp; synge he wiþ an efene soule.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.13" type="verse">If eny of ȝow be heuyed, pray he wiþ stable herte, &amp; ioye he in his heuynes.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.14" type="verse">And ȝef eny man is seek a-mong ȝow, brynge ȝe in prestes of þe churche, &amp; preyen þei up-on hym, &amp;
<seg id="b.JAM.5.14" type="verse">If eny of ȝow falle seke, brynge he in þe prestes of þe churche, &amp; þat þei preye for him, ennoyntynge him wiþ oyle in þe name of oure Lord:
<seg id="b.JAM.5.15" type="verse">&amp; þe preyȝere of feiþ schal saue þe seke, &amp; oure Lord schal uppreyse him; &amp; if he be in synne, þei beþ forȝeue him.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.15" type="verse">anoynteþ hym wiþ oyle in þe name of oure Lord: &amp; þe preyere of byleue schal saue þe sek man, and oure Lord wole maken hym lyȝtere of his sekenesse; &amp; ȝef he is in synnes, þei schuleþ ben forȝeuen hym.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.16" type="verse">&amp; þerfore schryue ȝow eche to oþur ȝoure synnys, &amp; prayeþ to-gedere, þat ȝe may be safe. Muche soþely auayleþ bysy preyere of þe riȝtwyse.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.16" type="verse">And þerfore knowleche ȝe ȝoure synnes eferychone to oþer, &amp; preye ȝe for oþer, þat ȝe ben y-saued. For muche worþ is a bysy preyere of a riȝtful man.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.17" type="verse">Helye was a man like vnto us, þat myȝte fele noye &amp; suffre, &amp; wiþ prayere he preyed þat it schulde not reyne up-on erþe; &amp; it reyned not þre ȝere and syxe moneþes.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.17" type="verse">Helye was a man lyche to ȝow, &amp; he preyed þat it schulde noȝt reyne upon þe erþe; &amp; it reyned noȝt þre ȝer &amp; sixe moneþes.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.18" type="verse">&amp; eft he preyede; &amp; heuene ȝaf reyne &amp; þe erþe ȝaf his fruyte.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.18" type="verse">Eftsones he preyed; &amp; hefne ȝef his reyn, &amp; þe erþe his fruyt.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.19" type="verse">My breþeren, soþely who of ȝow erreþ fro soþfastenesse, &amp; whoso him amendeþ,
<seg id="b.JAM.5.19" type="verse">My briþeren, ȝif eny of ȝow erre from
<seg id="b.JAM.5.1" type="verse">Do ȝee now, riche men, make sorwe &amp; wepeþ in ȝoure wrecchednes þe whuche schal come vn-to ȝow.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.20" type="verse">hym oweþ to wyte, þat he þat made þe synful to be turned fro þe erroure of his weye schal saue his soule fro deeþ, and hydeþ þe mechelnesse of his synnes þat wole turn to him.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.20" type="verse">trewþe, &amp; eny man turne hym aȝeyn; he schal vnderstonde, þat who þat makeþ a synful man turnen hym from þe errour of his weye, he schal sauen his soule from deþ, &amp; keuereþ þe multytude of synnes. Deo gracias.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.2" type="verse">Ȝoure rycchesse beþ y-roted, &amp; ȝoure cloþes beþ y-eten of mowtþes .
<seg id="b.JAM.5.2" type="verse">Roten beþ maked ȝoure richesses, and ȝoure cloþus wiþ mothes beþ frete.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.3" type="verse">Ȝoure gold and ȝoure seluer is y-rousted; &amp; þe roust of hem schal ben in wytnesse to ȝow &amp; ete ȝoure flesch as fuyr. Ȝe tresoureþ to ȝow-self wraþþe in þe laste dayes.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.3" type="verse">Ȝoure golde &amp; ȝoure seluer rust haþ ouer-goo; &amp; þe ruste of hem schal be a-geynus ȝow in wittnes &amp; schal ete ȝoure flesche as it were þe fyre. Ȝee make ȝow a tresorye of wraþþe in þe laste dayees.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.4" type="verse">&amp; þe mede of ȝoure werk-men þat han y-repe ȝoure kyndomes, þat ȝe haueþ bygyled hem of, cryeþ an hiȝ: &amp; hure cryynge haþ y-entred in-to þe eres of oure Lord of Sabaoth.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.4" type="verse">Lo, þe hire of ȝoure hyrid men &amp; of ȝoure seruauntis þat þei traueiled fore in ȝoure seruice, þe whuche fro hem ȝe haue wiþ-holden &amp; defrauded, crieþ: &amp; þe cry of hem entrede in-to þe eres of God almyȝty.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.5" type="verse">Ȝe habbeþ y-mad festes up-on þe erþe, &amp; ȝe habbeþ y-noresched ȝoure hertes in leccheryes in þe day of slauȝt.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.5" type="verse">Fat fedde ȝee beþ upon erþe, &amp; in leccheries ȝe nursched ȝoure hertes in day of sleynge.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.6" type="verse">Ȝee brouȝte forþe &amp; slowe þe riȝtwyse, &amp; he wiþstod ȝow nouȝt.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.6" type="verse">Ȝe han y-broȝt forþ &amp; y-slawen þe ryȝtful man, &amp; he ne aȝeynstondeþ ȝow noȝt.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore, breþeren, beþ sufferynge for þe comynge of oure Lord. Lo, þe tilyere abideþ þe precyouse frute of þe erþe, pacyently abidynge to it haue taken sesoun &amp; þe temperaunce.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore, briþeren, be ȝe pacyent to þe comynge of God. For
<seg id="b.JAM.5.8" type="verse">&amp; be ȝe pacyent, &amp; confermeþ ȝoure hertes, for þe comynge of God wol neyȝlachen.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.8" type="verse">&amp; þerfore be ȝee sufferynge, &amp; make stalworþe ȝoure hertus, for þe comynge of oure Louerd schal come ny nyȝte.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.9" type="verse">And breþeren, ne make ȝe noȝt waymentacyoun to-gedere, þat ȝe ben noȝt y-demed: for lo, þe domes-man abydeþ tofore þe ȝate.
<seg id="b.JAM.5.9" type="verse">Ne make ȝee no sorwe, breþeren, echone wiþ oþur, þat ȝe be not demed: lo, þe iustyse by-fore þe ȝate stondeþ.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.10" type="verse">Soþly what-so-euere þei knoweþ not þei blaspheme: soþly what-so-euere kyndely, as vnresonable bestes knoweþ , in þise dedes þei beþ corrumped .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.11" type="verse">Wo to hem þat ȝeden in þe weye of Caym, &amp; with errour of Balaam beþ ȝote oute þoroȝ mede , and þorouȝ þe ȝeynseyenge
<seg id="b.JUD.1.12" type="verse">Þese it beþ þat in here metis beþ defouled, in feestynge, fedynge hem-selue withoute drede: cloudes with-outen watyr, þat with wyndes beþ bore aboute; vnfruytful heruest trees þat no fruyt bereþ,
<seg id="b.JUD.1.13" type="verse">twyes deede þei ben, &amp; drawen up by þe rootes; þe flodes of þe woode see, spewynge here confusyoun; errynge sterres, to þe whuche þe storme of derkenesse is kept with-outen ende.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.14" type="verse">Of þese prophecyede þe seueþe fro Adam, Ennoch, &amp; seyde, Ecce Dominus venit in sanctis milibus suis etc. Lo, oure Lord schal come in his þousandys of his seyntes,
<seg id="b.JUD.1.15" type="verse">for-to make dome aȝeyn alle yuel , &amp; forto aresoun alle wykked of alle þe dedis of here wykkednesse þe whuche wykkedly þei wrouȝte , &amp; of alle þe harde wordes þat synful men &amp; wykked aȝeyns God haue spoken.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.16" type="verse">Þese beþ gruccheres , pleynners , þat walken aftur here desyres, &amp; here mouþ spekeþ pryde, merueylynge persones by cause of wynnynge .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.17" type="verse">Ȝe soþly, my breþeren, haueþ mynde of wordes , þat beþ byfore spoken of þe posteles of oure Lord Iesu Crist;
<seg id="b.JUD.1.18" type="verse">þe whuche seyde to ȝow, þat in þe laste tyme schulen come bygylours, wandrynge after þer desyres in .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.19" type="verse">Þes ben þei þat departen hem-self bestch , &amp; han not þe Holy Gost.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.20" type="verse">Ȝe soþly, my dere breþeren, house ȝoure-selfen. &amp; grounde ȝou holyly of verrey feiþ, preyenge in þe Holy
<seg id="b.JUD.1.21" type="verse">Gost, kepynge ȝoure-seluen in þe loue of God, abydynge þe mercy of oure Lord Iesu Crist in-te euerlastynge lyf.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.22" type="verse">&amp; hem
<seg id="b.JUD.1.23" type="verse">soþly þat be demed blame ȝe; saue hem forsoþe, rauyschynge hem oute of fyre; hauynge mercy to oþere in drede hatynge þat foule cote þe whuche is fleschly.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.24" type="verse">Soþly to hym þat is
<seg id="b.JUD.1.25" type="verse">oure Lord Iesu Crist, only to God oure Sauyour by Iesu Crist, to oure Lord b glorye &amp; worschupe &amp; gret lordschupe &amp; power byfore al þe worlde &amp; now in alle þe worldes. Amen .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.2" type="verse">Iesu Crist; mercy vnto ȝow &amp; pees &amp; charite be fulfylled.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.3" type="verse">Dere frende al bysynesse y haue don to wryte to ȝow of ȝoure comune hele: y hade nede to wryte vnto ȝou; preynge stalworþely to stryue aȝeyn synne in upholdynge of þe feiþ þat on taken to þe seyntes.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.4" type="verse">Soþly þer beþ
<seg id="b.JUD.1.5" type="verse">Y wole a-moneste ȝou, one knowynge alle þinges; for oure Lord Iesus saued þe peple of þe lond of Egypte, þe secounde tyme hem þat trowed not he loste .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.6" type="verse">Þe aungel soþly þat kepte not his princehede &amp; his comaundementes , bote forsoke his hous , in þe grete dome of God, with euerlastynge bondys vnder derkenesse he locked hym.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.7" type="verse">On þe same wyse þei synned in fornycacyoun, as dyde Sodom &amp; Gomorre &amp; þe cytee of fynytyme; &amp; after oþer flesch þei ȝeden awey ; þei beþ ensample to suffre peyne of euerlastynge fuyr.
<seg id="b.JUD.1.8" type="verse">On þe same wyse þei þat soþly þer flesch defouled, despysynge God here Lord, &amp; soþly his mageste þei blasphe .
<seg id="b.JUD.1.9" type="verse">Whan Mychael þe archaungel, disputynge wiþ þe deuel, fel at stryf of Moyses body, he durste not putte up-on hym þe dome of blasphemye , bote seyde, God ouercome þe .
<seg id="b.JUD.2.10" type="verse">byleuen in Crist by Poul þe apostel; &amp; þerfore y preye þe , telle me what manere he tauȝte men to lyue, when he hade y-turned hem from here fals byleue. For sum men seyn þat Crist and his oþer aposteles tauȝten hure parfyt techynge to þe chyldren of Israel, þat God hade raþer y-tauȝt by Moyses
<seg id="b.JUD.2.15" type="verse">&amp; oþer prophetes; &amp; þei seyn þat it is y-nouȝ for ous to byleuen in Crist, &amp; ben y-folewed, &amp; þanne we schulleþ ben y-saued. &amp; þerfore, broþer, y preye þe þat þou telle me wheþer þat Poule, þat wes a postel of mys-beleued men, tauȝte hem eny þing ellys þan to byleuen in Crist, &amp; ben y-folewed in his name."
<seg id="b.JUD.2.20" type="verse">"Suster , þou schalt vnderstonde þat Poule wryteþ many epysteles to dyuerse men þat he turned to þe byleue, how þei schulen byleuen, &amp; how þei schulleþ lyuen; bote y ne may noȝt at þis tyme wryte to þe alle his pysteles as þei stondeþ; bote naþeles, ȝef it be Goddus wylle, þou schalt habbe hem heraftur.
<seg id="b.JUD.2.25" type="verse">Bote suster, þu schalt vnderstonden þat seynt Poule techeþ þre þinges in his pysteles: on þing is þat þei byleuen in Iesu Crist, þat is Goddes sone &amp; sauyour of mankynde, þat come to saue synful men, þoroȝ grace &amp; þoroȝ mercy, þat byleueþ in hym; &amp; so Seynt Poule
<seg id="b.JUD.2.5" type="verse">"Broþer, y seo wel þat þese aposteles techeþ þe pepel as Crist techeþ in þe gospel, bote neþeles, broþer, þese apostelys weren y-ordeynyd to techen þe chyldren of Israel &amp; þe Iewes, &amp; we beþ noȝt of þe chyldren of Israel, for oure auncetres weren heþen men þat weren y-turned to
<seg id="b.JUD.3.10" type="verse">þat byleueþ in Iesu Crist, &amp; so men beþ y-iustyfyed of hure synnes, þoroȝ grace in byleuynge in Crist, &amp; noȝt þoroȝ kepynge þe werkes of þe lawe. For seynt Poule seyþ þat þe lawe ne was but a schadewe, þat broȝte no man to perfeccyoun. Þe þridde þing þat Poule techeþ is how men
<seg id="b.JUD.3.15" type="verse">schulleþ forsake synne in kepynge Cristes lawe of charite, &amp; of þis poynt, suster , þoroȝ Goddes grace ich wole telle þe what he seiþ in his pisteles, &amp; of þe oþer poyntes when ich haue gretter leyser wiþ þe grace of God ."
<seg id="b.JUD.3.5" type="verse">Moyses lawe, as circumsysyoun and suche oþer poyntes of þe lawe. Bote seynt Poule techeþ in his pystele þat no man was y-iustyfyed of his synne by þe lawe. Bote Crist in his comynge haþ y-geten men forȝeuenesse of hure synnes of his fader; &amp; so alle þilke men han forȝfnesse of hure synnes
<seg id="b.MAT.1.10" type="verse">Ezechyas gate Manassen. Manassen gate Amon. Amon gate Iosyam.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.11" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.MAT.1.12" type="verse">Iosyas gate Iechonyam. Iechonyas gate Salatyel.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.13" type="verse">Salatyel gate Zorobabel. Zorobabel gate Abiud.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.14" type="verse">Abiud gate Eliachym. Eliachym gate Azor. Azor gate Sadoc.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.15" type="verse">Sadoc gate Achym. Achym gate Eliud. Eliud
<seg id="b.MAT.1.16" type="verse">Iacob gate Ioseph þe housbonde of Marye, of whom was bore Iesus þe whuche is clepyd Crist.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.17" type="verse">Alle þe kynredys fro Abraham to Dauid beþ fourtene; and fro Dauid to þe goynge oute of Babilon to Crist fourtene.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.18" type="verse">Soþly þe generacyoun (or, kynrede) of Crist was on þis manere: whan Marye þe moder of Iesu was weddid to Ioseph, or þei come to-gyder sche was founde hauynge in hire wombe of þe Holy Gost.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.19" type="verse">For-soþe Ioseph hire housbonde, for he was ryȝtwys, he wolde not opynly sclawnder hire, but pryuely he wolde haue left hire.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.1" type="verse">Matheu seiþ in þe firste chapytyl on þis wyse in þe book of þe kynrede of Iesu Crist, þe sone of Dauid, þe sone of Abraham.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.20" type="verse">Soþly whyle he was þenkynge þese þinges for-to leue his wyf, loo, an aungel of oure Lord apperyd to hym in sleep, seyenge, Ioseph, þe sone of Dauid, ne wyle þ not drede to take Marye þy weddid wyf: forsoþe þat þing þat is bore in hire is of þe Holy Gost.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.21" type="verse">Soþly sche schal bere a sone, &amp; þou schalt nempne his name Iesus; forsoþe he schal make his puple safe fro þe synnys of hem.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.22" type="verse">Soþly þis was done, þat þat þing schulde be fulfild þe whuche was seyd by þe prophete,
<seg id="b.MAT.1.23" type="verse">seyenge on þis wyse, Lo, a mayden schal haue in hire wombe, &amp; sche schal bere a sone, &amp; his name schal be clepyd Emanuel; þat is, God is wiþ us (or, God schal be wiþ us).
<seg id="b.MAT.1.24" type="verse">Soþly Ioseph rysynge up fro his sleep dide as þe aungel
<seg id="b.MAT.1.25" type="verse">comawndid hym , &amp; he tooke Marye his wyfe; and he knewe hire not (þat is to seye, fleschly) tul sche bare hire sone first bygete: &amp; sche clepyd his name Iesus.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.2" type="verse">Abraham gate Ysaac, &amp; Ysaac gate Iacob. Iacob gate Iudam &amp; his breþeren.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.3" type="verse">Iudas gate Phares &amp; Zaram of Thamar.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.4" type="verse">Phares gate Esron. Esron gate Aram. Aram gate Amynadab. Amynadab gate Naason. Naason gate Salmon. Salmon gate Booz of Raab .
<seg id="b.MAT.1.5" type="verse">Booz gate Obed of Ruth. Obed gate Iesse.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.6" type="verse">Iesse gate Dauid þe kyng. Dauid þe kyng gate Salomon of hire þat was Vryes wyf.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.7" type="verse">Salomon gate Roboam.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.8" type="verse">Roboas gate Abyam. Abyas gate Asa. Asa gate Iosaphath. Iosophath gate Ioram. Ioram gate Ozyam. Ozyas gate Ioathan.
<seg id="b.MAT.1.9" type="verse">Ioathas gate Achas. Achaz gate Ezechyam.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.10" type="verse">Soþly þei seynge þe sterre
<seg id="b.MAT.2.11" type="verse">were ioyeful; &amp; wiþ gret ioye þei entrede in-to þe hous &amp; fownden þe chyld wiþ Mary his moder; &amp; þei felden down worschypynge hym; &amp; þei openyde þer tresoris &amp; offrede to
<seg id="b.MAT.2.12" type="verse">hym ȝyftys, gold &amp; encense &amp; myrre; &amp; toke in slepe an answere þat þei schulde not turne aȝeyn by Herode. By a-noþer weye þei turnyd aȝeyn in-to her cuntrey.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.13" type="verse">&amp; whan þei were gon aȝeyn, lo, an angel of oure Lord apperyd to Ioseph in his sleep, seyenge, Ryse up &amp; take þe chyld &amp; his modir, &amp; fle into Egypt, &amp; be þere vn-to suche tyme þat I warne to þee: for-soþe it is for-to come þat Herode sekeþ þe chyld to lose (or, to sle) hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.14" type="verse">Þan Ioseph rysynge toke þe chyld &amp; his moder in þe nyȝt, &amp; he wente in-to Egypt; &amp;
<seg id="b.MAT.2.15" type="verse">he was þere vnto þe deyenge of Herode: þat þat schulde be fulfylde þat was seyde of God by þe prophete, seyenge, Fro Egypt I callyd my sone.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.16" type="verse">Þan Herode, seynge þat he was bygylyd of þe kynges, he was ful wroþ, &amp; sende in-to Betlem, &amp; slow alle þe chyldren þat were in Betlem &amp; in alle þe costys bysyde, þat were of two ȝeer &amp; wiþinne, after þe tyme þat he hadde souȝt of þe kynges.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.17" type="verse">&amp; þanne was fulfillyd þat
<seg id="b.MAT.2.18" type="verse">was seyd by Ieremye, A voyce was herd in hye, gretynge &amp; mychil waymentynge, Rachel wepynge her sones; and
<seg id="b.MAT.2.19" type="verse">Þus whan Herode was deed, loo, an aungel of oure Lord appered
<seg id="b.MAT.2.1" type="verse">Herfore whan Iesus was bore in Bethlem of þe Iewery in þe dayes of kyng Heroude, loo, þe kynges come fro þe est
<seg id="b.MAT.2.20" type="verse">to Ioseph in sleep in Egypt, seyenge, Ryse &amp; take þe chyld &amp; þe moder of hym, &amp; go in-to þe lond of Israel: for soþly þei beþ deed þat souȝte þe chyldes lyf.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.21" type="verse">&amp; Ioseph roos &amp; toke þe chyld &amp; his moder, &amp; he come into þe lond of Israel.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.22" type="verse">Soþly he herynge þat Archelaus regned in þe Iude for Herode his fadir, he dredde for hym to go þider. &amp; Ioseph was amonestyd in his sleep by an aungel how he schulde go
<seg id="b.MAT.2.23" type="verse">in-to þe partys (þat is, to þe cuntrey) of Galyle, &amp; come &amp; duellyd in a cytee þe whuche is called Nazareth: þat þat þing schulde be fulfylde þat was seyd by þe prophetys, Forsoþe, he schal be called Nazarene (þat is to seye, holy).
<seg id="b.MAT.2.2" type="verse">to Ierusalem, seyenge, Where is he þat is bore þe kyng of Iewys? soþly we sawe a sterre of hym in þe est, &amp; we come to wurschupe hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.3" type="verse">Soþly kyng Heroud herynge was troublyd in herte, &amp; alle Ierusalem wiþ hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.4" type="verse">&amp; he gederyd alle þe princes of prestis &amp; þe wyse men of þe puple, &amp; he enqueryd of hem where Crist schulde be bore.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.5" type="verse">And þei seyde to hym, In Betleem of þe Iewrye: for-why so it is
<seg id="b.MAT.2.6" type="verse">wryte by þe prophete, &amp; þou Betleem, in þe lond of þe Iewrye, þou art not leest in princes of þe Iewry (þat is to seye , Þou cyte Betlem, þou art not holde to be lest among alle þe cytees of þe Iewry, but most of dignite): for soþly out of þe schal goo a dewke (a ledere), þe whuche schal gouerne my peple Israel.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.7" type="verse">Þan pryuely Heroud callyd þe kynges, &amp; bysyly he enqueryd of hem þe tyme of þe sterre þe whuche
<seg id="b.MAT.2.8" type="verse">apperid to hem; &amp; he seyde sendenge hem into Betlem, Goo ȝe, &amp; bysyly enquere ȝee of þe chylde; þat whan ȝe haue founden hym, telle ȝee me aȝeyn, þat I come &amp; wurschupe hym also.
<seg id="b.MAT.2.9" type="verse">Þese þre kynges, whan þei had herd þe kyng Heroud, þei wente þer weye; &amp; lo, þe sterre þat þei sawe in þe est wente byfore hem, vnto suche tyme þat it come &amp; stode aboue where þe chyld was.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.10" type="verse">Soþly now þe ax is sett to þe rote of þe tree: þerfore eche tree þe whuche makeþ not good fruyt it schal be kutt downe, &amp; it schal be sent in-to þe fyre.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.11" type="verse">For-soþe I baptyze ȝow in water
<seg id="b.MAT.3.12" type="verse">soþly he schal baptyze ȝow in þe Holy Gost &amp; in fyre: whos wyndel is in his honde, &amp; he schal clense fully his korne; &amp; he schal gedere his korne in-to his berne, &amp; soþly þe chaff he schal brenne in a fyre þat may not be slekked.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.13" type="verse">Þanne come Iesus fro Galyle in-to Iordan to Ion, þat he schulde be baptyzed of hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.14" type="verse">Soþly Ion forbeed hym, seyenge, I fel to be baptyzed of þee, &amp; þou comest to me?
<seg id="b.MAT.3.15" type="verse">Soþly Iesus ansuerynge seyde to hym, Suffre now: for on þis manere it bysemeþ us for-to fulfylle al ryȝtwysnesse. Þan he lyte hym (or , suffred hym).
<seg id="b.MAT.3.16" type="verse">Soþly Iesus baptyzed wente soone up fro þe water: &amp; lo, þe heuenes were opene, &amp; he saw þe Spiryte
<seg id="b.MAT.3.17" type="verse">of God comynge down as a doufe upon hym; &amp; lo, a voyce of heuene seyenge, Þis is my Sone wel loued, in whom I am wel plesed.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.1" type="verse">Soþly in þo dayes Ion baptist come, prechynge in þe
<seg id="b.MAT.3.2" type="verse">wyldernes (or, in þe desert) of þe Iewrye, &amp; seyenge, Do ȝe penawnce; for soþly þe kyngdom of heuene schal come nyȝ.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.3" type="verse">Soþly þis is he of whom it was seyd by Ysaye þe prophete, seyenge, A voyce of a cryere in wildernesse, make ȝe redy þe weye of oure Lord. Make ȝe ryȝt stretis (or elles, streyȝte þe weyes) of hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.4" type="verse">Soþly he Ion had cloþinge of þe heer of camels, &amp; a gyrdil of a skyn aboute his lendes; soþly his mete was hony-sokkles &amp; hony of þe wode.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.5" type="verse">Þan wente out to hym Ierusalem, &amp; al þe Iewry, &amp; al þe cuntrey aboute
<seg id="b.MAT.3.6" type="verse">Iurdane; &amp; þei were baptyzed of hym in Iordan, schryuynge here synnys.
<seg id="b.MAT.3.7" type="verse">Soþly he seynge many of þe Pharysees &amp; of þe Saduceus comynge to þe baptem, he seyde to hem, Ȝe kynredes of þe nedderis, who schewyd to ȝow for-to fle fro þe wraþþe þat is for-to come?
<seg id="b.MAT.3.8" type="verse">Do ȝe worþi fruyte of penawnce:
<seg id="b.MAT.3.9" type="verse">&amp; wyle ȝe not sey wiþinne ȝoure-self (þat is, in ȝoure hertys), We haue a fader Abraham: soþly I sey to ȝow, þat God is myȝty of þise stonys to rere þe sones of Abraham.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.10" type="verse">And þanne seyde Iesus to þe fend, Go
<seg id="b.MAT.4.11" type="verse">Þan þe fend lefte Crist; &amp; lo, goode aungelys comyn to hym &amp; serued to hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.12" type="verse">Whan Iesus herde þat Ion was put in-to prysoun, he
<seg id="b.MAT.4.13" type="verse">ȝede in-to Galyle; &amp; þe cyte of Nazareth lefte, he come &amp; duellyd in Capharnaum, by-syde þe see, in þe cuntreyes
<seg id="b.MAT.4.14" type="verse">of Zabulon &amp; of Neptalym: þat it schulde be fulfylde þat
<seg id="b.MAT.4.15" type="verse">was seyde by Ysaye þe prophete, Lond of Zabulon &amp; lond of Neptalym, þe wey of þe see byȝonde Iordane, of þe folke of
<seg id="b.MAT.4.16" type="verse">Galyle; þe folke þe whuche ȝede in derkenesse sawe gret lyȝt, &amp; to þe syttynge in þe rewme of schadowe of deeþ, lyȝt was rysen to hem.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.17" type="verse">After þat Iesus bygan to preche, &amp; seyde, Do ȝe penawnce; for soþly, þe kyngdom of heuene schal come nyȝ.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.18" type="verse">&amp; soþly Iesus wente by-syde þe se of Galile. He sawe two breþeren, Symon þe whuche is cleped Peter, &amp; Andrew his broþer, puttynge a nett in-to þe see; soþly þei were fyscheris.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.19" type="verse">&amp; he seyde to hem, Come ȝe after me, &amp; I schal make ȝow to be fyscherys of men.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.1" type="verse">Þanne Iesus was led in-to desert þorow a spiryte þere he schulde be temptyd of þe deuel.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.20" type="verse">&amp; þei a-noon lefte þer
<seg id="b.MAT.4.21" type="verse">nettes &amp; þe schyp, &amp; sueden hym &amp; he wente forþ fro þen &amp; saw oþer two, Iame þe sone of Zebede, &amp; Ion his broþer, in schype wiþ Zebede þer fader, makynge redy þer nettys; &amp; he clepyd hem.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.22" type="verse">Soþly þei left þer nettys &amp; her fader, &amp; folowed hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.23" type="verse">&amp; Iesus wente aboute al Galyle, prechynge &amp; techynge hem in here synagoges þe gospel of þe kyngdom of heuene, &amp; helynge alle sorowes &amp; alle sekenesse in þe peple.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.24" type="verse">&amp; þe knowynge of hym wente in-to al Sirry: &amp; þei offred to hym alle hauynge yuel, in dyuers sekenes &amp; tormentys taken, &amp; þo þat hadde fendus wiþ-inne hem, &amp; hem þat were lunatyke, &amp; men þat had þe palsy, &amp; he helyd hem.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.25" type="verse">&amp; many cumpanyes sueden hym, &amp; men of Galyle, &amp; of Decapoly (þat is to seye, of þat cuntrey þat hadde ten cytees) , &amp; of Ierusalem, &amp; of þe Iewry, &amp; of men fro ouer Iordane.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.2" type="verse">And whanne he had fastyd fourty dayes &amp; fourty nyȝtys, afterward he hungred .
<seg id="b.MAT.4.3" type="verse">&amp; þe temptere comynge to hym seyde to hym, If þou art Godes sone, sey þat þise stones be maade loues.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.4" type="verse">Crist answerynge seyde, It is wryte þat not onlyche in breed lyueþ man, but in eche word þat comeþ of Godes mouþ.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.5" type="verse">Þan þe fende toke hym in-to þe holy cyte; &amp; putte hym aboue þe
<seg id="b.MAT.4.6" type="verse">penacle of þe temple, &amp; seyde to Crist, If þou art Godes sone, send þy-self adowne : soþly it is wryte of þee, for God bad his aungelys of Crist to kepe þe in here hondys, as in awntyr þou herte þi foot to þe stone.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.7" type="verse">Iesus seyde to hym, Eft it is wryte, Þou schalt not tempte þe Lord þi God.
<seg id="b.MAT.4.8" type="verse">Eft þe fend toke hym in-to a ful hyȝ hille, &amp; he schewed to hym
<seg id="b.MAT.4.9" type="verse">alle þe kyngdomes of þe worlde, &amp; þe ioye of hem; &amp; seyde to hym, Alle þese þinges I schal ȝeue þee , ȝif þou falle &amp; loute me.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.10" type="verse">Blessyd be þey þat suffren purswynge for ryȝtwysnes: for here is þe rewme of heuenes.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.11" type="verse">Blessyd schal ȝe be whan þat men schal curse ȝow, &amp; whan þei haue purswed ȝow, &amp; whan þei haue seyd al yuel aȝeyns ȝow, lyȝenge, for me.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.12" type="verse">Ioye ȝe, &amp; be glad: for ȝoure hyre is muche in heuene: soþly so þei haue purswed þe prophetis þat were byfore ȝow.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.13" type="verse">Ȝe beþ salt of þe erþe: &amp; ȝif þe salt vanysche awey, in what þing schal þe erþe be saltyd? þis salt is not worþi after, but to be cast oute &amp; be defoulyd of men.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.14" type="verse">Ȝe ben lyȝt of þe world. A cytee sett on an hylle may not be hyd.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.15" type="verse">Nor men lyȝte not a lanterne &amp; putte it vndir a buschel, but þei sette it on a kandelsteke, þat it ȝeue lyȝt to alle þat beþ in þe hous.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.16" type="verse">&amp; so schyne ȝoure lyȝt byfore men, þat þei se ȝoure goode werkes, &amp; so þanke ȝoure Fadir þat is in heuene.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.17" type="verse">Wele ȝe not gesse þat I come to lose þe lawe ne prophetys: I come not to vn-do hem, but for-to fylle hem.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.18" type="verse">Soþly I seye to ȝow, To þat heuene &amp; erþe passe, an i ne a tytyl schal not passe fro þe lawe byfore alle þinges be done.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.19" type="verse">Þerfore who doþ not on of þe leeste comawndementis, he schal be cleped leest in þe kyngdom of heuene; and soþly he þat doþ þes comawndementes &amp; techeþ , he schal be cleped greet in þe kyngdom of heuene.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.1" type="verse">Soþly Crist seynge þe peple, he wente up in-to an hylle: &amp; whan he had sette hym downe, his discyplys come to hym:
<seg id="b.MAT.5.20" type="verse">Soþly I sey to ȝow, But if ȝoure ryȝtewysnes habounde more þan of þese wyse men of þe lawe &amp; of þe Pharyseus, ȝe schal not entre in-to þe kyngdom of heuene.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.21" type="verse">Soþly ȝe haue herd þat it is seyd to men of þe olde lawe, Þou schalt not sle; forsoþe he þat sleþ, he schal be
<seg id="b.MAT.5.22" type="verse">coupable in þe dome; soþly I sey to ȝow, þat who-so is wroþ
<seg id="b.MAT.5.23" type="verse">Þerfore if þou brynge þi ȝifte to þe auter, &amp; þere þou hast byþouȝt þee þat þi broþer haþ sum
<seg id="b.MAT.5.24" type="verse">þinge aȝeyns þee, leeue þi ȝifte þere byfore þe auter, &amp; go ferst to be reconsyled to þi broþer (þat is, be at on wiþ þi broþer), &amp; þanne þou schalt come &amp; offre þi ȝifte.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.25" type="verse">Be þou assentynge soone to þyn enemy, þe whylis þou art in þe wey wiþ hym, en awnter þyn enemy take þee to þe domus-man, &amp; þe domes-man bytake þee to þe jayleer, &amp; þou be putt in-to prysown.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.26" type="verse">Soþly I sey to þee, Þou schalt not go oute fro þi prysoun, to þou hafe ȝeue aȝeyn þe leste ferþing.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.27" type="verse">Ȝe haue herd þat it was seyd to þe olde men, Þou schalt not do
<seg id="b.MAT.5.28" type="verse">auowtrye: soþly I sey to ȝow, þat eche man þat haþ sey a womman &amp; coueyte for-to haf hire, he haþ don auowtrye wiþ hire in his herte.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.29" type="verse">If it so be þi ryȝt eyȝe sclawndir þee, drawe it oute, &amp; caste it fro þee: for soþly it is more spedynge to þee þat one of þi membres per-sche, þan al þi body be sente in-to helle.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.2" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.MAT.5.30" type="verse">&amp; ȝif þi ryȝt hond sclawnder þee, kutte it a-wey, &amp; caste it fro þee: for soþly it spedeþ to þee, þat raþere on of þi membris persche þan al þi body go in-to helle.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.31" type="verse">Soþly it is seyd to olde men, Whoso lefeþ his wyf,
<seg id="b.MAT.5.32" type="verse">hym byhoueþ ȝefe to hire a lybel of forsakyng: soþly y sey to ȝow, þat eche man þat lefeþ his wyf, outetake cause of fornycasyoun, he makeþ hire to do avowtrye: &amp; he þat weddeþ hire þat is left of hire housbonde, he doþ avowtrye.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.33" type="verse">Eft ȝe hafe herd þat it was seyd to þe olde men, Þou schalt
<seg id="b.MAT.5.34" type="verse">not forswere þee, for þou schalt ȝefe to God þi swerynge: but soþly it is seyd to ȝow noȝt to swere in eny manere; neyþer
<seg id="b.MAT.5.35" type="verse">by heuene, for it is þe trone of God; neyþer by þe erþe, for it is scaffold of his feet; noyþer by Ierusalem, for it is þe cyte of þe grete Kyng.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.36" type="verse">Nor þou schalt not swere by þin heuyd, for þou mayst not make one heer whȝit or blak.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.37" type="verse">Soþly ȝoure worde schal be, ȝe, ȝe; or nay, nay; soþly what so is more þan þis, it is of yuel.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.38" type="verse">Ȝe hafe herd þat it was seyd, Eyȝe for eyȝe, &amp; a toþ for a toþ (þat is to seye, a man schulde be punysched in þe same membre in þe whuche he disseyfede
<seg id="b.MAT.5.39" type="verse">his neyȝebores) : but soþly I sey to ȝow nouȝt to wiþstonde þe yuel: but whoso smyteþ þee in þe ryȝt cheke, ȝif to hym þe toþer.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.3" type="verse">&amp; he openynge his mowþe tauȝt hem, seyenge, Blessyd be
<seg id="b.MAT.5.40" type="verse">&amp; whoso wyle stryue wiþ þee in þe dome, &amp; take fro þee þi kote, lefe þou to hym also þi palle.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.41" type="verse">&amp; whoso angreþ þee a þousande paas, go wiþ hym oþer two þousande. And whoso wyle borowe of þee, ne turne þou not awey.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.42" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.MAT.5.43" type="verse">Ȝe hafe herd þat it was tolde to olde men, Þou schalt loue þi frend, &amp; þou schalt hate þin enemy.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.44" type="verse">But soþly I sey to ȝow, Loue ȝe ȝowre enemyes, do ȝe good to hem þat haten ȝow, &amp;
<seg id="b.MAT.5.45" type="verse">preye ȝe for hem þat purswen ȝow, &amp; chalange ȝow falsly; þat ȝe be þe sones of ȝoure Fadir þat is in heuene, þat makeþ his sunne sprynge on goode men &amp; yuele, &amp; reyneþ up-on iuste men &amp; vniuste.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.46" type="verse">For if ȝe louen hem þat loueþ ȝow, what meede schal ȝe haue? siþ puplycans don þus.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.47" type="verse">&amp; if ȝe greten only ȝoure breþeren, what schal ȝe do more? Ne don not heþene men þus?
<seg id="b.MAT.5.48" type="verse">Þerfore be ȝe parfyte, as ȝoure Fadur of heuene is parfyte.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.4" type="verse">Blessyd be þe mylde: for þei schal haue þe lond of lyf.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.5" type="verse">Blessyd be þei þat waylen: for þei schal be comfortyd.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.6" type="verse">Blessyd be þei þat hungren &amp; þrusten ryȝtwysnes: for þei schal be fulfyllyd. Blessyd be mercyful men: for þei schal swe mercy.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.7" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.MAT.5.8" type="verse">Blessyd be men of clene herte: for þei schal se God.
<seg id="b.MAT.5.9" type="verse">Blessyd be pesyble men: for þei schal be cleped Godes chyldren.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.10" type="verse">Þi kyngdom come to us. Þi wylle be don, as in heuene, &amp; in erþe.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.11" type="verse">Oure eche dayes breed ȝeue us to day.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.12" type="verse">&amp; forȝeue us oure dettys, as we forȝeue oure dettourys.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.13" type="verse">And ne lede us not in temptacyon, but delyuere us of yuel.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.1" type="verse">&amp; take ȝe heede þat ȝe do not ȝoure ryȝtwysnesse byfore men, to be seyn of hem: for elles schal ȝe haue no mede at ȝoure Fadir þat is in heuene.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.2" type="verse">And þerfore whan þou dost þyn almes, nele þou not trumpe byfore þee, as ypocritys don in synagoges &amp; stretis, for-to be worschuped of men. Soþly I sey to ȝow, Þei haue resseyuyd here mede.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.3" type="verse">But whan þou dost þyn almes, loke þi lyft syde
<seg id="b.MAT.6.4" type="verse">wyte noȝt what þi ryȝt syde doþ: þat þyn almes be in hyd: &amp; þi Fader þat seþ in hyd schal ȝeue þee hyre .
<seg id="b.MAT.6.5" type="verse">And whan ȝe preyȝen, ȝee schal not ben as ypocrytys, þat louen to stonde in churches &amp; in kornerys of stretys to preyȝe, for-to ben seyn holy of men. Soþly I sey to ȝow, Þese men han resceyued here mede.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.6" type="verse">But þou, whan þou schalt preye, entre in-to þi couche, &amp; schytt þe dore, &amp; pray þy Fader, and þy Fader þat seeþ in hyd schal ȝelde þee þi meede.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.7" type="verse">Soþly ȝe prayenge wele ȝe not speke mychyl, as
<seg id="b.MAT.6.8" type="verse">Þerfore wele ȝe noȝt be lyckenyd to hem; for-why ȝowre heuenly Fader wot what þing is nedeful to ȝow, byfore þat ȝee aske hym.
<seg id="b.MAT.6.9" type="verse">Þerfore ȝee schal preye on þis manere: Oure Fader þat art in heuene, halewed be þi name.
<seg id="b.PHI.1.27" type="verse">Suster , to þe Phylypences he wryteþ in þis wyse, Hafe ȝe worþilyche ȝoure conuersacyoun onlyche after þe gospel of Crist: þat, whanne ich come &amp; seo ȝou oþer absent yhere of ȝou, þat ȝe stondeþ in on spirit &amp; of on soule trafaylynge
<seg id="b.PHI.1.28" type="verse">to-geder to þe feiþ of þe euangelye; &amp; in no þing be ȝe a-gast of ȝoure aduersaryes: þat is to hem an enchesoun of perdycyoun,
<seg id="b.PHI.1.29" type="verse">bote to ous of hele, &amp; þis is of God; for it is y-graunted to ȝou, noȝt þat ȝe onlyche byleue in hym bote
<seg id="b.PHI.1.30" type="verse">þat ȝe suffren also for hym: hauynge þe same fyȝtynge þat ȝe han y-seyn in me, þat ȝe hereþ now of me.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.10" type="verse">þat in þe name of Iesu eferiche kne be y-bowed, of hefnelyche þinges &amp; of erþelyche þinges and of þynges þat beþ of helle,
<seg id="b.PHI.2.11" type="verse">&amp; eferich tonge knowleche þat oure Lord Iesu Crist is in þe blisse of God þe Fader.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.12" type="verse">And so, my dereste breþeren, as ȝe hafeþ herd byfore, ben boxum noȝt onlyche in my presence bote also in myn absence, so wiþ drede &amp; wiþ quakynge worche ȝe ȝoure owene hele.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.13" type="verse">For God is þat worcheþ in ȝou wil &amp; parformynge, for good wil.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.14" type="verse">&amp; alle þinges do ȝe
<seg id="b.PHI.2.15" type="verse">wiþ-outen grucchynges &amp; wiþ-outen doutynges; þat ȝe ben wiþ-outen blame, sympel chyldren of God wiþ-outen reprefe in þe myddel of a schrewed nacyoun &amp; a wykked, among
<seg id="b.PHI.2.16" type="verse">whom ȝe schyneþ as lanternes in þe worlde, holdynge þe word of lyf to my blysse in þe day of Crist; for y ne hafe noȝt y-ronne in veyn, ne y-trauayled in veyn.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.17" type="verse">&amp; ȝif þat ich be offred abofe þe sacrifyce &amp; þe seruyse of ȝoure feiþ, y ioye,
<seg id="b.PHI.2.18" type="verse">&amp; glade to ȝou alle: &amp; ioye ȝe alle also in þe same þing, and ioye to me.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.1" type="verse">And þerfore ȝif þer be any comfortynge in Crist, oþer eny solace of charyte, oþer eny felawschupe of spiryt, oþer
<seg id="b.PHI.2.2" type="verse">ny in-wardnesse of hafynge mercy &amp; reuþe, fulfylle ȝe my ioye, þat ȝe saferen on þing, hauynge on charyte, beynge of
<seg id="b.PHI.2.3" type="verse">on soule, &amp; felynge on þing; no þyng þoroȝ stryfynge, ne þoroȝ veyn glorye, bote in humelnesse deme ȝe eferich man
<seg id="b.PHI.2.4" type="verse">sofereyn to oþer; ne no man byholdynge his owene þinges, bote oþer mennes þinges.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.5" type="verse">And fele ȝe þis þing in ȝou, þat
<seg id="b.PHI.2.6" type="verse">was in Crist Iesu: þe whuche whenne he was efene wiþ God,
<seg id="b.PHI.2.7" type="verse">he ne demed it no rafeyn þat he were euene wiþ God, bote he anentysched hym-selfen, takynge þe forme of a serfaunt,
<seg id="b.PHI.2.8" type="verse">&amp; was y-mad in þe lykenesse of men, &amp; y-founden in habyt as a man; &amp; he humeled hym-selfe, &amp; was y-mad boxum to þe deþ, ȝe, to þe deþ of þe cros.
<seg id="b.PHI.2.9" type="verse">Wherfore God arered hym up, &amp; grauntede hym a name þat is abofen eferich name;
<seg id="b.PHI.3.10" type="verse">feiþ in God: to knowen hym, þe vertu of his arysynge from deþ to lyf, &amp; þe felawschype of his passyones; &amp; ich am
<seg id="b.PHI.3.11" type="verse">y-mad lyche to his deþ, ȝif y mowe in any manere come to þe up-rysynge þat is from deþ to lyf.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.12" type="verse">Noȝt þat ich hafe now vnderfongen oþer be ȝit parfyt: bot y sewe, ȝif þat y mowe in any manere taken hym, in whom ich am take, Iesu Crist .
<seg id="b.PHI.3.13" type="verse">&amp; breþeren, y ne deme noȝt þat ich hafe y-taken hym ȝet: bote on þing þer is, þat y forȝete þilke þinges þat beþ behynde, &amp; to þilke þinges þat beþ byfore y strecche out myselfe,
<seg id="b.PHI.3.14" type="verse">&amp; pursewe to þe mede þat is y-ordeyned of þe clepynge of a-bofen of God in Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.15" type="verse">&amp; alle we þat beþ parfyt, fele we þis same þing, &amp; ȝef ȝe feleþ eny oþer þing, God haþ y-schewed þat þing to ous.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.16" type="verse">Bote naþeles, to þat we beþ y-come, to folewe on þing, and dwelle we stille in on rewle .
<seg id="b.PHI.3.17" type="verse">And breþeren, be ȝe my foleweres, &amp; aspye ȝe hem þat walkeþ so, as ȝe han oure forme.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.18" type="verse">For many men walkeþ, as ich haue seyd ȝow fele syþes, and now wepynge y seye ȝow,
<seg id="b.PHI.3.19" type="verse">enemyes of Cristes cros, whos ende is deþ; &amp; hure God is hure wombe, &amp; þe blisse of hem is confusyoun, þat safereþ erþelyche þynges.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.1" type="verse">To wryte to ȝow it is noȝt hefy to me, bote also nedful for ȝow.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.20" type="verse">Bote oure conuersacyoun is in hefne;
<seg id="b.PHI.3.21" type="verse">þat schal reformen þe body of oure humelnesse, þat is lyche þe body of his clernesse, after his worchynge, þoroȝ whom he may maken alle þinges sogetes to hym-selfen.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.2" type="verse">Y-seo ȝe houndes, y-seo ȝe wykked werkmen, y-seo ȝe circumsisyoun.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.3" type="verse">For we beþ circumsycyoun, þat serfeþ to God in spiryt, &amp; ioyeþ in Iesu Crist, &amp; hafeþ no trust in oure flesch:
<seg id="b.PHI.3.4" type="verse">&amp; ȝif eny man is
<seg id="b.PHI.3.5" type="verse">y-seye trusten in flesch: y my-self was y-circumsyded þe eyȝteþe day , of þe kynde of Israel, &amp; of þe kynrede of Beniamyn, of Hebrees Hebrew; after þe lawe, a Pharyse;
<seg id="b.PHI.3.6" type="verse">aftur þe folewynge of þe lawe, pursewynge Goddes churche; &amp; aftur þe riȝtfulnesse þat is of þe lawe, ich hadde a conuersacyoun wiþ-outen blame.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.7" type="verse">Bote þilke þinges þat weren profytabel &amp; wynnynge to me, for Crist ich hafe y-demed þat þei beþ harmful.
<seg id="b.PHI.3.8" type="verse">for þe gret knowynge of oure Lord Iesu Crist; for whom ich hafe y-mad alle þilke þinges harmful, &amp; ich haue y-demed
<seg id="b.PHI.3.9" type="verse">hem as dryt, þat ich wynne Crist, &amp; þat ich be y-founden in hym, noȝt hafynge my ryȝtfulnesse þat is of þe lawe, bote þilke þat is of þe feiþ of Iesu Crist, þat is a ryȝtfulnesse of
<seg id="b.PHI.4.1" type="verse">And þerfore, my dereste breþeren, my ioye &amp; my corone, stonde ȝe so in oure Lord, my lefeste breþeren.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.4" type="verse">&amp; ioye ȝe in oure Lord efermore: &amp; eftsones y seye, Ioye ȝe.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.5" type="verse">Ȝoure softnesse be y-knowe to alle men. Oure Lord is nyȝ.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.6" type="verse">Be ȝe no þyng bysy; bote in eferiche preyere &amp; bysechynge, in doynge þankynges, ȝoure axynge ben y-knowe to-fore God.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.7" type="verse">And þe pees of God, þat passeþ eferich wytt, kepe ȝoure hertes &amp; ȝoure vnderstondynges in Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.8" type="verse">And breþeren, herafter, what-efer þinges þat beþ trewe, &amp; chaste, oþer ryȝtful, oþer holy, oþer worþi to ben y-lofed, oþer of good loos , whatefer vertu, what-efer preysynge of techynge, þese þinges þenke ȝe.
<seg id="b.PHI.4.9" type="verse">þilke þat ȝe habbeþ y-lerned &amp; vnderfongen &amp; y-herd &amp; y-seyn in me, þese þinges do ȝe, &amp; God of pees schal be wiþ ȝow.
<seg id="b.ROM.1.19" type="verse">Seynt Poule wryteþ to þe Romaynes , &amp; seiþ, Ryȝt as þe vnboxumnesse of on man many men beþ y-maad synful men, so by þe boxumnesse of on man many men beþ y-maad riȝtful men.
<seg id="b.ROM.1.20" type="verse">&amp; þe lawe entred in, þat sinne were in plente ; but þere as sunne was in plente, grace was in more plente:
<seg id="b.ROM.1.21" type="verse">þat, riȝt as sunne regned in-to deþ, so grace schulde regne þorowȝ riȝtfulnesse in-to an euerelastynge lyf, by Iesu Crist oure Lord.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.10" type="verse">For þat he dyed ones, he dyed to sunne: but þat he lyueþ, he lyueþ to God.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.11" type="verse">&amp; so trowe ȝe, þat ȝe ȝowself been dede to sunne &amp; lyuynge to God in oure Lord Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.12" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ne regne þere no sunne in ȝoure dedlyche body,
<seg id="b.ROM.2.13" type="verse">þat ȝe ben boxum to his coueytynges; &amp; ne ȝeue ȝe noȝt ȝoure membris to ben armer of wikkednesse to sunne; but ȝefeþ ȝow-selfen to God as lyuynge men of dede men, &amp; ȝoure membrys armer of riȝtfulnesse to God.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.14" type="verse">For sunne ne schal noȝt haue lordschupe in ȝow her-aftur: for ȝe beþ noȝt vnder lawe, but vnder grace. What þanne?
<seg id="b.ROM.2.15" type="verse">Schulle we don sunne, for we beþ noȝt vnder lawe but vnder grace? God forbede.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.16" type="verse">Wheþer ȝe ne knoweþ noȝt, þat to hym þat ȝe ȝefeþ ȝow-selfen to ben seruauntes, to ben buxum to hym, his seruauntes ȝe beþ to whom ȝe beþ boxum; wheþer it be of sunne to deþ, oþer of boxumnesse to riȝtfulnesse.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.17" type="verse">&amp; I þonke God, þat ȝe habbeþ y-ben seruauntes of sunne, but nowþe ȝe han obeysched of herte in-to þat forme of techynge, þat ȝe
<seg id="b.ROM.2.18" type="verse">beþ now y-take to; &amp; ȝe beþ y-maad fre of sunne &amp; seruauntis of riȝtfulnesse.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.19" type="verse">Y seye þing þat parteyneþ to man for þe infirmite of ȝoure flesche: for riȝt as ȝe han y-ȝefen ȝoure membres for-to serfen to vnclennasse &amp; to wickednesse in-to sunne: so ȝeueþ ȝe nowþe ȝowre membres for-to seruen to riȝtfulnesse in-to holynes.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.1" type="verse">What þanne schulde we seye ? Schulle we ȝet dwelle stille in sunne, þat grace be plenteuous?
<seg id="b.ROM.2.20" type="verse">For whanne ȝe weren seruauntis
<seg id="b.ROM.2.21" type="verse">What fruyt had ȝe þanne in þilke þinges, in þe whuche þinges ȝe beþ aschamed nowþe? for þe ende of hem is deþ.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.22" type="verse">But nowþe ȝe beþ y-maad fre of sunne, and seruauntes to God, &amp; ȝe han ȝoure fruyt holynesse, &amp; þe ende þerof an euerlastynge lyf.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.23" type="verse">For þe mede of sunne is deþ; but þe grace of God is an euerlastynge lyf in Iesu Crist oure Lord.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.2" type="verse">God forbede. For we þat beþ dede to sunne, how schulde we ȝit dwelle stille in sunne?
<seg id="b.ROM.2.3" type="verse">Bryþeren, wheþer ȝe ne knowe noȝt þat
<seg id="b.ROM.2.4" type="verse">For we beþ y-beryed to-gedere wiþ hym þorowȝ baptysme in-to deþ: þat ryȝt as Crist a-ros up from deþ to lyf þorowȝ þe blysse of his Fader, riȝt so walke we in a newe manere of lyfynge.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.5" type="verse">And ȝif we beþ y-plaunted to-geder &amp; i-mad to þe lyknesse of his deþ, we schuleþ ben also to-geder
<seg id="b.ROM.2.6" type="verse">in þe lyknesse of his rysyng aȝeyn from deþ to lyf: knowynge þis þing, þat oure olde man is crucyfyed, þat þe body of sunne be distroyed, þat her-aftur we ne serue noȝt to sunne; for he þat dyed is y-iustified from sunne.
<seg id="b.ROM.2.7" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.ROM.2.8" type="verse">&amp; ȝif we beþ dede wiþ Crist, we byleueþ þat we schulleþ lyuen also wiþ hym;
<seg id="b.ROM.2.9" type="verse">knowynge þat Crist þat aros up from deþ to lyf ne dyeþ noȝt nowþe; ne deþ schal neuere her-after haue lordschupe up-on hym.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.10" type="verse">lyfed aȝeyn, bote ich was ded; &amp; so þe comaundement, þat
<seg id="b.ROM.3.11" type="verse">was y-founde to lyf, it was to þe deþ: for in takynge an
<seg id="b.ROM.3.12" type="verse">&amp; so ȝit þe lawe is holy, &amp; þe comaundement holy, &amp; riȝtful, &amp; good.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.13" type="verse">What þanne, þat þing þat was good to me it was y-maad deþ? God forbede. But sunne, þat it seme snne, þor good wroȝte deþ to me: þat be made aboe maner þoroȝ þe comaundement.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.14" type="verse">&amp; we knoweþ þat þe lawe is spyrytual : &amp; ich fleschlyche sold vndur sunne.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.15" type="verse">For þat þing þat ich worche, y ne vnderstonde noȝt: for þat þing þat is good &amp; þat ich haue wille to , þat y ne do noȝt; bote þat þing þat is yfel &amp; þat ich haue y-hated, þat ich do.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.16" type="verse">And ȝif ich do þat þing þat y wole noȝt do, ich assente to þe lawe þat he is good.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.17" type="verse">Bote now y ne worche it noȝt, bote þe sunne þat dwelleþ in me.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.18" type="verse">For I wot wel þat it dwelleþ noȝt in me, þat is to seye, in my flesche, þat þing þat is good: &amp; so wille falleþ to me, bote y ne fynde noȝt to parforme þat þyng þat is good.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.19" type="verse">For þat good þat ich wolde, y ne do noȝt: bote þat efel þat y nolde noȝt , þat y do.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.1" type="verse">Wheþer ȝe ne knoweþ noȝt, breþeren, for to þilke þat knoweþ þe lawe y speke, for as longe as a man lyfeþ þe lawe haþ lordschupe on hym.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.20" type="verse">&amp; ȝif y do þat þing þat y nole noȝt, y ne worche noȝt þat , bote þe sunne þat dwelleþ in me.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.21" type="verse">&amp; þerfore y fynde a lawe to me þat wol do good, for efyl falleþ to me .
<seg id="b.ROM.3.22" type="verse">&amp; ich haue delyt to þe lawe of
<seg id="b.ROM.3.23" type="verse">good aftur myn in-ward man: bote y seo an oþer lawe in my membres, þat aȝeynstondeþ þe lawe of my þoȝt, &amp; makeþ me y-take in þe lawe of sunne þat is in my membres.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.24" type="verse">&amp; who schal delyuere me þat am an vncely man from þe body of þis deþ? Þe grace of God þoroȝ oure Lord Iesu Crist.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.25" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ich my-selfe serfe in my þouȝt to þe lawe of God; &amp; in my flesche to þe lawe of sunne.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.2" type="verse">For a womman þat is vnder here housbonde whyles þat hure housbonde lyfeþ heo is y-bounde to þe lawe; but ȝif hure housbonde be deed, he is delyuered from þe lawe of hure housbonde.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.3" type="verse">Þanne, whyles hure housbonde lyfeþ, he schal be cleped a spousebrekere ȝif he be wiþ an oþer man: bote ȝif hure housbonde be ded, heo is delyfered from þe lawe of hure housbonde, þat heo ne be noȝt y-cleped a spousebrekere, þauȝ heo be wiþ an oþer man.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.4" type="verse">&amp; so, breþeren, ȝe beþ y-maad ded to þe lawe by þe body of Crist; þat ȝe ben of anoþer þat ros up from deþ to lyfe, þat ȝe schulden make fruyt to God.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.5" type="verse">For whan we weren in þe flesch, þe passyones of sunnes, þat weren þoroȝ þe lawe, wroȝten in oure membres þat we schulden make oure fruyt to .
<seg id="b.ROM.3.6" type="verse">Bote we beþ now vnbounden from þe lawe of deþ in whom we weren y-holden, so þat we serfen in þe neweschupe of þe spyryt, &amp; noȝt in þe oldenesse of þe letter.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.7" type="verse">What schulle we seye þanne? þe lawe is sunne? God forbede. But y knewe no sunne bote þoroȝ þe lawe: for y knew noȝt coueytyse, bote for as muche
<seg id="b.ROM.3.8" type="verse">as þe lawe sayde, Þou ne schalt not coueyte: &amp; so in takynge an occasyon by þe comaundement of þe lawe, sunne haþ y-wroȝt in me eferiche couetyse: for wiþ-outen lawe sunne was ded.
<seg id="b.ROM.3.9" type="verse">&amp; ych lefed sumtyme wiþ-outen lawe: bote whanne þat þe comaundement of þe lawe was y-come, sunne
<seg id="b.ROM.4.10" type="verse">&amp; ȝif þat Crist is in ȝow, þanne is þe body deed for sunne; but þe spiryt lyueþ for iustificacyoun.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.11" type="verse">And ȝif þe Spiryte of hym þat a-rered up Iesu Crist from deþ to lyfe dwelle in ȝow, he þat arered up Iesu Crist from deþ to lyfe schal quykene ȝoure dedlyche bodyes for his Spiryt þat dwelleþ in ȝow.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.12" type="verse">&amp; þerfore, breþeren, we beþ dettoures, noȝt to þe flesch, þat we lyfen aftur þe flesch.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.13" type="verse">For ȝif ȝe lyfeþ aftur þe flesch ȝe schuleþ deyȝen; bote ȝef ȝe sleþ þe werkes of þe flesch þorowȝ þe spiryt, ȝe schuleþ lyfen.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.14" type="verse">For whoeuere beþ y-maad þorowȝ þe spiryt of God, þei beþ Godes chyldren.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.15" type="verse">For ȝe ne hafeþ noȝt vnderfongen þe spiryt of þraldom eftsones in drede; bote ȝe haueþ vnderfongen þe spirit of þe bygetynge of children, in þe whuche spirit we crieþ to God oure Fadur.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.16" type="verse">For þat Spirit ȝefeþ witnesse to
<seg id="b.ROM.4.17" type="verse">oure spirit, þat we beþ Godes children: and ȝef we beþ children &amp; eyres, we beþ eyres of God, &amp; eyres wiþ Crist; ȝif it is so þat we suffreþ to-gedere, þat we ben y-gloryfyed to-gydere.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.18" type="verse">&amp; I trowe þat þe suffrynges of þis tyme ne beþ noȝt worþi to þe blisse þat schal be schewed in ous her-aftur.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.19" type="verse">For þe abydynge of creature abydeþ þe schewenge of Goddis children.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.1" type="verse">And þerfore þer ne is no þing of dampnacyon to þese þat beþ in Iesu Crist, þat walkeþ noȝt after þe flesche.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.20" type="verse">For eferich creature is soget to vanyte, noȝt wilfullyche, bote for hym þat haþ y-maad hure soget in hope:
<seg id="b.ROM.4.21" type="verse">For þat creature schal be delifered from þe þraldom of corrupcyoun in-to þe fredom of þe blisse of Godes chyldren.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.22" type="verse">&amp; we knoweþ þat eferech creature makeþ waymentacyoun ȝit nowþe.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.23" type="verse">Noȝt onlyche heo, bote we also, þat habbeþ þe furstefruytes of þe Spirit, we makeþ waymentacioun wiþ-ynne ous-self, abydynge þe bygetynge of Godes children, &amp; þe for-buggynge of oure body.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.24" type="verse">&amp; þorow hope we beþ y-safed: For hope þat is y-seye ne is non hope: for þat þing þat a man seþ he ne hopeþ noȝt.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.25" type="verse">&amp; ȝif we hope þing þat we se noȝt, þoroȝ pacyence we abydeþ þat þyng.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.26" type="verse">&amp; þe Spirit also helpeþ oure infirmyte: for we ne koneþ noȝt preyen as it byhofeþ; but þe Spiryt preyeþ for ous þoroȝ sykynges þat
<seg id="b.ROM.4.27" type="verse">mowe noȝt ben y-told; and he þat sercheþ hertes knoweþ what þe Spirit desyreþ, þat þoroȝ God preyeþ for seyntes.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.28" type="verse">&amp; we knoweþ þat to þilke þat lofeþ God alle þinges worcheþ to-gedere in-to good, to þese men þat beþ aftur hure purpos y-cleped holy men.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.29" type="verse">For þilke he knew by-fore &amp; ordeyned byfore to ben y-confermed to þe ymage of his Sone, þat he be
<seg id="b.ROM.4.2" type="verse">For þe
<seg id="b.ROM.4.30" type="verse">þe furste bygete sone in many breþeren: &amp; þilke þat he ordeyned byfore, þilke he haþ y-cleped: &amp; þilke þat he haþ y-cleped, þilke he haþ y-iustyfyed : &amp; þilke þat he haþ y-iustifyed, þilke he haþ y-magnyfyed.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.31" type="verse">What schulde we seye þanne ? Ȝif God is wiþ ous, who is aȝeyns ous?
<seg id="b.ROM.4.32" type="verse">&amp; he ne spared noȝt his owne Sone, bote ȝef hym for alle ous, &amp; how ne he haþ noȝt y-ȝeuen ous alle þinges wiþ hym?
<seg id="b.ROM.4.33" type="verse">&amp; who schal accusen aȝeyn hem þat beþ y-chosen of God? God þat iustifyeþ ; who is he þat schal demen?
<seg id="b.ROM.4.34" type="verse">Iesu Crist þat dyed, &amp; ros al-so from deþ to lyfe, &amp; is on þe riȝtsyde of God, &amp; preyȝeþ also for ous.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.35" type="verse">Who schal þanne departen ous from þe charite of Crist? tribulacyoun, oþer angwysch, oþer hunger, oþer persecucyoun, oþer nakedschep, oþer pereyle, oþer swerd?
<seg id="b.ROM.4.36" type="verse">As it is wryten, For þe we beþ y-slawe al day; &amp; me weneþ þat we ben scheep of sleynge.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.37" type="verse">But in alle þese þinges we ofercomeþ for hym þat lofed ous.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.38" type="verse">&amp; ich am certeyn, þat nowþer deþ, ne lyf, ne angeles, ne princypaltees, ne vertues, ne þinges þat beþ nowþe, ne þinges þat schulleþ ben heraftur,
<seg id="b.ROM.4.3" type="verse">For þat þat was inpossyble to þe lawe, in þe whuche þing man was y-maad sek þoroȝ þe flesche, God sende his Sone in þe lykenesse of þe flesche of sunne, &amp;
<seg id="b.ROM.4.4" type="verse">of sunne he dampned sunne in flesch: þat þe iustifyenge of þe lawe were fulfulled in ous, þat walkeþ noȝt aftur þe flesch, bote aftur þe spiryt.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.5" type="verse">For þilke þat beþ aftur þe flesch safereþ þilke þinges þat beþ of þe flesch; but þilke þat beþ
<seg id="b.ROM.4.6" type="verse">aftur þe spiryt feleþ þilke þinges þat beþ of þe spiryt. For þe wisdom of þe flesch is deþ; bote þe wysdom of þe spiryt is lyf
<seg id="b.ROM.4.7" type="verse">&amp; pes: for þe wysdom of þe flesch is enemye to God: for þe lawe of God heo ne is noȝt soget, ne may not ben soget: &amp; þilke þat beþ in þe flesch ne mowe not plese God.
<seg id="b.ROM.4.8" type="verse">,
<seg id="b.ROM.4.9" type="verse">&amp; ȝe ne beþ noȝt in þe flesch bote in þe spiryt, ȝif þat þe Spiryt of God dwelleþ in ȝow. &amp; who þat haþ noȝt þe spiryt of Crist, he ne is noȝt of hym.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.10" type="verse">&amp; lofe ȝe to-geder, &amp; hafe ȝe charite of breþerhede; &amp; go ȝe byfore worschupynge eferichone
<seg id="b.ROM.5.11" type="verse">oþer; noȝt slowe in bysynesse; feruent in spirit; serfynge
<seg id="b.ROM.5.12" type="verse">oure Lord; ioyenge in hope; suffrynge in tribulacyoun;
<seg id="b.ROM.5.13" type="verse">bysy to preyere; comunynge to þe nedynesse of holy men; &amp; folewe ȝe herborewynge.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.14" type="verse">Blesse ȝe to þilke þat purseweþ ȝow; blesse ȝe, &amp; ne curse ȝe noȝt .
<seg id="b.ROM.5.15" type="verse">Ioye ȝe wiþ hem þat ioyeþ; &amp; wepe ȝe wiþ hem þat wepeþ.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.16" type="verse">&amp; fele ȝe to-gedere in-to þe same þinge, noȝt saferynge hyȝe þinges, but assentynge to humel þinges. &amp; ne wilne ȝe noȝt to ben wyse men tofore
<seg id="b.ROM.5.17" type="verse">ȝow-self; noȝt ȝeldynge to eny man efel for efel, but bysye ȝe to don goode þinges noȝt onlyche to-fore God, but
<seg id="b.ROM.5.19" type="verse">also to-foren alle men; noȝt defendynge ȝow-selfe, bote ȝefe ȝe place to wraþþe: for it is y-wryten, God saiþ , to me þe
<seg id="b.ROM.5.1" type="verse">I preyȝe ȝow, breþeren, by þe mercy of God, þat ȝee ȝefen ȝoure bodyes a sacrifice, lyfynge &amp; holy, &amp; plesynge to God, &amp; ȝoure seruyse resonabel.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.20" type="verse">&amp; ȝif þyn enemy be an-hungred, fede hym; &amp; ȝif he be a-þrust , ȝef hym drynke: For doynge þese þinges þou schalt gedere to-geder coles of fuyr up-on his hed.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.21" type="verse">Ne be þou ofercome of efel, bote in goode ofercome þou efel.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.2" type="verse">&amp; ne be ȝe noȝt conformed to þis world: bote be ȝe y-schaped a-ȝeyn in þe worschup of ȝowre wyt, þat ȝe knowen whuche be þe wille of God, þat is good &amp; wel plesynge &amp; parfite.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.3" type="verse">&amp; I seye, þoroȝ þe grace of God þat is y-ȝefe me, to alle þilke þat beþ among ȝow, þat ȝe ne safereþ no more þan it byhofeþ ȝow to saferen; bote þat ȝe saferen to sobernesse, &amp; eferych man as God haþ departed to hym þe mesure of bylefe.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.4" type="verse">For ryȝt as we han in on body many membres, &amp; ȝet alle þe membres ne habbeþ noȝt on doynge: riȝt so we beþ on body in Crist , &amp; eferichone of ous membres of oþer.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.6" type="verse">&amp; we þat han dyuerse ȝiftes after þe grace þat is y-ȝeue to ous, as prophecye aftur þe resoun of þe feiþ;
<seg id="b.ROM.5.7" type="verse">oþer seruyse in serfynge; oþer he þat techeþ, in techynge;
<seg id="b.ROM.5.8" type="verse">he þat warneþ, in warnynge; he þat ȝeldeþ, in sympelnesse; he þat is byfore, in bysynesse; he þat a-reweþ an oþer, in gladnesse.
<seg id="b.ROM.5.9" type="verse">B þer lofe wiþowten feynynge. &amp; hate ȝe efel, &amp; draweþ ȝow to goode.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.10" type="verse">Þe loue of a mannes nexte neyȝebore ne worcheþ non euel: an þerfore þe fulnesse of þe lawe is loue.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.11" type="verse">&amp; knowe ȝe þis tyme, for it is now tyme to rysen up from sleep: for oure hele is ner now þan we wenden þat it were.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.12" type="verse">Þe nyȝt is passed, &amp; þe day wole neyȝlyche: &amp; þerfore þrowe we a-wey werkes of derkenesse , &amp; be we cloþed
<seg id="b.ROM.6.13" type="verse">&amp; walke we honestlyche as in day-tyme, noȝt in etynge out of mesure, ne in dronkenesse, ne in kouchynges abedde, ne in vnclannesse, ne in stryuynge, ne in hatynge.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.14" type="verse">Bote be ȝe y-cloþed wiþ oure Lord Iesu . Þus, suster, seynt Poule wryteþ to þe Romaynes , how þei schuleþ lyuen þat byleueþ in Crist.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.1" type="verse">Euerich soule be soget to poweres þat beþ hyȝere þan heo: for þer ne is no power bote of God; &amp; þilke þinges þat beþ, of God þei beþ y-ordeyned.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.2" type="verse">And þerfore who þat a-ȝeynstondeþ geteþ dampnacyoun to hemselfen.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.3" type="verse">For princes ne beþ noȝt to drede of goode werkes, bote of efel werkes. &amp; ȝif þou wolt noȝt drede a power, do good, &amp; þou schalt haue preysynge þer-of.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.4" type="verse">For he is Godes serfaunt to þe in good. &amp; ȝif þou dost efel, þan drede þou: for wiþ-outen enchesoun he ne bereþ noȝt his swerd: for he is Goddes serfaunt, wracchful in wraþþe to þilke þat doþ efel.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.5" type="verse">&amp; þerfore algates be ȝe sogettes, noȝt onlyche for wraþþe, bote also for conciense.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.6" type="verse">For þerfore ȝe ȝeueþ trybut; for þei beþ Goddes serfauntes, serfynge for þis þing.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.7" type="verse">&amp; þerfore ȝelde ȝe to alle men ȝoure dettes: to hym þat ȝe schuleþ trybut, trybut; to hym þat ȝe schuleþ drede, dred; &amp; to hym þat ȝe oweþ worschup, worschup .
<seg id="b.ROM.6.8" type="verse">Ne owe ȝe no þing to no man, bote þat ȝe lofen to-gedere: for he þat lofeþ his neyȝebore fulfulleþ þe lawe.
<seg id="b.ROM.6.9" type="verse">For, Þou ne schalt noȝt breke spoushod, Þou ne schat noȝt sleen, Þou ne schalt noȝt stele, Þou ne schalt seye no fals wyttnesse, Þou ne schalt noȝt coueyte þi neyȝebores good, &amp; ȝif þer be eny oþer comaundement, it is y-vnderstonde in þis word, Þou schalt loue þi nexte neyȝebore as þi-selfe.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.10" type="verse">For þer beþ manye in-obedyent, veyn spekeres &amp;
<seg id="b.TIT.1.11" type="verse">gyloures, &amp; most of þilke þat beþ of circumcysyoun, whom byhofeþ to ben vndernomyn; for þei turneþ up alle houses, techynge þat ne byhofeþ noȝt to ben y-tauȝt, for enchesoun of foul wynnynge.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.12" type="verse">And on of hure owne prophetes seyde, Men of Crete beþ efermore lyeres, lether bestes, of slow
<seg id="b.TIT.1.13" type="verse">&amp; þerfore blame hem
<seg id="b.TIT.1.14" type="verse">harde, þat þei ben hol in feiþ, noȝt takynge kepe to þe fables of Iewes, ne to mennes comaundementes þat turneþ hem a-wey from trewþe.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.15" type="verse">And to clene men alle þinges beþ clene: bote to men þat beþ defouled &amp; mysbylefed þer ne is no þing clene; for hure þoȝt and hure conscyence beþ defouled.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.16" type="verse">&amp; þei knowlecheþ þat þei knoweþ God; bote in hure dedys þei forsakeþ hym, for þei beþ abhomynabel, &amp; vnbylefed, &amp; to eferich good werk.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.5" type="verse">wryteþ in þis wyse, For þis enchesoun y lafte þe at Crete, for þou schuldest amenden þilke þinges þat lakkeþ, &amp; þat þou
<seg id="b.TIT.1.6" type="verse">schuldest ordeyne prestes by cytees, as ich ordeyned þe; and who þat is wiþ-outen blame, a man of on wyf, þat haþ feiþful children, noȝt in-to accusacyoun, ne soget to leccherye.
<seg id="b.TIT.1.7" type="verse">For it byhofeþ þat a byschop be wiþ-outen blame, as despensatour of God; noȝt proud, ne wraþþeful, ne dronkelew, ne a smyter,
<seg id="b.TIT.1.8" type="verse">ne coueytous of foul wynnynge; bote an ospyteler &amp; benygne,
<seg id="b.TIT.1.9" type="verse">sober, ryȝtful &amp; holy, contynent; &amp; cleppynge a feiþful &amp; a trewe word þat is aftur good doctryne, þat he be myȝty to warne men in hol techynge, &amp; vndernymen þilke þat aȝeynseyen.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.10" type="verse">lordes, plesynge in alle þinges &amp; noȝt aȝeyn-seyenge; ne bygylynge, bote in alle þinges schewynge a good feiþ; þat þei worschupen in alle þinges þe doctrine of oure God &amp; oure Safyour.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.11" type="verse">For þe grace of God oure Safyour haþ appered
<seg id="b.TIT.2.12" type="verse">to alle men, techynge ous þat we forsaken wykkednesse &amp; wordlyche desyres, &amp; þat soberlyche &amp; ryȝtfullyche &amp;
<seg id="b.TIT.2.13" type="verse">mukelyche we lyfen in þis worlde, abydynge þe blissed hope &amp; þe comynge of þe blysse of þe grete God &amp; oure Safyour
<seg id="b.TIT.2.14" type="verse">Iesu Crist; þat ȝef hym-selfen for ous to fore-byȝenge ous of eferich wykkednesse, &amp; to maken ous a clene pepel &amp; an acceptabel to hym-selfe &amp; a folewere of goode werkes.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.15" type="verse">Þese þinges spek þow &amp; warne &amp; vndernyme wiþ eferich power of comaundynge. No man despyse þe.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.1" type="verse">Bote speke þou hol doctryne þat bysemeþ þe to speke:
<seg id="b.TIT.2.2" type="verse">þat olde men ben sober and chaste, redy &amp; wys, hol in feiþ,
<seg id="b.TIT.2.3" type="verse">in lofe, &amp; in pacyence: olde wymmen also ben in an holy habyt, noȝt schidesteres, noȝt serfynge to muche wyn ,
<seg id="b.TIT.2.4" type="verse">spekynge &amp; seyenge wel, þat þei techen wysdom: ȝonge wymmen, þat þei lofen hure housbondes &amp; hure chyldren
<seg id="b.TIT.2.5" type="verse">also, &amp; þat þei ben redy &amp; wys, chast &amp; sober, hafynge of þe houshold, benyngne, &amp; sogetys to hure housbondes, þat þe word of God ne be noȝt y-blasphemed.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.6" type="verse">Warne þou also
<seg id="b.TIT.2.7" type="verse">ȝonge men þat þei ben sober: &amp; in alle þinges ȝef þi-selfen an ensampel of goode werkes, in techynge, in holnesse, in
<seg id="b.TIT.2.8" type="verse">chastyte, in sadnesse þi word be hol &amp; wiþouten reprefe; þat he þat is aduersary be adrad, &amp; fynde non yfel to seyn of ous.
<seg id="b.TIT.2.9" type="verse">Also þat serfauntes ben in alle þinges sogetes to hure
<seg id="b.TIT.3.10" type="verse">A man þat is an heretyk aftur þe furste &amp; þe secounde correccyoun schenye hym;
<seg id="b.TIT.3.11" type="verse">knowynge þat such a man is y-turned upso-doun, &amp; he agulteþ whan he is y-dampned þorowȝ his owne dom.
<seg id="b.TIT.3.1" type="verse">And warne hem to be sogetes to princys, &amp; to potestatys, to ben
<seg id="b.TIT.3.2" type="verse">werk, to blaspheme no man, ne ben none stryferes, bote softe, schewynge eferich mansuetude to alle men.
<seg id="b.TIT.3.3" type="verse">And we weren ous-self sumtyme vnwyse, vnbylefed, errynge, &amp; serfynge to oure desyres &amp; to dyuerse lustes, &amp; in malyce and in enuye lyfynge, y-hated of oþer men, &amp; hatynge to-gedere.
<seg id="b.TIT.3.4" type="verse">Bote when þe benygnyte &amp; þe humanyte appered of God
<seg id="b.TIT.3.5" type="verse">oure Safyour, noȝt of þe werkes of ryȝtfulnesse, þat we hafeþ y-don, bote þoroȝ his owne mercy he safed ous, by waschynge
<seg id="b.TIT.3.6" type="verse">of a bygetynge aȝeyn &amp; renewynge of þe Holy Gost, whom he haþ y-sched in ous plenteuouslyche, by Iesu Crist oure
<seg id="b.TIT.3.7" type="verse">Safyour; þat we ben y-iustyfyed þoroȝ his grace &amp; ben eyrys þoroȝ hope of an eferlastynge lyf.
<seg id="b.TIT.3.8" type="verse">A trew word, &amp; of þese þinges ich wole conferme þe, þat by goode werkes men chargen to ben beforen oþer, þilke þat bylefeþ to God. For
<seg id="b.TIT.3.9" type="verse">þese þinges beþ goode &amp; profytabel to men: bote schenye þou questyones of foly, and genologyes, and stryfes of þe lawe; for þei beþ vnprofytabel and veyn.
